<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 5thLd-Writethru   03-15 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0881,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Launch Grenades Around Presidential Palace, Wounding Seven</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with rebels catapulting homemade
bombs. Pick up 6th pvs, `Earlier Wednesday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas fired
rocket-propelled grenades at the presidential palace and an adjacent
military garrison Wednesday, wounding a palace guard and six
civilians in the neighborhood, officials said.
   Leftist rebels also attacked a provincial capital and vowed to
kill election workers and mayors, trying to disrupt Sunday's
presidential election and stepping up the pace of the civil war.
   The rebels also vowed to destroy vehicles defying its traffic ban
scheduled to begin midnight Wednesday.
   Col. Ricardo Casanova, commander of El Zapote garrison next to
the palace, said several of the grenades landed in the neighborhood
near the palace, which houses President Jose Napoleon Duarte's
office. Duarte was not at the scene.
   Witnesses said a grenade apparently hit one of the patios of the
block-wide presidential palace. Casanova said the rebels also
launched homemade bombs with catapults.
   Earlier Wednesday, authorities said two bombs exploded outside
the garrison, slightly injuring a woman passer-by but causing no
damage.
   Shortly after the attack, Radio Venceremos, the radio station of
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, said the attack was
launched by its ``urban commandos.''
   Casanova said some of the shrapnel was found inside the walls of
the palace. Six civilians were injured by other grenades that fell
in the adjoining neighborhood.
   Casanova said the grenades also toppled two electricity poles.
   Also Wednesday, gunmen killed Francisco Peccorini, 60, a
well-known conservative politicial theoretician, as he traveled in a
car with his bodyguards through the capital's downtown commercial
section. The killers fled, their identity and motives unknown.
   The front, the umbrella guerrilla organization, made clear it was
trying to intensify El Salvador's nervousness about the upcoming
nationwide election.
   It issued an implicit death threat against election workers,
reiterated that it will enforce its call for an election boycott
with the transit ban and stepped up attacks on military and civilian
targets.
   The military is preparing to provide armed escorts to vehicles
carrying voters to the polls.
   The election presents this small Central American nation, which
has a long history of coups and military rule, with its first chance
to vote out an elected civilian government.
   But Duarte has said he fears people will be afraid to vote.
   The widely acknowledged front-runner in the presidential race is
Alfredo Cristiani, nominee of the rightist Republican Nationalist
Alliance, or Arena.
   Duarte's Christian Democrats are fielding Fidel Chavez Mena,
ranked in the polls as the No. 2 contender.
   A leftist alliance, the Democratic Convergence, is the third
major force. Its candidate, Guillermo Ungo, returned from exile to
represent the left in its the elections.
   Salvadorans approached election day with uncertainty, unsure if a
clear winner would emerge and braced for an outbreak of fighting the
rebels have promised.
   More than half the people questioned in a poll released Wednesday
by the respected Central American University either refused to say
for whom they would vote, said they hadn't decided or said they
weren't voting.
   Most of the 70,000 people who have died in the nine-year civil
war were civilians.
   Most civilian deaths are attributed to security forces and
right-wing death squads, but the leftist insurgents also have
extracted their toll.
   ``We are aware that there is going to be an increase in the
violence nationwide,'' Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, armed forces chief of
staff, said as he inspected the aftermath of a fierce battle in
Chalatenango on Wednesday.
   He said a rebel force of about 200 attacked the provincial
capital about 45 miles north of San Salvador.
   The military said 18 rebels died in eight hours of fighting that
raged into the pre-dawn hours. Two soldiers were killed and four
injured.
   Rebel radio said the military suffered 13 casualties, without
giving a breakdown of dead and wounded.
   Ponce said three guerrillas also were killed in an attack on a
government warehouse near Chalatenango.
   The guerrillas' campaign has left half of El Salvador's cities
and town without mayors. Rebels killed nine mayors and 135 resigned.
   The rebels told election workers, as they had told the mayors, to
resign or become targets.
   ``We remind you that the FMLN is everywhere,'' the rebels said
Wednesday on clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   The rebels crippled vital services with attacks on telephone and
electrical installation and on Tuesday bombed filling stations.
   Tens of thousands of leftists, suspected leftists and other
presumed government opponents have been killed in El Salvador during
this decade. The United States and international organizations have
described the killings as massive human rights abuses by the
military and far-right death squads.
   Most observers say the big question is whether there will be a
runoff between Arena and the Christian Democrats. Anything over 50
percent is a first-round victory.
</TEXT>
