<FIRST>r a PM-People-Reagan     03-15 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Reagan,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Waives Appearance Fee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan has waived his fee
for appearing at a conference here, but officials said he wasn't
influenced by the fact that more than three quarters of the tickets
remain unsold.
   Reagan is scheduled to appear Monday at Arizona State University
as part of an ``Insuring Tomorrow'' leadership conference. His
speaking fee wasn't disclosed when conference organizers arranged
for his appearance. The former president has signed a
$50,000-a-speech lecture contract.
   Neil Giuliano of the Alumni Association said Reagan waived his
honorarium Monday during negotiations between school officials and
the Washington Speaker's Bureau.
   ``I believe we put forth a very strong case that this is the kind
of program that is important for him to come to,'' Giuliano said.
   Only 2,200 of 10,000 tickets for the appearance at the school's
Activity Center had been sold. Ticket prices ranged from $10-$25.
   Giuliano insisted the slow ticket sales were not a factor in the
decision. People who have bought tickets will receive refunds, he
said.
   Other conference speakers were to include Rep. Pat Schroeder,
D-Colo., and David Gergen, editor of U.S. News &amp; World Report.
</TEXT>
