<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Beauty     03-15 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Beauty,0240</SECOND>
<UNK>Hairdresser Wins First Beauty Contest In Post-War Saigon</UNK>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old hairdresser has won the
first beauty contest in Saigon since Communist forces overran the
capital of the U.S.-backed South Vietnam government in 1975,
Vietnamese media said.
   Do Thi Kieu Khanh beat out 216 other women ranging in age from 16
to 25 in the contest for the title of ``Miss Ao Dai 1989,'' the
official Vietnam News Agency said in a report seen in Bangkok today.
   Ao Dai is the long traditional Vietnamese dress. It has been
infrequently seen on Vietnam's streets since the war ended.
   The runners-up were Duong Nu Minh Tam, a 19-year-old high school
student, and Tran Thu Nga, a 16-year-old student at the city's
choreography school.
   ``In the competition, the contestants appeared before the
audience in Ao Dai, bathsuits and in clothes chosen by themselves,''
the report said. ``Besides, they had to answer some questions on
general knowledge.''
   The contest in Saigon, now called Ho Chi Minh City after the
independence leader, was jointly sponsored by the Women's Union and
The Women Weekly publication, the report said. It said the contest
was held recently.
   The nation's first beauty contest since the war was held last
November in the stubbornly staid capital of Hanoi. The strictures on
society, economy and politics have been relaxed under the
two-year-old rule of pragmatic Communist Party chief Nguyen Van Linh.
</TEXT>
