<FIRST>r a AM-CountryAwards     03-15 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Country Awards,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nashville's WSIX Best in Country Radio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nashville, Tenn., radio station WSIX is the
nation's best in country music and Southern California's Crazy Horse
Steak House &amp; Saloon is the top nightclub, the Academy of Country
Music said in announcing awards Tuesday.
   There was a tie for disc jockey of the year between Jon Conlon of
WGKX radio in Memphis, Tenn., and Dandalion of WRKZ in Hershey, Pa.
Dandalion is the first female ever to win the honor.
   It was the third consecutive country nightclub of the year honor
for the Crazy Horse, an Orange County honkytonk within the Santa Ana
city limits 30 miles south of Los Angeles.
   The winners announced Tuesday will get their ``hat'' trophies
April 10 during the 24th Annual Academy of Country Music Awards
ceremony at the Walt Disney Studios in Burbank. The show will be a
two-hour special on NBC-TV.
   Balloting is currently under way for entertainment awards.
   K.T. Oslin, who emerged as 1988's robust queen of down-home music
with ``Eighties Ladies,'' led with five nominations, including best
record for ``I'll Always Come Back.''
   The nominees included eight who got three nominations apiece,
including such venerable performers as Reba McEntire, Randy Travis
and Hank Williams Jr.
   The winners are decided by ballots cast by the academy's 2,000
winners.
</TEXT>
