<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     03-15 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Retrieves Tuesday Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC seems to have successfully plugged the hole
that ``Moonlighting'' left in its Tuesday schedule.
   Last week, ``Roseanne'' took the top spot in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
ratings and was followed in the top 10 by the new ``Anything But
Love'' and the newly moved ``The Wonder Years.''
   If NBC's Thursday lineup slid a bit, its Monday movie had the
highest Monday movie rating since ``The Burning Bed'' in 1984.
``Those She Left Behind,'' the story of a husband (Gary Cole) whose
wife dies, leaving him to care for a newborn, ranked third last week.
   NBC won the week, its 38th straight victory, tying its record for
longest winning streak.
   For the week, NBC had an average, prime-time rating of 16.0 to
ABC's 12.3 and CBS' 12.1. NBC leads in the season-to-date averages
with a 16.1, followed by ABC's 12.8 and CBS' 12.6.
   ``Anything But Love,'' a half-hour comedy about '80s romance
starring Jamie Lee Curtis and Richard Lewis, was this season's
highest-rated premiere since ``Roseanne.''
   ``Roseanne'' had once before edged ``The Cosby Show'' for first
place _ ``Cosby'' came in second _ but that was a repeat. Last week,
each show attracted a 40 share, but ``Roseanne'' had a rating of
27.7 to ``Cosby's'' 25.3. NBC said ``Cosby'' was affected by
basketball playoffs carried on some independent stations Thursday
night. It was the highest-rated ``Roseanne'' episode yet.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The top-10 shows of the week were: ``Roseanne'' ABC, ``The Cosby
Show'' NBC, ``Those She Left Behind'' NBC, ``60 Minutes'' CBS,
``Who's the Boss?'' ABC, ``A Different World'' NBC, ``Anything But
Love'' ABC, ``The Wonder Years'' ABC, ``Cheers'' NBC and ``Murder,
She Wrote'' CBS.
   Fox, which has done well with the reality-based crime show
``America's Most Wanted'' on Sunday, seems to have successfully
added ``COPS'' on Saturday. The hour-long premiere had a rating of
7.5 and a 13 share.
   In news, ``The CBS Evening News'' remained in first place with a
rating of 11.5 and a 21 share. ``ABC World News Tonight'' had an
11.2 and a 20. ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 10.2 and 19.
</TEXT>
