<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Misery Bjt   03-15 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Misery, Bjt,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garbage Gleaners See Little Promise in Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOYAPANGO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilda Barahona steps across a
mountain of garbage and contends with vultures, dogs and pigs for
edible or saleable refuse from homes better than her own.
   She won't bother to vote on Sunday, when this small Central
American nation wracked by civil war chooses a new president.
   ``One wants to believe that changing the government could improve
things. But one sees that they stay the same. The poor remain poor
and disdained,'' she says.
   More than 200 men, women and children _ toddlers to the aged and
infirm _ scavenge through the Soyapango dump, five miles east of San
Salvador, every day beneath a searing tropical sun and despite an
intense stench.
   Dump trucks and bulldozers, their drivers' faces covered against
the smell with kerchiefs or surgical masks, traverse the two-acre
pile.
   Of 15 voting-age people interviewed, five said they planned to
cast a ballot Sunday _ most because it was a ``duty of
citizenship.'' Voting is legally required here, although there is no
real sanction for not voting.
   Seven parties are contesting the election, the second
presidential vote since 1982, when the country began a rough journey
toward representative constitutional rule.
   Before that, this nation of 5.5 million had been governed
throughout its modern history by an alliance of landed oligarchs and
the armed forces.
   This year, for the first time, Salvadoran voters have a chance to
replace the party in power with a party that has a completely
different outlook.
   The incumbent Christian Democrats are trailing the opposition
rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, with the leftist
Democratic Convergence running third.
   Arena's economic philosphy revolves around the marketplace and
private enterprise. The party says it will institute ``capitalism
for the masses.'' Although it is hard to see how denizens of the
dump would accumulate capital, the only one who would express a
preference said he was voting for Arena.
   ``We're not here because we like this work,'' said Rene Antonio
Vasquez, who will not vote. ``We're here out of necessity. It's the
only option we have. We have to feed our kids.''
   The 19-year-old father of two has worked as a construction
laborer, but such employment is sporadic. He has spent most of the
past 12 years scrounging through the Soyapango dump. For nine of
those years, the nation has been in a civil war between
U.S.-supported government forces and the leftist Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front.
   Unemployment nationwide is estimated at near 40 percent. Over
half the population is illiterate. Fewer than a quarter of rural
Salvadorans have access to safe drinking water. El Salvador has the
highest rate of infant mortality in Central America; the main cause
is diarrhea.
   The country has been the Western Hemisphere's biggest recipient
of U.S. aid this decade. Despite the donation of more than $3 bilion
in U.S. economic and military assistance since 1980, several major
indices, including availability of potable water, have worsened
rather than improved.
   Gilberto Rivera, 23, supports his mother, sister and niece with
the $4 he earns scavenging on an average day. Plastic fetches three
cents a pound, scrap metal one cent, paper three cents and iron two
cents.
   ``One government is just like another,'' he said of the election.
``They're of no matter to us.''
   He said scavenging has its hazards, principally exposure to
disease. The septic environment is particularly harmful to the
children.
   Francisca Aguilar, 37, her hands caked with black grime, talked
as she stooped and ripped open a plastic bag. She picked through the
contents _ melon rinds, eggshells, chicken bones and empty
containers _ separating plastic and glass while tossing organic
morsels aside to be snatched up by gray-headed vultures hopping
through the trash.
   Her 14-year-old daughter Lidia worked beside her. Lidia attended
school through second grade, but had to leave because the $3 her
mother makes each day from the dump isn't enough for notebooks and
shoes and clothes to keep her five children in school.
   ``I've only got the boy (her one son) studying,'' Mrs. Aguilar
said.
   Lidia withdrew a pair of eyeglasss with a missing lens from the
rubbish. She put them on and continued sifting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Presidents'Librarian     03-15 0122</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Presidents' Librarian,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Curator Switches To Ford</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Kratsas will be crossing party
lines when he moves from his job as curator of the Jimmy Carter
library to the Gerald R. Ford museum.
   Kratsas has worked since 1985 as curator of the Carter
Presidential Library in Altanta. He will hold a similar post at the
Ford museum.
   Frank H. Mackaman, director of the Ford museum and library,
announced the appointment Monday. He said Kratsas probably will be
on the job by June. Kratsas, 34, replaces Mackaman in the curator
post.
   Kratsas said the switch didn't have anything to do with politics.
   ``Professionally, this offers me a lot more opportunity, a lot
more responsibility,'' he said.
</TEXT>
