<FIRST>u a AM-TransitWorkers 2ndLd-Writethur a0429 03-15 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transit Workers, 2nd Ld-Writethur, a0429,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Reached To Avert Philly Transit Stike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with length of contract, ADD comment
from Tauss; picks up 5th graf, ``Gambaccini and ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators reached a last-minute settlement
Tuesday night, averting a strike that would have paralyzed city
buses, trolleys and subways that carry 400,000 commuters to work
daily.
   The three-year contract agreement was announced shortly before
the midnight strike deadline by Louis J. Gambaccini, general manager
of the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, and Roger
Tauss, president of Transport Workers Union Local 234.
   ``We think we have, what is in our opinion, a fair agreement all
around,'' Gambaccini said. ``It was a tough, tough negotiation.
   ``I would like to say that the union has been admirable in its
seriousness in its approach and we tried to respect that. I could
not have asked for a better, earnest effort,'' he said.
   Tauss also said he was happy with the agreement.
   Gambaccini and Tauss refused to reveal any terms of the agreement
until a union membership meeting Wednesday.
   The sticking point in negotiations had been wages, pensions and
SEPTA's demand that the union absorb projected increases in
health-care costs by paying some of the premiums or approving a cut
in benefits.
   The authority has projected its health care costs would increase
from a current $20 million to $30 million in the next three years.
   The news left workers gathered at a North Philadelphia depot
relieved.
   ``I feel good about the news, because I know if they got us a
contract, they got us a hell of a good one, and I know we don't have
any Blue Cross-Blue Shield to pay,'' said Jean Alexander, a union
spokeswoman.
   Leaders of Local 234, which represents about 5,200 city bus,
trolley and subway operators, had said the strike would begin at
12:01 a.m. Wednesday, when the contract expired, if there was no
agreement.
   Contract negotiations had resumed with a state mediator ordering
both sides to avoid public statements after transit workers hinted
there was nothing on the table to head off the city's fourth transit
strike in 12 years.
   Before the announcement, police prepared to put extra officers on
traffic control duty for the Wednesday morning rush, and the Bicycle
Coaltion of Delaware Valley set up a phone line to offer information
on bicycle routes.
   The authority told commuters it would add trains to regional rail
lines, which would not be affected, and make more stops through the
city.
   The transit workers last struck for four days in 1986. Previous
walkouts included a 44-day strike in 1977, a 19-day strike in 1981,
a 108-day strike in 1983.
</TEXT>
