<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Guns-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0810 03-15 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Guns-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0810,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Officials Praise Federal Ban in Import of Assault Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf with 3 grafs to ADD background on gun
bans, edit for transition; picks up last graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials reacted with
enthusiasm Tuesday after the Bush administration banned imports of
semiautomatic assault weapons, including the type used to kill five
schoolchildren in Stockton.
   ``This is great news,'' said state Attorney General John Van De
Kamp. ``Today's action is long overdue and I urge the administration
to make it permanent.''
   ``I congratulate the president and the administration. But my
response from the heart is, thank God for Barbara Bush,'' said city
Police Chief Daryl F. Gates, referring to the first lady's outspoken
opposition to assault weapons.
   The order suspends the importation of more than 110,000
assault-type weapons for which import applications are pending, said
national drug control director William J. Bennett.
   Affected by the decision are imports of AK-47s, Uzi carbines,
FN-FAL and FN-FNC-type weapons as well as Steyr Aug semiautomatic
weapons.
   On Jan. 17, a disturbed drifter, Patrick Purdy, used an AK-47 to
kill five children and wound 30 other people at Grover Cleveland
Elementary School in Stockton.
   Using the weapon, which allows the shooter to fire single shots
as quickly as he can pull the trigger, Purdy was able to fire 106
bullets in two minutes. He then shot and killed himself with a
handgun.
   A rising death toll from the use of semiautomatic weapons in gang
warfare had already prompted an outcry against the guns. But the
Stockton tragedy crystallized opposition and led to a nationwide
movement to ban assault weapons.
   On Monday, the California Assembly narrowly passed legislation
that would virtually ban the sale of all semiautomatic assault
weapons. The weapons have already been banned by local ordinances in
Los Angeles and Cleveland.
   Van De Kamp said he thought the Stockton shootings and the move
to restrict assault weapons in California ``have had a tremendous
impact on the administration's thinking on this issue.''
   Assemblyman Michael Roos of Los Angeles, who wrote the Assembly
bill, said he ``can't stop shaking from the excitement.''
   ``Not in my wildest imagination would I have ever dreamed that
within 24 hours of the Assembly taking action that the United States
government ... would effectively ban the importation of these
weapons,'' Roos said.
   The state Senate passed a similar bill last week. The differences
between that bill and the House's must be resolved before the
governor can sign legislation.
   The Bush administration's action Tuesday also brought praise from
Roberg Strang, a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement Administration
in New York.
   ``Certainly, anything that's done is helpful to us,'' Strang
said. ``In the last year, agents across the country have been issued
submachine guns because of the automatic weapons that we're up
against on a daily basis. ... Certainly, anything we can do to
lessen the firepower of the drug traffickers is going to be
beneficial to us.''
</TEXT>
