<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Blasphemy     03-15 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blasphemy,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie's Book Regenerates Controversy Over Old Blasphemy Law ^Eds:
Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem anger over ``The Satanic Verses,'' a novel
they say insults their faith, has renewed debate over Britain's
ancient, rarely used blasphemy law.
   The law, which has been cited in court just twice in the past 67
years, applies only to the Christian state Church of England.
   Its failure to embrace other religions was among the reasons the
Law Commission, an independent panel of academics and jurists,
called in 1985 for its abolition.
   But others, including Moslems, are fighting to extend the law to
other religions to reflect Britain's multi-ethnic society.
   Moslems say it would give them legal ground for opposing Salman
Rushdie, the author of ``The Satanic Verses,'' without resorting to
the violence urged by Iranian leaders who have called for his death.
   Eight Moslem lawyers failed Monday to persuade a London
magistrate to summon Rushdie to court on charges of blasphemous and
seditious libel, but they vowed to press their cause.
   ``What we are asking is that the law should be changed so that it
gives equal status to all citizens,'' said Liaqat Hussain,
secretary-general of the Bradford-based Council For Mosques.
   Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam by
associating the prophet Mohammed with prostitutes and suggesting
that the Koran, Islam's holy book, was Mohammed's invention, not
Allah's work.
   Rushdie, born to a Moslem family in India, is a British citizen.
He has been in hiding in England since Feb. 14, when Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ordered Moslems to kill him.
   The British government has refused to review the blasphemy law.
``There is no general consensus for reform,'' says the Home Office.
   John Vincent, a Bristol University history professor, wrote in
The Times of London that the government's position ``looks narrowly
ethnocentric.''
   Cases of blasphemy and its written form, blasphemous libel, date
to the time when church and state were indivisible and an attack on
Christianity was regarded as subversion. But church power waned, and
the law came under secular court jurisdiction in 1676.
   As part of the system of common rather than statute law, offenses
are decided by legal precedent and punishments are set by the
courts. Judges have wide discretion, since there is no definition
for blasphemy.
   Blasphemy is generally considered as the use of scurrilous,
abusive, vilifying, ludicrous or offensive words about God or
Christ, the Christian religion, the Bible, or the ``formularies of
the Church of England as by law established.'' Material must be
deemed strongly offensive to break the law.
   Other European nations also have such laws, especially the
strongly Roman Catholic ones, including Ireland, Italy, Spain and
Portugal, says Nicholas Walter, an expert on blasphemy. ``But they
are not often used,'' he says.
   Holland's law bans blasphemy that is deliberately intended to
offend religious feelings. But the Justice Ministry has decided
Rushdie's book did not break it.
   In France, which has no blasphemy law, activists have tried to
ban material on grounds of defamation.
   In the first British prosecution for blasphemy since 1922,
anti-pornography activist Mary Whitehouse sued Gay News magazine in
1977 for publishing an explicit poem about a Roman soldier's
homosexual fantasies over Christ's crucified body. The magazine and
editor Denis Lemon were fined $2,500, and Lemon drew a nine-month
suspended sentence. He lost an appeal.
   In September, state attorneys rejected Mrs. Whitehouse's demand
to prosecute the makers of the film ``The Last Temptation of
Christ'' for showing Christ dreaming of having sex with a prostitute.
   In its 3-2 decision in favor of abolishing the law, the Law
Commission held that it was wrong to single out one religion for
protection when ``members of society have a multiplicity of faiths
or none at all.''
   The commission noted that most of the public comment it received
during its four-year inquiry _ from 2,000 individuals or groups and
11,000 petition signatories _ supported retaining the law in some
form. But it said none of the proposed substitutes would work.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Church of England, approves of extending the law to all religions,
an option Jewish and Moslem groups support.
   Opponents say such a change would have to give protection for any
organization calling itself a religion, including cults, and would
infringe upon freedom of speech.
   Supporters of an extended law see no threat to free speech.
Vincent argues that it is not denials or criticism of religion that
are blasphemous, but truly offensive, sometimes inflammatory
language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bolivia-Drugs     03-15 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bolivia-Drugs,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack Of Resources Hampers Drug War In Bolivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIMORE, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trucks and jeeps stand idle for lack of
fuel. Specially trained Bolivian police complain of too little food.
   It hasn't been a good week at this key base of operations for the
national war on drug trafficking.
   Indeed, U.S. and Bolivian officials say that despite improved
cooperation between their countries, the battle is being lost
because troops don't get enough logistic and economic support.
   ``Our biggest problem is the lack of resources,'' said Travis
Kuykendall, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration's attache in
Bolivia.
   ``If Congress does not send checks to back us, they should send
us home,'' he said in an interview.
   U.S. aid for drug interdiction in Bolivia was cut from $15
million in 1988 to $10 million.
   ``We are doing everything we can to fight the cocaine trade, but
we are fighting a losing war if consumer nations do not increase
their support,'' Information Minister Herman Antelo told The
Associated Press.
   An elite U.S.-trained anti-drug police squad of 200 men, known as
the Leopards, and about 30 U.S. Drug Enforcement and Border Patrol
agents are based in Chimore, a tropical town in the heart of the
Chapare. It's a region east of Cochabamba city known for its
cultivation of coca, the plant whose dried leaves are the source of
cocaine.
   From Chimore, the men stage raids on cocaine paste processing
pits that lie hidden under the jungle canopy.
   During a weekend visit, however, police said they halted
operations because they did not have fuel for the vehicles or enough
food for the Bolivian forces.
   The United States has donated eight rebuilt Huey helicopters to
cover an area the size of Texas. Five were operational during the
weekend, but were being deployed in another region of the country,
the Beni plains.
   So coca leaf buying and selling was brisk along the main Chapare
highway.
   On better weeks, Bolivian police helped by the American agents
raid hundreds of crude cocaine processing pits.
   But the increased police presence has led many processors to set
up camp outside range of the base's ground vehicles and even
choppers, according to Drug Enforcement agents who asked not to be
identified.
   Gov. Bob Martinez of Flordia visited the Chapare region Tuesday
under tight security because of reports an assassination squad of
Colombian drug dealers was in the area.
   ``We had some information that was not confirmed that there was a
Colombian hit team in the area,'' said U.S. Drug Enforcement agent
Gene Castillo. He accompanied Martinez, who arrived in Bolivia
Monday, and U.S. Ambassador Robert Gelbard on their tour of the
district. A dozen DEA agents and Bolivian police provided security
for the group.
   Martinez, commenting on the importance of the coca plant to the
area farmers, said, ``We can't win the war here, we are going to
have to win it in the U.S.''
   Authorities of both countries say cooperation has increased, and
they are confiscating more chemicals used to process cocaine.
According to the State Department, last year they seized 5,549
gallons of ether, 11,158 gallons of sulfuric acid, 927 tons of lime,
10,304 gallons of acetone and 1.5 million gallons of gasoline and
diesel fuel.
   ``Our main purpose in the Chapare is to stop the ability to get
precursor chemicals in and cocaine paste out,'' Kuykendall said.
``Then they can't sell paste and farmers will not have a market for
their leaves.''
   Raids on pits where the leaf is mashed and mixed with chemicals
are on the rise. Last year 3,542 pits were raided, compared with
1,112 in 1987, according to the State Department. Also last year,
authorities raided 24 laboratories where the paste is converted into
hydrochloric cocaine, the refined powder sniffed by drug users. In
1987, just eight were raided, the records show.
   But, in almost all cases, the processors manage to flee before
the raids. And the number of pits raided is believed to represent
only a small portion of Bolivia's cocaine industry, whose annual
profits are estimated at $300 million. Little if any real decline in
trafficking has been noted.
   According to U.S. officials, neither Bolivia nor the U.S.
government has a single plane capable of intercepting drug flights
out of the country. Large areas bordering Argentina, Peru and Brazil
have no police presence and drugs also move freely on the rivers.
   The United States bought eight powerful motorboats, and a crew
last week confiscated 950 pounds of cocaine paste on one river. But
they had to stop because they, too, ran out of fuel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
