<FIRST>r a PM-RobberyShootings     03-15 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robbery Shootings,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Store Shootout Involving Semiautomatic Leaves Two Dead, Teen Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Semiautomatic Weapons, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shootout between a grocer and robbers
wielding a semiautomatic gun ended with two intruders shot to death
and the store owner's 14-year-old son critically wounded, police
said.
   Three men, armed with a handgun and a Mac-10 semiautomatic
pistol, entered family-owned Chico's Mini Market on Tuesday
afternoon and ordered clerks to put their hands up, said Sgt. Danny
Sneed.
   The gunman with the Mac-10 then went to a rear kitchen area.
   ``The owner, in the back with his 14-year-old son, saw the guy
and reached for his (own) gun,'' Sneed said.
   The robber then sprayed the room with at least a dozen rounds and
the owner returned fire with a .357-caliber Magnum revolver, fatally
wounding two gunmen, Sneed said.
   The third robber fled without taking any money.
   The owner's son was shot in the right side and was listed in
critical condition at Martin Luther King Jr.-Drew Medical Center,
Sneed said.
   Gerald Gerard Bennett, 18, of Compton, was pronounced dead at the
scene and Gerald Anthony Bennett, 26, of Compton was pronounced dead
at the hospital. The two men were not related, Sneed said.
   The names of the owner and his son were being withheld.
   The shooting in this suburb 10 miles south of downtown Los
Angeles occurred on the day President George Bush announced
suspensions of imports of semiautomatic weapons. The Mac-10 was not
affected by the suspension because it is American made.
</TEXT>
