<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-Panama     03-15 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Panama,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Considers Removing US Dependents from Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III says the
administration is looking into removing the dependents of U.S.
citizens working in Panama, where Americans have been targets of
harassment.
   Baker made the comments after hearing complaints from Rep.
William Lehman, D-Fla., on Tuesday about difficulties faced by both
U.S. officials in Panama and workers at the Panama Canal.
   ``There is a lot of serious potential there for conflict, for
bloodshed, and for the complete breakdown of the Panama Canal
operation,'' Lehman claimed. ``I don't think the American people are
aware of this crisis in the canal area.''
   Lehman, who chairs the House Appropriations transportation
subcommittee, spoke at a foreign operations subcommittee hearing.
   Last month, the U.S. military command headquarters in Panama said
in a statement that during the first six weeks of this year,
Panama's defense forces have ``stopped, searched, rerouted, detained
or impounded'' more U.S. government vehicles than in the previous
eight months.
   U.S.-Panamanian relations have deteriorated since 1987. Gen.
Manuel Noriega, the country's strongman, is under indictment in
Florida for drug trafficking.
   In recent months, the number of official U.S. personnel from
various government agencies has been scaled back.
   Lehman told Baker of an incident earlier this month when
Panamanian police, who are part of Noriega's defense forces, stopped
nine buses carrying about 100 American school children. The police,
who stopped the buses for about three hours, complained the vehicles
did not have proper license plates.
   Lehman also cited other incidents of harassment directed against
Panamanians who work at the canal, such as with car licenses.
   Lehman asked if the administration has a ``fallback position'' or
policy ``in case chaos breaks out.''
   Baker replied that the administration will take ``whatever steps
necessary'' to protect U.S. citizens and the canal, but added that
U.S.-Panamanian relations will not be normalized until Noriega is
removed from power.
   Asked if the administration was considering removing dependents
from the area, Baker replied, ``That's being looked into.''
   Noting that elections are set in Panama for in May, Baker
commented that Noriega is unpopular with many Panamanians.
   ``I think that there is some reasonable chance that if a
semi-fair election is held, that the opposition could win the
election,'' Baker said, adding, ``But if ... he steals that
election, he'll be even more unpopular.''
   The United States does not recognize the legitimacy of the
Panamanian government. It continues to recognize as the legitimate
authority ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was deposed
last February in a coup led by followers of defense chief Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   The United States has about 10,00 military personnel in Panama to
defend the Panama Canal. Of the about 8,000 employees who work at
the canal, the overwhelming majority are Panamanian.
</TEXT>
