<FIRST>r w PM-SenateTravel     03-15 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate Travel,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Official Agrees to Repay Some Travel Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Sergeant-at-Arms Henry K. Giugni has
agreed to stop approving his own travel expenses, and instead submit
his trip vouchers to the Rules Committee, a spokesman for the
panel's chairman says.
   Giugni accepted the arrangement suggested by Rules Committee
Chairman Wendell Ford, the Kentucky Democrat's spokesman, Phil
Norman, said Tuesday.
   Giugni also agreed to reimburse the Senate for some of his
wide-ranging travel in 1987 and 1988, according to a letter from
Ford to Giugni.
   The amount of Giugni's reimbursement was not clear Tuesday, and
attempts to reach the Senate's second-ranking staff official were
unsuccessful.
   Giugni had offered last week to reimburse any questionable
expenses after news stories revealed he had taken a dozen
taxpayer-financed trips in 1987-88, at least half of them to his
native Hawaii.
   Ford, in a March 8 letter that became public this week, wrote
Giugni, ``I concur in your proposal to reimburse the Senate for a
portion of your travel expenses.''
   Ford said that all of Giugni's claims could be justified ``in a
legal sense,'' but wrote that ``some of them might be questioned and
require additional explanation.''
   ``But your decision avoids any appearance of impropriety,'' Ford
said, in commending Giugni for his decision.
   Giugni said last week that he conducted official business on all
of the trips, mostly to inspect senators' home-state offices. Giugni
said trips that included non-Senate business were only partially
billed to taxpayers.
   Giugni, with a $115 million budget, is the chief Senate
purchasing officer and has authority over the Capitol police force.
</TEXT>
