<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Homeless-HUD     03-15 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless-HUD,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Different Racial Mix and More Families Among Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal survey says the nation is housing
more homeless people than ever, particularly families, but it offers
no estimate of the total number of homeless Americans.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development study released
Tuesday said spending on homeless shelters has increased more than
fivefold, to more than $1.5 billion annually, since a similar HUD
study in 1984.
   It said the number of shelters and shelter beds had nearly
tripled since then.
   The study was released as President Bush called homelessness a
``national shame,'' and vowed to step up the search for solutions.
He said he was troubled by ``ragged pathetic figures huddled over
steam grates'' near the White House.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said the study ``shows that America's
efforts to shelter the homeless are beginning to bear results, and
that it is very much a grass roots campaign, characterized by local
and private intitatives.''
   The HUD study reported a large-scale private effort to aid the
homeless, with nine of every 10 shelters around the nation operated
by private, non-profit groups. Two-thirds of the operating funds
come from local, state and federal governments, it said.
   HUD's findings were based on a survey of a sampling of homeless
shelter managers.
   The department did not offer an estimate of the total homeless
population. In its 1984 study, HUD estimated the figure at 250,000
to 350,000 people, a figure that homeless advocates criticized as
too low.
   The new study estimated there were 5,400 homeless shelters in the
nation in 1988, up from 1,900 in 1984. Total bed capacity was
estimated at 275,000, up from 100,000.
   The study found a two-thirds occupancy rate overall, and placed
the average occupancy per night in homeless shelters at 180,000. The
figure was 70,000 in the earlier study.
   Occupancy rates varied greatly by size, city and type of homeless
shelter, as well as the weather.
   About one-fourth of the shelters were reported full all year
round. Shelters set up primarily to handle families with children
showed the highest average of nights at full capacity _ 259 days a
year.
   Almost half the shelter managers surveyed reported having to turn
away at least one person on an average night because of lack of
space _ although most were referred to other shelters.
   The survey concluded that the types of people staying at homeless
shelters has changed.
   ``While both families and unaccompanied men are increasing among
the sheltered homeless, families are increasing more rapidly,'' it
said. ``Unaccompanied men no longer represent the majority of the
sheltered homeless.''
   The percentage of those sheltered who are members of families was
put at 40 percent, nearly twice the 21 percentage figure in 1984. In
actual numbers, the family members receiving shelter quadrupled over
the past four years to more than 60,000.
   Three-quarters of those were single parents with children. The
remainder was divided equally between couples with children and
couples without children.
   The study said one-fourth of those in the shelters are children.
In big cities, children make up almost one-third of those in
shelters.
   The proportion of unaccompanied women in shelters was unchanged
at 14 percent. But their actual numbers increased 180 percent. The
report said that category included victims of domestic violence and
``so-called `bag ladies.'''
   Shelter populations also changed in racial makeup. In 1984,
nearly three out of five were white, and in 1988 the proportion was
reversed. It found 58 percent on an average night were minorities,
most of whom were black.
   Shelter managers estimated that 33 percent of their clients had
problems with alcoholism, 34 percent with mental illness and 25
percent with drug abuse.
   HUD estimated that 80,000 people contributed 30 million hours of
time a year to the shelters.
   HUD surveyed 205 shelter managers and administrators of voucher
programs for the homeless in 65 cities and towns with populations of
25,000 or more, conducted by telephone, and extrapolated the results
for the entire nation.
</TEXT>
