<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-15 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Shoot Up, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost marginal ground against the Japanese
yen Wednesday, while share prices sharply rose on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
171.39 points Tuesday, added another 376.13 points, or 1.19 percent,
to finish trading at 32,100.48, surpassing the 32,000-point level
for the first time since March 3, when it finished at 32,000.10.
   The dollar closed at 129.88 yen, down 0.04 yen from Tuesday's
129.92-yen fihish. The currency opened at 129.80 yen and fluctuated
in a tight 129.75-129.90 yen range.
   Dealers said the dollar opened lower in Tokyo following similar
trends on overseas markets and added that the trading rate was
likely to move only slightly until the release later Wednesday of
U.S. trade figures.
   The U.S. Commerce Department was scheduled to announce American
trade figures for January, and Tokyo dealers said they expected the
figure to narrow from December's deficit.
   In stock dealings, traders said the stability in the dollar-yen
rate prompted the Nikkei rise.
   A government report released late Tuesday that showed a decline
in U.S. retail sales in January also removed investor concern over
inflation and helped the index gain, said Kenji Ishizuka of Daiwa
Securities.
</TEXT>
