<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings     03-15 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Endorses Base-Closing Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Armed Services Committee has
overwhelmingly backed a military base closing plan, supporting
Chairman Les Aspin's prediction that the full House will go along.
   The committee voted 43-4 Tuesday to support recommendations of
the independent Commission on Base Realignment and Closure, which
proposed that 145 military facilities either be shut down, have
their operations reduced, or their mission changed.
   Both houses must disapprove the entire list of recommendations to
stop them. The deadline for voting under will be in May, with the
exact date to be determined by the number of days each house is in
session.
   Aspin, D-Wis., said after the commission's recommendation was
released last Dec. 29, ``I fully expect the Congress to support this
package.''
   He said that while two dozen House members' districts were
affected, more than 100 others who feared base closings were ``are
breathing a sigh of relief.''
   ``They now have a vested interest'' in approval of the list,
``because it will give the bases in their areas at least a decade's
breather,'' Aspin said.
   The last batch of closings occurred in 1977.
   Tuesday, Aspin said, ``From the information we've gotten, the
commission has done a reasonable job.'' Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., chairman of the military installations subcommittee, added,
``It does appear a reasonable, prudent commission has reached these
decisions.''
   Voting against the commission were Reps. Jim Courter, R-N.J.;
Larry Hopkins, R-Ky.; Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., and Lane Evans, D-Ill.
   Evans has been upset with the proposed closing of Chanute Air
Force Base in Illinois, while Hopkins _ and others who supported the
commission _ were angry with what they called Pentagon stonewalling
on congressional requests for justification of the proposals.
   Courter said the plan to place Fort Dix, N.J., on a semi-active
status would end its basic training mission without permitting
non-military use of the facility. McCloskey warned of substantial
environmental cleanup costs if the Jefferson Proving Ground in
Indiana is closed.
   The commission said its recommendations could save an estimated
$694 million a year, with 20-year savings estimated at $5.6 billion.
While a number of lawmakers said the savings would disappear because
of environmental cleanup costs, the law establishing the commission
told the panel not to consider such expenses.
   The Pentagon already had been required to clean up hazardous
waste at military installations.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee held a hearing on the
commission plan Tuesday. Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
said, ``The military services did not indicate to me they had a
problem with any part of the recommendation.''
   But Sen. Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill., a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said the recommendations would result in an
``American tragedy'' for those thrown out of work in places such as
Chanute.
   Dixon said the point system used to decide the fate of Chanute
was based on incorrect assumptions about the base's facilities.
   The commission last Dec. 29 proposed closing 86 facilities,
partially closing five others and changing the mission in 54 other
installations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
