<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CleanNeedles     03-15 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Needles,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Remarks Depart from Earlier Memo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arm of the Department of Health and Human
Services is warning local AIDS programs they could lose federal
money if they support needle-exchange programs, even though the head
of HHS has more recently endorsed such programs.
   The warning was contained in a memo from the National Institute
of Drug Abuse. The memo went out about two weeks before HHS
Secretary Louis Sullivan endorsed local programs that let drug
addicts trade their used needles for clean ones to stem the spread
of AIDS.
   Sullivan, whose department includes the Public Health Service,
which oversees the institute, also said the federal government could
provide information and personnel to such programs.
   But Public Health Service spokesman James Brown denied a conflict
between the memo and Sullivan's comments. He said the policies of
both the service and the White House prohibit use of federal funds
for needle-exchange programs, but if that policy were changed, the
department could provide such federal support.
   ``You could do it, which is what Sullivan said,'' Brown said.
``We're not doing it and NIDA (the institute) is telling people
we're not going to do it.''
   Asked about the policies, Sullivan's spokesman, Campbell Gardett,
said: ``We're in an in-between period when an awful lot has to be
worked out. ... It's a controversial enough thing that it's
eventually going to come down to Bush.''
   Bush's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, told reporters Friday: ``The
president is opposed to exchangeable needles under any condition.''
   Sullivan, in an interview with the AP two days before that, said
he did not ``subscribe to the view'' that clean-needle programs
condone drug abuse. Of such programs, he said, ``We would be very
supportive of such efforts'' in communities that want such programs.
   The Feb. 19 institute memo, obtained by The Associated Press,
told 41 institute-funded AIDS programs that Public Health Service
policy prohibits ``any kind of federal support'' for programs that
distribute clean needles to addicts to help stop the spread of the
deadly virus.
   The author of the memo, Barry S. Brown, chief of community
research at the institute, told the 41 affected programs that
federal aid would be denied to anyone ``who is engaged in, or who
supports'' needle-exchange programs.
   In part, the memo said:
   ``It should be clearly understood by all NIDA (institute)
grantees and contractors that it is against NIDA and Public Health
Service (PHS) policy to provide any kind of federal support to
programs involving the making available of new or cleaned needles or
providing a needle exchange program. Anyone receiving NIDA funds who
is engaged in, or who supports, activity prohibited by the PHS will
face prompt action to suspend that program's funding.''
   Brown said that he had written the memo after someone running one
of the projects raised the needle-exchange issue and that he had
subsequently gotten ``a couple'' of calls about his directive.
   Brown said that after he explained to the callers that the
support referred to in the memo was federal financial aid, ``they
went away satisfied.''
   Billi Odegaard, director of the Multnomah County Health Division,
which serves Portland, Ore., and is receiving about $1 million in
institute funds this year for its AIDS project, said the memo at
first ``sounded extreme.''
   But she said Brown explained to one of her colleagues that
``we're OK under that policy as long as we're not directly
operating'' a needle-exchange program.
   Still, officials of a Portland community group, Outside In, are
concerned the directive could hamper their efforts to start a
needle-exchange program, which they had hoped to coordinate with the
Multnomah project.
   ``We're worried about whether they can continue to be supportive
and to what degree,'' said Kathy Oliver, director of Outside In.
   Brown, the research chief, said an institute-funded program could
subcontract with a needle-exchange program as long as the federal
funds weren't mixed with the needle-exchange money. He also said
that while someone paid from institute funds could not spend their
federally-paid time coordinating or advising a needle-exchange
program, they could do so ``on his or her own time.''
   It is unclear how much discretion Sullivan has in changing policy
within his department.
   Congress last year passed legislation that prevents certain
federal funds from being used on needle-exchange programs. Another
law passed last year gives the surgeon general authority to use
federal funds on a demonstration needle-exchange project.
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who runs the Public Health
Service, has said he supports needle-exchange trials to study how
effective such programs could be. However, he hasn't proposed a
federal program.
</TEXT>
