<DOCNO> AP890315-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ContraAid     03-15 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Aid,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, White House Differ on Aid Statements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is fine-tuning its
proposal for non-military aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels amid
confusion between the White House and State Department over how much
to request from Congress.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday that
reports President Bush is preparing to ask Congress to approve aid
in the $40 million to $50 million range are ``in the ballpark.''
   But Secretary of State James A. Baker III told a congressional
subcommittee that was ``not an accurate number as far as I'm
concerned.'' Testifying before before the House Appropriations
foreign operations subcommittee, Baker didn't say whether the figure
was too high or too low.
   Told about the discrepancy, Fitzwater said he agreed with Baker
and that when he talked about ballpark figures, ``It's a big
ballpark.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., one of Capitol Hill's most
ardent Contra supporters, will introduce legislation this week to
give the Contras $75 million in new humanitarian aid when the
current aid package runs out March 31, according to a congressional
source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Helms plan would allow for purchase of such items as
gasoline, which are banned under the current aid setup because they
could have a potentially military use.
   Helms also will seek a sense-of-the Congress resolution that
resumption of military aid for the contras should be considered
after one year unless President Bush determines Nicaragua has lived
up to its promises to implement democratic reforms, the source said.
   Bush administration officials have said they are not seeking
miliitary aid, and Fitzwater reiterated Tuesday that the goal is a
diplomatic solution to the eight-year-old internal war in Nicaragua.
   Fitzwater said no final decision has been made on what will Bush
will propose in the way of new humanitarian aid, ``and we are not
setting artificial timetables for decisions.''
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero said administration officials told
him Bush would seek in the neighborhood of $40 million to keep the
Contras alive in their camps on the Honduran side of the Nicaragua
border where some 11,000 rebels are encamped.
   U.S. sources have said the request probably will exceed $50
million.
   Fitzwater said Bush's plan would include ``the ideas of
incentives and disincentives'' to accompany the humanitarian aid and
diplomacy efforts.
   ``In this approach we are also pursuing the building of a
bipartisan support for whatever policy emerges,'' he said.
   Administration officials have said Baker is considering various
economic and diplomatic incentives toward Nicaragua if the ruling
Sandinistas live up to their promises for democratic reform.
   Fitzwater also acknowledged that the cooperation of Honduras in
allowing the Contras to keep their camps on the border is a key
factor.
   He noted that Undersecretary of State Robert Kimmitt visited
Honduran President Jose Azcona on Monday and discussed with him the
matter of incentives, Sandinista compliance with democratization
pledges, and the agreement by the five Central American nations to
reach agreement on disbanding the Contras.
   Baker said the effort to maintain the anti-Sandinista Contras
afloat represents ``a genuine view that they do represent somewhat
of an incentive for the Sandinista government to keep the promises
they haven't kept in the past,'' including steps toward
democratization and civil liberties.
   The five Central American presidents agreed last month in El
Salvador to devise a plan by this spring for the disbanding of the
rebels in exchange for democratic reforms in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
