<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SpecialProsecutors     03-15 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Special Prosecutors,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Extends Inquiry Into Fauntroy While Ethics Order is Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is giving the
Justice Department 60 more days to determine whether a special
prosecutor is needed to investigate payroll padding allegations
against House member Walter Fauntroy.
   The move by Thornburgh gives his department more time to assess
allegations against Fauntroy and buys time to deal with a ticklish
political question posed by the independent counsel order issued
last summer by then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   On Tuesday, Thornburgh amended the order that was issued as
Meese's last official act on his last day in office.
   Meese, who himself was twice investigated by court-appointed
independent counsels, issued a regulation expanding the reach of the
independent counsel statute from members of the executive branch to
members of Congress.
   Thornburgh gave himself the option of extending for another 60
days the 90-day preliminary inquiry provided in Meese's order for
determining if evidence warranted appointment of an independent
counsel.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said Thornburgh issued
the order to give the Justice Department's Public Integrity Section
more time to complete the inquiry into Fauntroy, a Democrat who is
the District of Columbia's non-voting delegate.
   The department has been investigating allegations that Fauntroy
hired the son of Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., and paid him $21,398 even
though the younger Savage was living in Chicago instead of
Washington.
   Savage was on Fauntroy's payroll between September 1987 and June
1988, a period during which he swore he was living in Chicago
because he was running for the Illinois legislature.
   The department opened its 90-day inquiry after a report by The
Associated Press about the employment arrangement.
   After taking office, Thornburgh expressed doubts about the Meese
order. Thornburgh said that the public integrity section, created
when he was head of the Criminal Division in the mid-1970s, was
capable of investigating corruption allegations against members of
Congress.
   Thornburgh, however, faced a storm of criticism from Meese
loyalists and conservative Republicans in the House who are anxious
to use the special prosecutor issue to embarrass House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, the subject of an internal ethics probe.
   The law has been criticized, notably by people who have been
prosecuted under it, as unfairly applying only to executive branch
officials and not members of Congress.
   After threatening to rescind the order, Thornburgh said he would
study the issue. Since then, the issue has been reviewed at the
White House and in the Justice Department.
   The attorney general recently asked the President's Commission on
Federal Ethics Law Reform to study the issue. The panel, which
issued its recommendations last week, said members of Congress
should be subject to the independent counsel provisions as well as
executive branch officials.
   Had Thornburgh wished, the Fauntroy case would have provided the
attorney general with a perfect opportunity to scuttle Meese's
order, according to Justice Department sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Assistant Attoney General Edward S.G. Dennis Jr. and other
officials have voiced objections to the regulation, which bars the
department from subpoenaing documents or testimony during the
preliminary investigation, sources said.
   The sources say there is uneasiness with the Meese regulation
because it could hobble a criminal investigation of a member of
Congress.
   After the preliminary inquiry is completed, according to the
regulation, the attorney general has the choice of closing the
investigation or appointing an independent counsel to purse a
full-scale criminal probe.
   The independent counsel would be empowered to impanel a grand
jury.
   ``Given this administration's recognition and the attorney
general's recognition that the appearance of fairness and of ethical
conduct is important... I would have hoped that the attorney general
would have been more careful to avoid the appearance of an
eleventh-hour change in the rules of the game,'' said Laurence
Tribe, a Harvard University law professor who is an avid defender of
the independent counsel law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
