<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--ChurchDebts     03-15 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Church Debts,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Council Runs Out of Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco Council of Churches has
gone broke, officials said.
   ``As of today, the council is defunct,'' the Rev. Norman Leach,
executive director of the organization, said as he cleaned out his
desk Tuesday.
   The organization has a $2 million annual budget, but faces a
$200,000 deficit, said Leach.
   The council's five staff members were told March 9 they were
being laid off, according to Leach, who blamed the organization's
financial problems on its board's ``lack of expertise.''
   ``They are good and sincere Christians, but they don't know how
to run a business,'' he said.
   About 45 Protestant churches belong to the council, which
provides social services such as food programs that feed about 400
elderly people daily, halfway houses and night ministries.
   Many of the services have been picked up by other agencies, but
sponsors are need for others, including a halfway house for women
convicts and their small children, and a day-care center.
</TEXT>
