<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Contras     03-15 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contras,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduras, Nicaragua Clash over U.S. Request for More Contra Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras and Nicaragua are at odds
over whether the Bush administration's expected proposal for more
aid to Nicaraguan rebels violates a Central American agreement to
dismantle Contra rebel forces.
   A Honduran presidential spokesman on Tuesday said such a request
would not not contradict the Feb. 14 accords, which call for the
dissolution of the Nicaraguan rebels.
   ``The accord ... reached in El Salvador does not rule out
humanitarian help before the dismantling,'' said Marco Tulio Romero,
spokesman for Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo.
   But Barricada, the newspaper of Nicaragua's ruling Sandinista
party, on Tuesday maintained the aid plans ``trample'' on Central
American peace efforts.
   ``The United States cannot continue indefinitely with the double
standard of speaking in favor of peace when the only thing it wants
is to make war,'' the newspaper said.
   The neighboring countries were reacting to reports the Bush
administration will ask Congress for an extension of non-lethal aid
to the Contras.
   Washington has helped the Contras since 1981 in their fight
against the leftist Sandinistas, a campaign all but halted one year
ago after U.S. military aid to the rebels ceased and a truce was
signed by the warring parties.
   Azcona and four other Central American presidents agreed to draft
a plan by May 15 to demobilize the Contras, about 11,000 of whom
live in jungle camps in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua promised, in turn, electoral
and other reforms to bring greater democracy to his country. Ortega
moved up general elections by 10 months, to February 1990.
   In keeping with that agreement, Nicaragua's National Assembly on
Tuesday it would grant amnesty to 1,933 former national guardsmen,
most of them jailed since the triumph of the Sandinista revolution
in July 1979.
   Barricada said the announcment ``that Bush will ask Congress for
more humanitarian aid to maintain the Contras in Honduran territory
for a year to pressure Nicaragua clashes with the task of
demobilization and tramples the Central American accord.''
   The pro-government Nicaragua daily ``El Nuevo Diario'' said the
request would be a ``blow to the peace agreements.''
   Government sources in Washington and Contra leaders have told The
Associated Press the 12-month aid request is $40 million to $50
million.
   A $27 million six-month package of non-lethal aid approved by
Congress last year runs out at the end of March.
   ``They (the Bush administration) want something that'll see us
through well into the Nicaraguan election,'' U.S. Embassy spokesman
Charles Barclay said in Tegucigalpa.
   ``It is in Honduras' interests that these armed insurgent groups
don't remain orphans without humanitarian aid from the United
States,'' Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras told a news
conference.
   Honduran officials met in this capital Monday with the U.S.
undersecretary of state for political affairs, Robert M. Kimmitt.
   ``The purpose of his visit was to politically coordinate the
strengthening of Central American democracy,'' said Lopez Contreras.
``The United States and our government don't want armed groups to
remain permanently in Honduran territory, but we also support the
democratization of Nicaragua.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Mutants     03-15 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Mutants,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Virus Resistance Said To Have No Immediate Impact On Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The finding that some strains of AIDS virus are
resistant to treatment by the most widely used anti-AIDS drug will
not require any immediate change in use of the drug, researchers
said.
   A study by the drug's maker found that 11 patients with advanced
AIDS or AIDS-related complex, a related illness, were infected with
virus strains only partly responsive to treatment with the anti-AIDS
drug AZT.
   Five patients carried virus strains with ``very marked reductions
in sensitivity'' to the drug, according to a letter sent to doctors
by the the the manufacturer, Burroughs Wellcome Co. of Research
Triangle Park, N.C.,
   AZT, also known as zidovudine or Retrovir, is the only drug
approved in the United States to treat AIDS virus infection.
   ``People who are on AZT and are currently benefiting from AZT
should not panic and consider this a major setback,'' said Dr.
Anthony Fauci, director of the AIDS program at the National
Institutes of Health.
   ``Just because one can isolate a resistant strain from a patient
doesn't mean AZT is not effective in combating most of the viral
replication in the patient.''
   Preliminary results of the study were announced Tuesday in
London. A full report of the study, by Brendan Larder and Graham
Darby of Wellcome Research Laboratories in England and Douglas
Richman of the University of California, San Diego, will be
published soon in the journal Science.
   The development of resistant strains of infectious agents after
widespread use of a drug is common, doctors said. Many bacteria, for
example, have become resistant to penicillin and therefore must be
treated with other antibiotics.
   The same thing happened with genital herpes virus after the
introduction of a drug to treat it, said Dr. Sandra Nusinoff
Lehrman, head of the department of antimicrobial therapy at
Burroughs Wellcome.
   In that case, the viruses that became resistant to the drug also
became less able to cause disease, she said.
   ``I would say these findings don't in themselves require that any
alterations in patient therapy be made,'' said Lehrman.
   ``However, the thing you have to stress is that decisions about
the treatment of HIV (the AIDS virus) really are joint decisions
between a particular physician and his patient.''
   Fauci said two new anti-AIDS drugs are beginning human trials
now, and the use of those drugs in combination with AZT should
enable doctors to control any AZT-resistant strains of the human
immune deficiency virus that causes AIDS.
   ``You have other drugs that are also effective against the AIDS
virus,'' Fauci said. ``You either switch or use a combination of
drugs.''
   The two new drugs _ dideoxycytidine, or DDC, and dideoxyinosine,
or DDI _ are available at National Institutes of Health AIDS
treatment centers across the country for patients whose infection
might become severely resistant to AZT, he said.
   Eventually those drugs might be used in combination with AZT or
each other to treat resistant strains, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
