<DOCNO> AP890315-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls-Congress     03-15 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Congress,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riegle Promotes Paying S&amp;L Cost Up Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal for more up-front payments to close
insolvent savings and loans is gaining support among some Democrats
as an alternative to President Bush's bailout plan for the industry.
   The General Accounting Office was asked Tuesday by Sen. Don
Riegle, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, to work up
estimates on the impact of absorbing most of the bailout costs
immediately rather than spreading them over 30 years as Bush would
do.
   ``We may find ourselves a way to save an awfully lot of money,''
Riegle said after congressional auditors testified it would have
been cheaper to close and pay off depositors in 179 failed S&amp;Ls in
1988 that instead were merged and kept open through government
subsidies.
   Comptroller General Charles A. Bowsher said he could not estimate
how much cheaper outright closings would have been. But because many
of the mergers arranged by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board carry
10-year aid packages that include tax breaks and guarantees against
losses for the new owners, he estimated the mergers plus expenses in
closing 43 other S&amp;Ls last year will total more than $62 billion
over a decade.
   Bush would pay for closing or merging another 350 S&amp;Ls at or near
insolvency through $50 billion to be raised over the next three
years from the sale of taxpayer-guaranteed bonds by a new off-budget
government corporation.
   The bonds would not be paid off for 30 years and only the annual
interest costs associated with them would be reflected in the
federal budget. But those interest costs would be $100 million to
$200 million more annually _ or $3 billion to $6 billion more over
30 years _ than if the tab for the bailout were simply lumped into
the federal debt.
   Riegle said dumping as much of the bailout costs as possible into
the fiscal 1989 budget would be a ``cleaner'' approach without
upsetting a resolve by Congress and Bush to meet a $100 billion
deficit target in the fiscal 1990 budget.
   Both have given up hopes of meeting the $136 billion deficit
target set in the 1985 Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law for fiscal
1989, which ends Sept. 30. The White House now says the 1989 deficit
will be more like $170 billion.
   ``This may be another way to work with the Gramm-Rudman
restraints and at the same time save the taxpayers an awfully lot of
money,'' Riegle said. ``Then we wouldn't be forced to make these
mergers, which are very expensive.''
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the House Banking
Committee, has endorsed a similar approach to Riegle's plan, as has
William Niskanean, a former economic adviser to President Reagan.
   According to Riegle's plan, the government would buy back many of
the notes and loans it sold at discounts to the new owners of the
institutions it merged in 1988 before Sept. 30.
   The plan also would include in the 1989 budget the cost of
closing and paying off depositors in the worst of the 350 insolvent
but still-operating S&amp;Ls.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has taken control of over 120
of those institutions in the two months since Bush announced his S&amp;L
proposal and plans to take control of another 100 before the end of
March.
   However, without the needed money in the government insurance
funds to pay off their depositors or subsidize their mergers, those
S&amp;Ls are still operating with losses mounting in the tens of
millions of dollars daily.
   The GAO estimated the cost of the 1988 S&amp;L closings and mergers
at $37 billion _ assuming all could be paid for immediately rather
than financed, and not including the $6 billion to $8 billion in tax
breaks that were a part of some packages.
   Both administration and congressional experts put the
present-value cost of resolving the other 350 insolvent institutions
at roughly $50 billion. That makes the total cost of the bailout
package about $90 billion _ if it all could be paid for in cash
instead of borrowing.
   ``I don't think people realize the magnitude of the problem,''
Bowsher said.
   ``This is bigger than the Marshall Plan,'' he said, referring to
the $13 billion _ $60 billion in today's dollars _ that the United
States spent rebuilding Europe after World War II.
   Bowsher said the cost to the government of just one S&amp;L merger
package alone in December was greater than the combined costs of the
government's bailouts of New York City, the Lockheed Corp. and the
Chrysler Corp. in the 1970s.
</TEXT>
