<SECOND>PM-Forest Money,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Acres to be Added to Forests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly $55 million in Forest Service money that
the Reagan administration diverted from a land acquisition fund has
been restored, making it possible to add thousands of acres to
national forests in 22 states.
   The Forest Service had been told in the final months of the
Reagan administration to move the $54.9 million into its
firefighting fund in anticipation of forest fires in 1989, John
Leasure, budget officer for the Forest Service, said Tuesday.
   He said the fire season has just begun and it is too early to
tell how much will be needed, but about $40 million is available and
more could be obtained later if needed.
   The land being added to existing national forests is considered
necessary to protect forests from encroachment by developers or
other private interests.
   The largest expenditures and the forests involved are $8.04
million for Nantahala National Forest, N.C.; $7.4 million, Lake
Tahoe Basin, Calif.; $5.7 million, Columbia River Gorge, Ore.; $4.9
million, Green Mountain National Forest, Vt.; and $3.6 million,
Eleven Point Wild and Scenic River, Mo.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. and chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee, along with others in Congress had objected to the Office
of Management and Budget when the Reagan administration proposed to
spend land acquisition funds on firefighting.
   ``I am pleased that budget director (Richard) Darman has seen to
it that President Bush's expressed commitment to the environment has
been honored,'' said Leahy. ``I am glad that our last-ditch efforts
paid off and that the OMB reversed its earlier position.''
   Other expenditures are:
   California _ San Bernardino National Forest, $1 million.
   Colorado _ Arapahoe National Recreation Area, $120,400.
   Idaho _ Rapid River Wild and Scenic River $3,050; Sawtooth
National Recreation Area, $2.4 million; Main Salmon Wild and Scenic
River, $900,000.
   Illinois _ Shawnee National Forest, $950,000.
   Indiana _ Wayne-Hoosier National Forest, $650,000.
   Kentucky _ Daniel Boone National Forest, $78,000.
   Maine and New Hampshire _ White Mountain National Forest,
$152,655.
   Michigan _ Kirtland Warbler Habitat, $578,867; Ottawa National
Forest $48,135.
   Minnesota _ Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness, $508,191.
   Montana _ Flathead National Forest, $1.9 million; Middle Fork,
Flathead Wild and Scenic River, $95,521.
   New Mexico _ Santa Fe National Forest, $56,000.
   North Carolina _ Pisgah National Forest, $1 million.
   Ohio _ Wayne National Forest, $3.1 million.
   Oregon _ Cascade Head Scenic Research Area, $197,346; Oregon
Dunes National Recreation Area, $175,073; Rogue Wild and Scenic
River, $727,446; Siuslaw National Forest, $400,000.
   Pennsylvania _ Allegheny National Forest, $151,658.
   Utah _ Red Butte Canyon Research Area, $160,000; Wasatch National
Forest, $22,000.
   Virginia _ Mount Rogers National Recreation Area, $1.7 million;
Jefferson National Forest, $13,932.
   Washington _ Mount Baker-Snoqualmi National Forest $2.5 million;
Mount St. Helen's, $36,300.
   West Virginia _ Monongahela National Forest, $11,920; Spruce
Knobs-Seneca Rocks National Recreation Area, $1.03 million.
</TEXT>
