<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     03-15 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Up Sharply; Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose back
beyond the 32,000-point level with a sharp gain today, while the
dollar lost marginally against the Japanese yen.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 129.88 yen,
down 0.04 yen from Tuesday's 129.92-yen finish. The currency opened
at 129.80 yen and fluctuated in a tight 129.75-129.90 yen range.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 171.39-point gainer
Tuesday, added another 376.13 points, or 1.19 percent, to finish
trading at 32,100.48, surpassing the 32,000-point level for the
first time since March 3, when it finished at 32,000.10.
   The Nikkei, which was higher across the board, rose notably in
the last 30 minutes of trading.
   Despite concerns that today was the account settlement day for
futures markets, in which the Nikkei's 225 spot issues are often
sold for profit-taking, the index rose mainly due to stability in
the bond and foreign exchange markets.
   ``Even before the release of the U.S. trade figure later today,
investors' buying interest was strong,'' said a dealer with Nomura
Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Commerce Department was to announce U.S. trade figures
for January later today and Tokyo dealers said they expect the
figure to narrow to about $10 billion, down from December's $11.89
billion.
   Construction issues were among the winners in active trading,
with the first-section volume estimated at 1.2 billion shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate moved little in
anticipation of the U.S. trade report, dealers said.
   Most Japanese investors made some position adjustments and
remained on the sidelines, trying to avoid making major moves before
the announcement of the major economic indicator, said a dealer with
a commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
