<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-15 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Requiring Approval of Foreign Airline Security Procedures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign airlines operating in the United States
will have to have security programs approved by the Federal Aviation
Administration, under a new rule adopted by the government.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner told the Senate
Transportation appropriations subcommittee Tuesday that the new
requirement is aimed at making sure foreign carriers ``have adequate
security measures to protect civil aviation against criminal acts of
violence.''
   The rule was proposed by the government late last year, before
the Dec. 21 destruction of Pan American Flight 103 by a bomb over
Lockerbie, Scotland, which resulted in 270 deaths.
   American carriers already must have FAA-approved security
procedures.
   Under the new regulation, the 111 foreign airlines serving the
United States would have to submit their security procedures to the
FAA within 90 days of the rule's official publication in the Federal
Register. That is expected Thursday.
   The FAA is required to tell the carriers if their rules are
adequate within 30 days of receiving them. If they are judged
insufficient, the government could ultimately withdraw an airline's
permission to land in this country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Congressman Sees Problem in Long-Distance Calls from Pay Phones</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government should step up action
against companies that charge high rates without notice to people
who make long-distance calls on public phones, a Tennessee
congressman says.
   Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn., said Federal Communications Commission
action last month was ``too little, too late'' in ordering five
``alternative operator service'' companies to clearly identify
themselves, make their rates available and not block calls to any
long-distance carrier.
   ``Much more is needed to protect the consumer'' from such
companies that now are handling 20 percent of the calls at the
nation's 7.5 million public phones, Cooper said Tuesday.
   ``Even the major AOS companies themselves have already agreed to
a code of ethics that goes farther than the FCC action,'' he said.
``Why is the FCC so timid when almost everyone agrees that major
reforms are needed?''
   Cooper, who along with Rep. Matthew J. Rinaldo, R-N.J., has
introduced legislation requiring such companies to charge ``just and
reasonable rates,'' said these companies are carging as much as 200
percent more than normal long-distance rates, charging for
incompleted calls, billing from cities the caller has never visited
and are channeling callers onto long-distance carriers they did not
choose.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Cost Estimates for Major Weapons Programs Soaring</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Statistics showing a higher estimated cost of
major Pentagon weapon programs ``have already been overtaken by
events,'' says a defense spokesman.
   The latest Selected Acquisition Report released Tuesday showed
that the estimated cost of the Pentagon's 94 biggest weapon programs
skyrocketed by $57.5 billion last year, primarily because the
services want to buy more of certain weapons in the mid-1990s.
   However, President Bush told Congress in February he would cut
back the military build-up plans of former President Reagan, so the
statistics are out of date, said Jim Turner, a Pentagon spokesman.
   The update is based on the budget and policy guidelines of the
Reagan administration because Congress mandates the review be
conducted every Dec. 31, Turner said.
   Nonetheless, the report outlines the priorities of the services
and the budget items over which Bush, Congress and the military are
likely to clash.
   As of Dec. 31, the Pentagon said the 94 key programs that Reagan
was pursuing carried a combined pricetag of $818.6 billion, up $57.5
billion or 7.6 percent from a quarterly estimate last Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
