<FIRST>r i PM-Greece     03-15 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Cabinet Member Resigns Because Of Financial Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's top aide
resigned from the Cabinet over his alleged involvement in a banking
scandal, and a member of the governing party said the premier should
follow suit.
   Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas on Tuesday became the eighth Cabinet
member to resign since the scandal surfaced in October.
   ``Having stood by you for 25 years in all democratic struggles .
.. I resign from my position as minister to the prime minister
expressing my sensitivity,'' the premier's aide said in a letter to
Papandreou.
   Papandreou's government defeated a motion of censure by a
parliamentary vote of 155-123 Monday night. The motion was
introduced by the opposition New Democracy party, which said members
of Papandreou's Socialist government were deeply involved in the
scandal.
   Three legislators from Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement abstained in the voting, and the premier quickly expelled
them from the party for not supporting the government.
   One of the three, Antonis Tritsis, said Tuesday the government
should resign to save Greece's honor.
   He said if a caretaker government is not formed to prepare for
the June 18 elections then ``Papandreou puts a tragic end to his
political life.''
   Koutsogiorgas has repeatedly denied the claims by the
conservative opposition that he was directly involved in the
scandal, which centers around Greek banker George Koskotas.
   Koskotas is in a Salem, Mass., jail awaiting a hearing on a Greek
extradition request. He fled Greece in November after being indicted
in a $200 million fraud and embezzlement case.
   He has said Papandreou and Cabinet members authorized plans to
siphon millions of dollars from the Bank of Crete while Koskotas was
chairman and that they received millions of dollars in payoffs.
   Papandreou has denied the allegations and claimed Koskotas was
part of a CIA scheme to destablize Greece's Socialist government.
   The premier also threatened ``painful'' consequences if the
United States does not return Koskotas to Greece before the
elections. He did not say what the consequences might be but hinted
last week they could involve the future of U.S. military bases in
Greece.
   Washington has denied the allegations about the CIA, and New
Democracy leader Constantine Mitsotakis called them a ``children's
fairy tale.''
</TEXT>
