<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-F-16Crash     03-15 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-F-16 Crash,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesota Man Killed In Crash Of F-16 In Spain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cliff Washington is a woman.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials sought today to determine the
cause of the collision of two U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter jets in
which one pilot was killed and the other parachuted to safety, a
spokeswoman said.
   The accident took place Tuesday during a routine training mission
over central Cuenca province, about 85 miles southeast of Madrid's
Torrejon Air Base, Master Sgt. Cliff Washington said.
   Ms. Washington said the crash killed 1st Lt. Daniel R. Johnson,
25, of Wayzata, Minn., while the pilot of the other single-seat jet,
Capt. Steven Kempf, 27, of Glendale, Ariz., escaped unharmed.
   Both aircraft belonged to the U.S. 401st Tactical Air Wing
squadron, which is part of the U.S. 16th Air Force headquartered at
Torrejon.
   The accident was the first involving the top-of-the-line U.S.
fighter jet since Dec. 5, when the crash of an F-16 on a routine
mission killed the commander of the 16th Air Force, Gen. Winfield S.
Harpe.
   Seven Torrejon-based U.S. F-16 jets have crashed since 1984,
killing three American pilots, according to base records.
   The 72 F-16s in the 401st are to be transferred to a base in
Crotone, Italy, within three years under the terms of a new
eight-year defense agreement signed in December by Spain and the
United States.
</TEXT>
