<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Elections     03-15 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Elections,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Likud Edges Out Labor in Local Polling Runoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc cemented its domination of Israeli local government by
defeating the rival Labor Party in 11 election runoffs.
   Results published today also showed a victory for Islamic
fundamentalists who wrested control of two more local councils in
Arab villages from popular non-religious parties.
   The runoffs were held Tuesday in 27 townships and cities where
candidates failed to win a minimum of 40 percent of vote in local
elections held Feb. 28.
   The Likud's gains mean the party now controls 44 townships, as
compared to only 26 in 1983 elections. The left-leaning Labor Party
won eight councils Tuesday, bringing its total to 32, a significant
decline from 54 in 1983.
   Shamir has said the results represent a vote of confidence for
Likud's policy of rejecting territorial concessions or any dialogue
with the PLO. Labor has said local issues had an effect on the
outcomes.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, who is in Washington to discuss
Middle East peace prospects with American leaders, telephoned his
party headquarters in Tel Aviv to praise their victory, Israeli
radio stations reported.
   ``This is a continuation of the Likud's big achievements,'' Arens
was quoted as saying.
   Boaz Shapira, a political science professor at Tel Aviv
University said the polling results indicated ``a new tendency, an
upheaval.
   ``The Likud is now adding local government to its control of
central government,'' he said on Army radio.
   Labor leaders did not concede defeat, however, and voiced
satisfaction over winning tight races in two key traditional Likud
strongholds: the Tel Aviv suburb of Rehovot and Beit Shemesh on the
outskirts of Jerusalem.
   ``We have won proof that we are capable of beating the Likud,''
Labor secretary general Micha Harish said on the radio.
   ``Whoever was eulogizing the Labor Party was making a big
mistake,'' Labor's leader and Finance Minister Shimon Peres was
quoted by the radio as saying.
   Islamic fundamentalists, meanwhile, emerged victorious in the
Arab villages of Rahad and Jaljoulya. The fundamentalists' success
has sparked concern among Israeli officials who fear a rise of Arab
nationalism among Israeli Arabs.
</TEXT>
