<FIRST>r a PM-Semiautomatic-Reax     03-15 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Semiautomatic-Reax,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Praise For Federal Ban in Import of Assault Weapons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Semiautomatic Weapons, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in California praised a new federal import ban on
semiautomatic weapons, but some gun store owners predicted it will
whet the public's appetite for the firearms.
   ``I can't stop shaking from the excitement,'' said state
Assemblyman Michael Roos of Los Angeles, author of a bill approved
Monday by the California Assembly that would virtually ban the sale
of of more than 40 types of semiautomatic assault weapons.
   ``Not in my wildest imagination would I have ever dreamed that
within 24 hours of the Assembly taking action that the United States
government ... would effectively ban the importation of these
weapons.''
   The Bush administration order issued Tuesday suspends the
importation of more than 110,000 assault-type weapons for which
import applications are pending, said national drug control director
William J. Bennett.
   Affected by the decision are imports of AK-47s, Uzi carbines,
FN-FAL and FN-FNC-type weapons as well as Steyr Aug semiautomatic
weapons.
   On Jan. 17, a disturbed drifter, Patrick Purdy, used an AK-47 to
kill five children and wound 30 other people at a Stockton, Calif.,
elementary school.
   Using the weapon, which allows the shooter to fire single shots
as quickly as he can pull the trigger, Purdy was able to fire 106
bullets in two minutes. He then shot and killed himself with a
handgun.
   A rising death toll from the use of semiautomatic weapons in gang
warfare had already prompted an outcry against the guns. But the
Stockton tragedy crystallized opposition and led to a nationwide
movement to ban assault weapons.
   The weapons have already been banned by ordinances in Los Angeles
and Cleveland.
   ``This is great news. Today's action is long overdue and I urge
the administration to make it permanent,'' California Attorney
General John Van De Kamp said of the federal import ban. ``I
strongly encourage the president and the Congress to follow
California's lead and enact legislation to permanently ban assault
weapons.''
   Van De Kamp said he thought the Stockton shootings and the
Legislature's move to restrict assault weapons in California ``have
had a tremendous impact on the administration's thinking on this
issue.''
   Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl F. Gates called the import ban ``a
step in the right direction.''
   The Bush administration's action Tuesday also brought praise from
Robert Strang, a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement Administration
in New York.
   ``Certainly, anything that's done is helpful to us,'' Strang
said. ``In the last year, agents across the country have been issued
submachine guns because of the automatic weapons that we're up
against on a daily basis. ... Certainly, anything we can do to
lessen the firepower of the drug traffickers is going to be
beneficial to us.''
   But in Dallas, some gun store owners predicted the ban on
imported assault rifles will increase weapons sales.
   ``I'll probably have 200 calls tomorrow,'' said Charles Zuber,
owner of Guns Unlimited. ``Anytime you tell people they can't have
something, they want to have it.''
</TEXT>
