<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Abbey     03-15 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Abbey,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author Edward Abbey Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TCS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Edward Abbey was remembered upon his
death as an ardent environmentalist whose writings decried paved
roads and billboards in the desert Southwest.
   The man dubbed ``the Thoreau of the American West'' by ``Lonesome
Dove'' author Larry McMurtry died Tuesday at age 62 at his home of
internal bleeding, said Jack Macrae, a friend who is editor-in-chief
of Henry Holt and Co.
   Abbey wrote 19 books, fiction and non-fiction, including the 1975
novel ``The Monkey Wrench Gang,'' a story of radical
environmentalists who plot the destruction of Glen Canyon Dam in
northern Arizona. Two of his books were made into movies: ``The
Brave Cowboy,'' from which came the 1962 Western, ``Lonely are the
Brave,'' starring Kirk Douglas, and ``Fire on the Mountain'' in 1981.
   Former Interior Secretary Stewart Udall said Abbey ``became a
courageous and outspoken advocate of environmental values through
his writing and I believe he's one of the Westerners who has left a
lasting legacy.''
   A transplanted Pennsylvanian, Abbey first came West in 1944. He
lived in Tucson since the early 1970s.
   Macrae's company published Abbey's most recent book, ``The Fool's
Progress,'' a novel detailing the travels of an introspective man.
   Abbey called the work his ``fat masterpiece,'' Macrae said.
   The author dreamed of returning the West to a pristine setting,
and bemoaned its adulteration by the cement and asphalt of
civilization.
   ``I'd like to see the whole American West made into a
wilderness,'' he said in a 1987 interview with The Associated Press.
   He once said there was nothing wrong with throwing beer cans out
car windows since paved roads were abominations and unworthy of
respect.
   His writings have been credited by founders of Earth First!, a
no-compromise environmental group, with crystallizing their
philosophy.
   Abbey resisted descriptions of himself as an environmentalist or
naturalist. ``If a label is required,'' he wrote, ``say that I am
one who loves the unfenced country.''
   His works included ``Desert Solitaire,'' ``Beyond the Wall:
Essays from the Outside,'' ``The Journey Home: Some Words in Defense
of the American West'' and ``One Life at a Time, Please.''
   His agent, Don Congdon, said Abbey had been finishing a sequel to
``The Monkey Wrench Gang'' called ``Hayduke Lives!'' He said the
book could be published in 1990.
   Abbey taught in the creative writing program at the University of
Arizona.
   He attended the University of New Mexico, worked part time as a
park ranger and firefighter, and as a writer and a radical.
   Besides his wife, Clarke, Abbey is survived by three sons, two
daughters and his father, Paul Revere Abbey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0084 </DOCNO>
