<FIRST>r a PM-InmateDeath     03-15 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Death,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate To Testify In Murder Trial Killed, Mistrial Declared</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 10th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state prison inmate scheduled to
testify as a defense witness in the murder trial of another prisoner
was bludgeoned to death with an iron bedpost, officials said.
   A judge immediately declared a mistrial in the trial of William
``Red'' Snyder, who is charged with murder in the stabbing death of
another inmate during a Jan. 1, 1986, riot at the state prison at
Moundsville.
   Randy Gossett, a lawyer who had subpoenaed John Gideon Perry and
12 other inmates to testify Tuesday, had interviewed the men at the
Harrison County Jail shortly before Perry was killed.
   ``They slapped each other on the back. They shook hands. They
were all here to testify for my client,'' said Gossett, who is
representing Snyder.
   Authorities notified him of Perry's death about 90 minutes later.
   Harrison County Circuit Judge Daniel McCarthy granted Gossett's
request for a mistrial because of Perry's killing.
   ``We asked for a mistrial ... over concerns for our own safety,''
Gossett said. ``How do you go down and talk to a group of people who
just murdered somebody and have a meaningful conversation?''
   Marshall County Assistant Prosecuting Attorney Jeffrey Kessler
said he was unsure whether he would ask for a new trial, saying,
``What's the use?''
   Snyder already is serving a life sentence without parole for
another murder conviction. The trial was moved to Harrison County
because of pretrial publicity in Marshall County.
   ``They all backed Perry into a corner and just beat his brains
out,'' said Gossett in an interview outside the jail. ``They used a
frame from an iron bed.''
   A doctor at the scene said Perry suffered severe head injuries in
the beating. No charges have been filed in Perry's death.
   Perry, 39, was acquitted in January of a murder charge in the
1986 slaying of inmate Danny Lehman, who was stabbed to death in the
prison's notorious, maximum-security North Hall.
   Prosecutors said Perry headed a prison gang called the Aryan
Brotherhood and said Lehman was the head of a rival gang named the
Avengers.
   Snyder, who went on trial Monday in Harrison County Circuit
Court, was accused in the death of state prison inmate Kent Slie,
who was stabbed 18 times during the 1986 uprising.
</TEXT>
