<FIRST>r a PM-TelephonePlea     03-15 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telephone Plea,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Inmate Pleads Guilty Over Phone To U.S. Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what legal authorities called the nation's
first international telephone plea, a federal judge heard a prison
inmate in Canada plead guilty to drug charges.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise sat at the head of a
conference table in his chambers Tuesday as Claude Tremblay admitted
participating in a northern New Jersey-based drug ring prosecuted in
1982.
   Defense attorneys, the prosecutor, news reporters and the court
reporter listened to Tremblay's voice over a loudspeaker.
   Tremblay spoke from Archambault prison near Montreal, where he is
serving a seven-year jail term for an unrelated armed robbery.
Debevoise sentenced him to five years' probation.
   ``I haven't heard of a guilty plea by phone,'' said David
Sellers, a spokesman for the federal Administrative Office of the
Courts in Washington.
   ``There's a whole wave, a big push, to be innovative in a
technological sense'' among courts, he said. A number of state
courts arraign defendants by phone, and in some courts, lawyers are
allowed to file lawsuits by facsimile, Sellers said.
   Arguments on pretrial motions or emergency search warrant
applications are more examples of telephone use by the courts, said
Lloyd Weinreb, a professor at Harvard Law School.
   Weinreb said a phone plea is ``not something I'm aware of but it
doesn't strike me as very remarkable.''
   The long-distance hearing took 1{ years to arrange and needed
approval from the U.S. State and Justice departments, Debevoise and
Canadian authorities, said attorneys in the case.
   ``After the initial chuckle, everybody said there's nothing that
says you can't do it,'' said Michael V. Gilberti, senior trial
attorney in the U.S. attorney's office who arranged the plea.
   As part of the plea, the government agreed not to pursue
additional charges, if any, against Tremblay, 50, in exchange for
his guilty plea to a drug conspiracy. Tremblay was indicted in
November 1982 with 21 other people in a large-scale drug operation
that distributed cocaine, amphetamines and Quaaludes.
   Tremblay admitted helping supply the group with Quaaludes.
According to the Probation Department, all but two of the other
defendants pleaded guilty. One is a fugitive and the other had
charges dismissed.
   Tremblay, a Montreal-born former construction worker, was
arrested on a New Jersey warrant in Canada in January 1985. A month
later, Canadian authorities implicated him in a 1984 armored car
heist in Ottawa. He pleaded guilty to that charge and went to jail
in 1987.
   In a plea agreement dated Sept. 4, 1987, Tremblay agreed to waive
his right to be present before a judge and to submit himself to the
jurisdiction of federal court in New Jersey. He also agreed not to
fight extradition. In turn, the government said it wouldn't oppose a
request by Tremblay to serve a prison term on the drug charge in
Canada.
   Defense attorney John Iannuzzi, who specializes in defending
people in Canada charged with crimes in the United States, sees a
future for such phone pleas.
   ``If we can get to the point where we can eliminate extra expense
and avoid getting people here from all over the world, it would
certainly expedite the system of justice,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
