<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against all major foreign
currencies except the British pound and Canadian dollar today in
Europe ahead of the release of U.S. trade figures for January. Gold
prices eased.
   Foreign currency dealers said they expect the trade figures to
show a narrowing of December's $10.2 billion deficit and lift the
market from its week-long doldrums.
   ``Sentiment is in favor of the dollar and most expect the dollar
to be bid higher,'' said one dealer in Rome.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.04 yen to a closing 129.88. Later, in London, it
was quoted higher at 130.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8635 West German marks, up from 1.8630
   _1.5980 Swiss francs, up from 1.5935
   _6.3150 French francs, up from 6.3125
   _2.1015 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1010
   _1,366.90 Italian lire, up from 1,366.125
   _1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1970
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7250, more expensive for
buyers than late Tuesday's $1.7170.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $394.40 a troy ounce,
down from $395.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $394.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $394.55, down from $395.25 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 54 cents to close at a bid
$395.91.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.15 a troy ounce,
down from Tuesday's $6.17.
