<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-15 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Whip Midwest with Snow, Thunderstorms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful storm buffeted the nation's midsection this morning,
dumping more than a foot of snow in upper Michigan and driving
thunderstorms and gale-force winds through Indiana and Ohio.
   Snow and high winds prevailed in the upper Great Lakes and upper
Mississippi Valley. Accumulations ranged up to 16 inches at
Wakefield, Mich., by late Tuesday, 10 inches at Eau Claire, Wis.,
and 7 inches at Minneapolis.
   A winter storm warning remained in effect this morning for
eastern upper Michigan and northern lower Michigan. Snowfall totals
in western upper Michigan may approach 2 feet.
   Strong winds circulating around the storm's powerful low pressure
center kicked up dust in the central Plains, sharply reducing
visibility and closing some roads in western Kansas Tuesday.
   Gale warnings were in effect for Lake Huron and Lake Erie, and
winds in central Indiana gusted to 64 mph at Marshall.
   Severe thunderstorms developed ahead of the storm, producing
large hail and damaging winds from Illinois to Ohio.
   In Indiana, golf ball-size hail was reported at Walkerton and
Columbus. Thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph at Detroit and
Cincinnati and reached 62 mph at Durand, Mich.
   Rain fell over the Middle Atlantic States, the lower Great Lakes
and the northern Pacific Coast.
   Snow fell in parts of Idaho, reducing visibilities to near zero
in the north-central part of the state.
   Today's forecast called for showers and some thunderstorms in the
southern and central Appalachians, rain in the upper Ohio Valley
across New York state and into New England, and rain in much of the
Pacific Northwest. Scattered snow was forecast from the northern
Rockies across North Dakota into much of the upper Great Lakes.
Winds were expected to be strong and gusty from the upper Ohio
Valley into the central Appalachians.
   Highs were expected to be in the teens and 20s from eastern
Montana across North Dakota, eastern South Dakota and the upper
Mississippi Valley to the northern part of the upper Great Lakes;
the 30s and 40s from Washington state to the northern Rockies, the
central Plains, the middle Mississippi Valley and the rest of the
Great Lakes; the 70s and 80s from Southern California across
southern Arizona and New Mexico, most of Texas, the Gulf Coast,
Florida and the southern and middle Atlantic Coast. The remainder of
the nation were expected to have highs in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8 degrees below zero at
Warroad, Minn., to 73 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 66 partly cloudy; Boston 43 foggy; Buffalo 56
rain; Charleston, S.C. 60 foggy; Cincinnati 56 fair; Cleveland 59
cloudy; Detroit 53 windy; Miami 69 fair; New York 44 drizzle;
Philadelphia 46 foggy; Pittsburgh 57 windy; Portland, Maine 38
drizzle; Washington 47 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 16 cloudy; Chicago 37 windy; Dallas-Fort Worth
58 dust; Denver 29 fair; Des Moines 22 windy; Indianapolis 44
blowing dust; Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 14 partly
cloudy; Nashville 70 partly cloudy; New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis
37 windy.
   _West: Albuquerque 43 partly cloudy; Anchorage 21 fair; Las Vegas
53 fair; Los Angeles 55 foggy; Phoenix 67 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 33 partly cloudy; San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 49 fair;
Seattle 40 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 43 rain; Toronto 55 rain.
