<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-O'Hara     03-15 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-O'Hara,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longtime Suburban Detroit Congressman Dies at 63</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James G. O'Hara, a Democratic congressman from
suburban Detroit from 1958 to 1976, has died at George Washington
University Medical Center. He was 63.
   O'Hara, who had lung cancer, was a lobbyist and attorney with the
law firm of Patton, Boggs &amp; Blow when he died Monday. He joined the
firm in Washington in 1976 after losing the U.S. Senate primary
election to Sen. Donald Riegle.
   He first won election to the House by five votes after two
recounts, becoming the first Democrat to represent the Thumb region
north of Detroit in Congress since 1895.
   O'Hara pursued a generally liberal, pro-labor agenda, said Macomb
County Circuit Judge John Bruff, the congressman's campaign manager
and district representative.
   ``His slogan for his first campaign was `For Full Employment,'''
Bruff said Tuesday. ``He also was one of the congressional
architects of the Great Society programs, Medicaid, Medicare, the
civil rights bills ... the Clean Air Act, the Clean Water Act.''
   O'Hara moved from Washington to Detroit when he was 13. He earned
bachelor's and law degrees from the University of Michigan after
serving as a combat paratrooper during World War II. O'Hara
practiced law in Detroit before joining Congress.
   Survivors include his wife, Susan, five sons and two daughters.
</TEXT>
