<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-ZoBell     03-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-ZoBell,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Claude ZoBell, Pioneering Marine Researcher, Dead at 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claude Ephraim ZoBell, a scientist who
discovered living organisms at extreme ocean depths and was known as
the father of marine microbiology, has died of cardiac arrest. He
was 84.
   ZoBell, who died Monday at Scripps Memorial Hospital, is credited
with discovering 65 species of ocean bacteria. He also was noted for
discoveries on how microorganisms affect the formation and
transformation of petroleum.
   ``Claude ZoBell's contributions to marine biology and the ecology
of the oceans is acclaimed worldwide, but less known was his devoted
service to the scientific community,'' said Edward Frieman, director
of Scripps Institution of Oceanography at the University of
California, San Diego.
   ``His leadership in the field of marine microbiology drew many
researchers from all over the world to his laboratory, and his
generosity in directing younger scientists will last for many years
into the future.''
   ZoBell, a professor emeritus at Scripps since 1972, was the first
researcher to recover and cultivate living organisms from ocean
depths greater than 20,000 feet, said George Somero, chairman of the
Marine Biology Research Division of Scripps Institution.
   ``Claude ZoBell's discoveries that microbial life is possible in
such extreme habitats as the deep sea opened entirely new vistas for
later generations of microbiologists,'' Somero said.
   King Frederick IX of Denmark awarded ZoBell the Galathea Medal in
1952 for successfully recovering living bacteria from more than
34,000 feet of water in the Mindanao Trench near the Philippines.
   ZoBell joined the Scripps Institution in 1932 as an instructor.
His early research included studies of how bacteria helps create oil
in marine sediments.
   His discovery that bacteria can cause oil to separate from
sediments won a patent for the process in 1947, which ZoBell
assigned to the American Petroleum Institute for free public use.
His research has shed much light on how microbial action affects oil
spills, Frieman said.
   An author who published nearly 300 scientific papers and one
textbook, ZoBell founded the international Geomicrobiology Journal
in 1976 and served as its editor until 1981.
   ZoBell was born in Provo, Utah, and earned bachelor's and
master's degrees in bacteriology from Utah State University in
Logan. He received his doctorate from the University of California
at Berkeley in 1931.
   Survivors include his wife of 42 years and a fellow
microbiologist, Jean, who worked with ZoBell on many of his
projects; two sons, 11 grandchildren and 12 greatgrandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     03-15 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Clash With Riot Police In Three Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students fought
riot police with clubs, firebombs and rocks in three cities today
and announced a nationwide campaign to defeat President Roh Tae-woo
in an upcoming referendum.
   The student councils of 38 colleges and universities in Seoul
said they would launch anti-government protests to overthrow Roh's
government in alliance with dissident political groups.
   About 700 students, shouting ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'', battled
riot police who responded with tear gas for an hour outside the main
gate of Seoul's Sejong University. No arrests or injuries were
reported.
   Fighting also broke out at Dankuk University in southern Seoul
where about 500 students, demanding Roh's resignation and a halt to
joint U.S.-South Korea military exercises now being held, tried to
march into the streets.
   Police fired tear gas to disperse the protesters after a two-hour
battle.
   In the central city of Taejon, about 1,000 students, hurling
firebombs and rocks, battled riot police who retaliated with tear
gas, news reports said. The protesters shouted slogans against Roh
and his government.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, the South Korean news agency
Yonhap reported, about 5,000 students held an anti-Roh rally and
vowed to defeat the president in the referendum, which is expected
to be held next month.
   Roh said in a 1987 campaign pledge that he would seek a midterm
appraisal of his performance after the Seoul Olympics, which ended
last October. Under pressure from the opposition, he said last week
that he would fulfill the pledge by holding a referendum.
   Roh has said that in the referendum people would be simply asked
to assess the progress of democratic reforms he has introduced since
his inauguration 13 months ago.
   May people think the reforms, which have included greater press
freedom, are insufficient.
</TEXT>
