<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Crash     03-15 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Crash,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inquiry Blames Weather for Crash of Fighter Prototype</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government inquiry said today sudden
weather changes and problems with the flight control system caused
the crash of the first JAS 39 Gripen, Sweden's new combat plane.
   The Feb. 2 crash came at a time when the government already was
reconsidering the $5.5 billion plane _ the country's biggest defense
project _ because of delays and escalating costs. The pilot suffered
a broken arm.
   The industrial Group JAS, a consortium of Swedish companies, is
under contract to start deliveries to the air force in 1992. The
jets will replace aging Viggen planes.
   Rune Lundin, a member of the commission that investigated the
crash, told a news conference the prototype was known to have an
oversensitive flight control system, which is regulated by computers.
   He said computer software had not been adjusted before the crash
but that test pilots were instructed to compensate for the
sensitivity with the control stick.
   However, the weather worsened during flight, with winds exceeding
the approved limit. The commission said gusts of wind reached 28 mph
instead of 22 mph as predicted.
   Defense Minister Roine Carlsson said he was waiting for a more
extensive inquiry, due by the end of May, before he would comment on
the future of the project.
</TEXT>
