<SECOND>PM-People-Atwater,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Find the Republican in the Band'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This first ran for Wednesday AMs and is now available for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``This would be a good quiz,'' David Letterman
said at the top of his show. ``Find the Republican in the band.''
   It wasn't hard to find the button-down cat in back in the blue
blazer and red tie wailing out on ``Soul Man'' _ Lee Atwater,
Republican Party chairman and rock-blues guitar player.
   Atwater was the musical guest Tuesday night on NBC's ``Late Night
with David Letterman,'' sitting in with Paul Shaffer and the World's
Most Dangerous Band.
   ``Any musician in America would give their right arm to play with
this band,'' Atwater said after the taping. ``Paul's band is the
most respected band in the country. It's a musician's band.''
   ``That's a non-partisan comment,'' added Shaffer.
   ``Well, music is non-partisan,'' said Atwater. ``Music and
musicians are a world in their own, so there was no politics here
tonight, just good music.''
   Maybe just a little bit of politics. While Atwater stood in the
background, Letterman delivered his monologue, including one last
joke on John Tower, whose nomination as secretary of defense was
rejected last week by the Senate.
   ``Does (President) George Bush know you're here?'' Letterman
asked Atwater.
   ``Of course,'' said Atwater.
   ``Does he mind?'' queried Letterman.
   ``That's another question,'' replied Atwater.
   It wasn't Atwater's first big gig. On Jan. 21, he helped put a
hard-rocking finish to a weekend of inaugural parties by jamming
with a stage full of rock 'n' roll legends, including Ron Wood, Sam
Moore and Joe Cocker.
   On Tuesday night, Atwater was billed after Chevy Chase, Rita
Rudner and Caren Callahan, the national championship grocery bagger.
And, he was almost eclipsed by the shrieks emitted by the
participants of Exotic Bird Night in the Control Room.
   But, ``The cat can groove, if you want a quote, that's my
quote,'' Shaffer pronounced after the show.
   Shaffer said a couple of the show's writers who had seen Atwater
play thought it would be ``a hip idea'' to have him on.
   Atwater said he did not regret going into politics instead of
music.
   ``I'd be at the Holiday Inn making $65 a night still, A, and B,
I'd have never made it here on this stage if I'd-a stuck with
music.''
   ``I don't know about that,'' said Shaffer.
</TEXT>
