<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     03-15 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Establish New West Bank Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers moved tractors and mobile homes
to a West Bank hilltop today, starting the first new settlement in
the occupied territories since the November elections.
   The settlement started the same day that Israel withdrew from the
Red Sea resort of Taba, handing sovereignty over to Egypt after
seven years of squabbling.
   Uri Ariel, head of the West Bank settlement council, said the
West Bank construction work was Israel's response to the withdrawal
from Taba.
   ``It's a good start that we are building a settlement in the land
of Israel,'' Ariel said on Israel radio. ``Maybe it's also a special
day when they are folding the (Israeli) flag in Taba.''
   However, there was opposition to the settlement in Israel's
divided government.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, three Palestinians, including a
9-year-old boy, were shot and wounded in clashes with Israeli
troops, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was checking
the report.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, the army arrested Palestinians
suspected of killing two Palestinian hospital workers who cooperated
with Israel, an army spokesman said. He identified the leader of the
hit squad as a member of Fatah, the mainstream PLO faction headed by
Yasser Arafat.
   During house searches, troops confiscated a submachine gun, seven
handguns and a typewriter used to write threatening letters to
people who allegedly collaborate with the occupation government, the
spokesman said.
   Israeli officials have said attacks by Palestinians against
collaborators are in violation of Arafat's pledge that the Palestine
Liberation Organization has abandoned terror.
   At least 396 Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed since
the Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
territories broke out Dec. 8, 1987.
   Tractors today plowed a hilltop northwest of the West Bank town
of Ramallah to prepare the proposed settlement of Talmon, said
Yehuda Hasani, a settler spokesman.
   Three mobile homes later moved to the site despite heavy rain,
hail and fog. Hasani said 15 families were expected to move to
Talmon within a few days.
   Ariel said settlers had received all necessary government permits
to build the settlement.
   The government, a coalition of the right-wing Likud bloc and the
left-leaning Labor Party, has authorized the construction of eight
settlements during its four-year term, which expires in 1992. The
settlements include Talmon.
   Housing Ministry spokesman Amos Hadad said about 80,000 Jewish
settlers live in 103 settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
About 1.7 million Palestinians live in the territories, which Israel
took from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The last settlement was started just before the Parliament
elections in November 1988.
</TEXT>
