<FIRST>r a PM-TortureTrial     03-15 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Torture Trial,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Torture Tape Brings Tears From Juror, Defendant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents. Trial to resume at 10 a.m. EST.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tape-recorded account of a teen-ager's
torture, murder and mutilation brought tears from a juror and sobs
from the killer.
   ``I can't. Stop,'' John R. Weber, 25, of Phillips, said halfway
through Tuesday's playing of the tape that he told authorities he
made to scare his wife.
   The outburst prompted Judge Gary Carlson to order one of several
brief recesses in the sanity phase of Weber's trial, which was to
continue today.
   The jury is considering whether Weber was sane and can be held
responsible for the 1986 slaying of Carla Lenz, his 17-year-old
sister-in-law, and the attempted murder of his wife on Sept. 3.
   Weber put his hands over his ears and sobbed Tuesday as the
cassette tape that investigators found in his car was played for the
jury.
   When the male voice on the tape described cutting the calf off
the dead girl and later eating it, a juror put her hand to her mouth
and began crying. The judge called an immediate recess and the jury
left the courtroom.
   The jury had heard an edited version of the tape, without
references to cannibalism and a feeling of being two persons, during
the first part of the trial. At that time, Weber was not in the
courtroom, and the jurors sat expressionless.
   Weber was convicted Monday of mutilating and sexually assaulting
Miss Lenz. He had pleaded guilty to murdering the teen-ager and
attempting to murder his wife. But he also pleaded innocent by
reason of mental disease or defect to all charges.
   Defense attorney John Reid told the jury he wanted them to hear
the whole tape ``as difficult as that is'' so they could better
judge Weber's mind.
   If a jury decides Weber could not control his actions because of
mental illness, he will be committed for treatment, with any
possible release to be determined by a court.
   If he is found sane, he will be sent to prison, where he faces a
maximum sentence of life plus more than 250 years.
   The defense described Weber as a loner and bedwetter whose
problems were diagnosed by two psychiatrists as a disorder of sexual
sadism.
   Weber was accused of torturing Miss Lenz with a lighted
cigarette, pins and wooden wheelbarrow handles. He was accused of
using a lighted cigar, safety pin and wheelbarrow handle to assault
his 22-year-old wife before beating her with a shovel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
