<FIRST>r a PM-FalseArrestTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0523 03-15 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-False Arrest Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Transit Cops Convicted of Series of False Arrests on Subway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to ADD motive for false arrests; PICKS
UP 7th graf pvs, ``It's really ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Transit Authority police officers face up to
71 years in prison each for arresting people on trumped-up charges
on the subways.
   A federal jury Tuesday convicted Officers Alphonse Iannacone, 42,
an 18-year veteran, and Mary McDermott, 32, a member of the force
since 1980, of conspiracy and deprivation of civil rights after
three days of deliberations.
   Shouts of ``Oh no!'' and ``How could they do this?'' came from
sobbing spectators, including the officers' mothers, as the verdict
was read.
   Sentencing was set for May 10.
   The charges stemmed from a series of arrests the officers made in
1983 and 1984 while on plainclothes duty.
   Prosecutors said the officers were trying to improve their arrest
records to advance their careers. Defense attorneys said the
officers had no motive to fabricate crimes, since thousands of real
thefts and assaults occur in the subways every year.
   ``It's really hard for a police officer to get a fair trial,''
said defense attorney Barry Agulnick. He and the other defense
lawyer, Kenneth Kaplan, said they would appeal.
   Federal prosecutors called more than 20 witnesses, including the
eight men arrested by Iannacone and McDermott and the eight
``victims'' of the men.
   The men _ all of whom were black, Hispanic or Asian _ described
how they were taken off subway trains, arrested, handcuffed and
detained on charges of either sexual abuse or attempted grand
larceny.
   The alleged victims _ seven women and one man _ described their
shock when they learned they were listed as the complainants in the
cases against the men. The women said they had not sought police
assistance and had not felt anyone touching them in a lewd way. The
man said he was not a pickpocket victim.
   The defense called just two witnesses. A transit police
lieutenant explained that discrepancies between arresting officers'
notes and those of the prosecutor are not uncommon.
   A clinical psychologist testified that victims of sex abuse often
deny it occurred.
   Transit Police Chief Vincent Del Castillo said in a statement,
``While we can never be pleased by the conviction of any police
officers, we are pleased that this old and lingering issue has
finally been resolved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Whip 1stLd-Writethru a0521 03-15 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Whip, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0521,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Claims To Have 70 Of 88 Votes Needed For House GOP Whip
Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; Subs graf 2, Gingrich a six-term, to CORRECT majority whip to
minority whip.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, a conservative Republican
known for his ethics campaign against House Speaker Jim Wright, is
claiming the front-runner's position in the intra-party battle for
the No. 2 spot in the House GOP leadership.
   Gingrich, a six-term Georgia congressman, said Tuesday he has
commitments from 70 House Republicans for the minority whip position
and another 22 have indicated they're leaning in his direction.
   ``We're gaining ground,'' said Gingrich, who said he has talked
with more than 100 Republican congressmen since Friday, when
President Bush nominated the current GOP whip, Rep. Dick Cheney of
Wyoming, for secretary of defense.
   Provided that Cheney is confirmed by the Senate for the defense
post, his successor as whip will be chosen by the 175 House
Republicans.
   Gingrich and Rep. Ed Madigan, R-Ill., are the only announced
candidates. Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., chairman of the House
Republican Conference, the No. 3 GOP leadership spot, also has
considered entering the race.
   Madigan, in a letter sent Monday to his GOP colleagues, said he
would ``maximize cooperation'' with Minority Leader Robert Michel,
R-Ill., and help President Bush press his legislative agenda.
   Gingrich, leader of a band of several dozen arch-conservatives,
has been the chief accuser of Wright over several alleged ethics
violations.
   Gingrich said Tuesday he was running a ``positive campaign'' and
added, ``It is my intention to be the whip who works with Bob Michel
and who works to make Bob Michel speaker.''
</TEXT>
