<HEAD>No Charges To Be Filed in Cyanide Yogurt Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has decided to bring no criminal
charges in the cyanide-poisoning death of a teen-ager, the
prosecutor's office says
   The panel found ``nobody culpable at this point,'' George Kerns,
a spokesman for Camden County Prosecutor Samuel Asbell, said
Tuesday. ``As far as we're concerned, it's finished.''
   The panel began hearing testimony last month to determine whether
Thomas Lee, 17, of Haddonfield, died as a result of random product
tampering, homicide or suicide. Law officers have said evidence
pointed strongly toward suicide.
   Lee lapsed into a coma Jan. 3 after eating cyanide-laced Breyer's
black cherry yogurt. He died Feb. 7 after being removed from
life-support equipment.
   The grand jury heard from 20 witnesses, including the youth's
classmates, medical experts, a homicide investigator and the
teen-ager's parents, Hsin-Yi and Frances Lee, who testified
voluntarily before the panel Tuesday.
   The panel did not present a formal report of its findings, Kerns
said.
   Dennis Wixted, first assistant county prosecutor, said the panel
reached several conclusions, which he would not discuss.
</TEXT>
