<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Raid 1stLd-Writethru a0551 03-15 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Raid, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0551,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Guerrillas From Egypt Captured in Cross-border Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Mordechai claiming Arafat had
knowledge of attack, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-age Arab guerrillas crossed the
Egyptian border today and attacked an Israeli military outpost in
the occupied Gaza Strip with rifles and hand grenades, the army
said. The guerrillas were captured and wounded.
   A military source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the 3
a.m. attack failed when a grenade hurled at the Israeli camp rolled
back onto the guerrillas' position and exploded, injuring the two
Arabs. Soldiers opened fire after hearing an explosion.
   No Israeli soldiers were hurt. The attack came on the day Israel
withdrew from the Red Sea resort of Taba and handed sovereignty to
Egypt.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, head of Israel's southern command,
said the guerrillas belong to a fundamentalist group known as Jihad
Islami, or Islamic Holy War.
   The guerrillas, aged 15 and 17, carried Soviet-made automatic
AK-47 rifles, a Swedish-made Karl Gustav submachine gun and six
Soviet F1 hand grenades, the army said. It said the teen-agers were
from the Canada Palestinian refugee camp in Egypt.
   Sources who demanded anonymity said a third person, perhaps
acting as a scout, slipped back across the border and avoided
capture.
   Mordechai said the attack was carried out with the knowledge of
PLO chief Yasser Arafat and his Fatah guerrillas.
   ``To the best of our knowledge, the ring was prepared and trained
in the Canada refugee camp in Egyptian Rafah and from there they
went with a scout to our territory,'' he said.
   ``According to the terrorists being questioned, the ring acted
and was sent by Jihad Islami. (They went) with the knowledge of
Fatah, and with the knowledge of Abu Ammar (Arafat).''
   Israel radio said the goal of the guerrillas was to kill
soldiers, take hostages and return to Egypt. The guerrillas were
promised $20,000 for making the attack, it claimed.
   The last infiltration from Egypt came on Dec. 29, when Israeli
soldiers shot and killed three men who crossed the border. It was
not known if the infiltrators were smugglers or guerrillas.
   In March 1988, three Palestinians crossed the Egyptian border and
hijacked a bus. They killed three Israeli civilians before they were
shot to death. The PLO's Force 17 unit claimed responsibility.
   Today's infiltration came amid reported efforts by U.S. officials
to work out a cease-fire between Israel and the Palestine Liberation
Organization to stop infiltrations from Lebanon.
   Army officials estimate about 30 guerrillas have been killed in
south Lebanon during infiltration attempts since the beginning of
the year.
   The United States has asked the PLO to halt such attacks. But the
PLO said attacks on military targets were not included when Arafat
renounced terrorism last December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
