<HEAD>Settlement Reached To Avert Philly Transit Stike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A last-minute settlement averted what would
have been the fifth transit strike in 12 years today for some
400,000 commuters.
   The Philadelphia-area transit authority and its biggest union
reached the tentative agreement Tuesday, minutes before the midnight
strike deadline.
   A walkout would have idled 5,200 union members who run
Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority buses, trolleys
and subways. SEPTA's regional rail lines would have continued
running with expanded routes.
   ``It was a tough, tough negotiation,'' SEPTA General Manager
Louis J. Gambaccini said. ``I would like to say that the union has
been admirable in its seriousness in its approach and we tried to
respect that.''
   Roger Tauss, president of Local 234 of the Transport Workers
Union, said he was very happy with the agreement.
   Gambaccini and Tauss refused to disclose terms of the agreement
until a union membership meeting today.
   But union officials who declined to be identified said the
three-year contract calls for a 16{ percent raise. The top hourly
wage is now $12.23.
   The agreement also calls for a pension increase and retains the
arrangement of SEPTA paying the entire cost of the workers'
health-care coverage, according to sources.
