<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     03-15 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Adopts Budget After Three-Month Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today passed the country's
budget for the 1989 fiscal year after a three-month dispute over the
size of defense expenditures, the official Tanjug news agency
reported.
   It said that because of inflation the federal budget of $3
billion was 165 percent higher than last year's figure. The
government says the annual inflation rate recently rose to a record
346 percent.
   Yugoslavia's federal budget covers only outlays on defense, aid
to underdeveloped regions, government salaries and retirement
benefits.
   All other expenditures are covered by the individual budgets of
the country's six member republics.
   The spending plan devotes $2 billion, or 4.9 percent of the gross
national product, for the military, Tanjug said. A proposal to spend
5.2 percent of the GNP on defense was defeated after it was opposed
by Slovenia, the nation's most liberal and economically developed
republic.
   The Communist Party in Slovenia and independent groups who want
the role of the army scaled down led the fight for a lower military
budget, saying defense spending was taking up too many scarce
resources.
</TEXT>
