<SECOND>PM-Undercover Taxi,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York City Tourists Being Ripped Off By Cab Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tourist arriving at Kennedy International
Airport has a 66 percent chance of being overcharged for a cab ride
into Manhattan, an undercover investigation by the Taxi and
Limousine Commission found.
   A dozen inspectors posed as tourists arriving at the airport on
evening flights March 6-10 and took cabs to a hotel in lower
Manhattan.
   In eight cases, the commission said Tuesday, the drivers took a
circuitous route that raised the usual fare of $29 to as much as
$40.75.
   The weeklong probe yielded 445 summonses for traffic violations,
fare refusals and overcharges.
   Eleven hack licenses, two meters and two taxi medallions were
confiscated and one driver was arrested for obstructing justice and
assaulting an officer.
   The inspectors found two taxis fitted with ``zappers'' that
secretly speed up the meter. The drivers' licenses were suspended
pending revocation hearings.
