<FIRST>r a PM-HinckleyBuzzards     03-15 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hinckley Buzzards,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buzzards Adhere To Tradition, Arrive Back At Hinckley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HINCKLEY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right on schedule, the buzzards returned to
Hinckley today, renewing a 150-year tradition.
   Three of the birds arrived at the town buzzard's roost at 6:32
a.m. with Metroparks Ranger Capt. Roger Lutz on hand to record the
event.
   Buzzard spotting each March 15 in Hinckley has become an annual
sign of spring in northeast Ohio.
   Lutz said a flock of about 80 buzzards migrates to the park in
the small town 20 miles from Cleveland. The migration route of the
scavenger birds remains a mystery.
   Legend has it the buzzards were first attracted to Hinckley in
1819 when a March thaw exposed the carcasses of predatory animals
that had been killed by residents the previous December during their
Great Hinckley Varmint Hunt.
</TEXT>
