<HEAD>Religious Paper Hopes Fish Will Hook New Readers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A religious weekly will include cans of sardines
in 6,000 copies to poke fun at the notion that newspapers are good
only for wrapping fish.
   The sardines will appear in some April 7 editions of Michigan
Catholic, the Archdiocese of Detroit paper, Editor Alfred Doblin
said Tuesday.
   ``I'm just using a commonly held belief and getting a little joke
out of it,'' said Doblin. ``I want to make people chuckle and break
through the barrier that this is an old stuffy paper. It's not
written by nuns.''
   Students at Sacred Heart Seminary will help stuff the cans into
the papers, which will be distributed free.
   ``It's a neat tie-in with the old concept of wrapping fish in
newspaper and with Catholics eating fish,'' said Jay Berman, an
archdiocese spokesman. ``I hope it works.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
