<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Chancery     03-15 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chancery,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Various Options Under Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is considering several
options on the future of the American Embassy chancery in Moscow, a
U.S. official said today, including razing it and building a new one.
   The chancery is said to be riddled with eavesdropping devices and
has not been used.
   Among the options, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, were:
   _ Razing the chancery and building a new one. That could cost an
estimated $500 million.
   _ Dismantling and rebuilding three stories and constructing an
annex for the most sensitive work, as suggested in a study by former
Defense Secretary James R. Schlesinger.
   _ Clearing the new embassy of eavesdropping devices, as
recommended by Anne Armstrong, head of former President Reagan's
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board.
   In the meantime, Nicholas M. Salgo, a former ambassador to
Hungary, was appointed last week to develop plans for facilities in
Moscow that meet U.S. security requirements.
   Salgo made similar studies in China, East Germany and Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
