<DOCNO> AP890315-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DogEaters     03-15 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dog Eaters,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Refugees Cleared of Animal Cruelty Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge dismissed animal cruelty
charges against two Cambodian refugees who admitted killing a
4-month-old German shepherd for food.
   ``Under the facts, I don't believe it can be said that these
defendants inflicted unreasonable pain on the animal,'' Municipal
Judge Bradford L. Andrews said Tuesday. ``To hold otherwise would
subject every slaughterhouse employee or farmer to prosecution.''
   Andrews had ruled last week that killing a dog for food was not
illegal unless the dog was ``maimed, wounded, tortured, mutilated or
tormented'' in a manner beyond that required to prepare it as food.
   ``I am sympathetic to the feelings of those who champion the
cause of animal rights,'' Andrews said, ``but the remedy lies in
convincing the Legislature to enact laws that would make the actions
of these defendants unlawful.''
   Sokheng Chea, 32, and Seng Ou, 33, both of Long Beach, said they
killed the puppy in June by holding the dog down on the kitchen
floor, hitting it over the head with a blunt instrument and slashing
its throat before they began skinning it.
   Police, alerted by a neighbor who heard the dog's yelps, arrested
the men. They were charged with misdemeanors.
   ``I am happy,'' Ou, speaking through an interpreter, said of
Tuesday's ruling, ``but I can assure you that there will be no
second time.''
   Local Asian leaders said that dogs and cats are considered
delicacies in some Southeast Asian countries.
   Local animal rights activists said they were disappointed by the
outcome.
   ``I think that what these defendants did offends the
sensibilities of the community,'' said Wendy Aragon. ``There is a
need for legislation to outlaw the slaughter of dogs and cats; they
are companion animals, not food animals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
