<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-15 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: terrorists understand.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 9
   Chicago Tribune on Bush's slow start:
   George Bush is beginning to disappoint people who expected him to
take the presidential baton from Ronald Reagan and keep the
governmental relay race going full tilt.
   Instead, he is taking his time, sizing up the stadium and
examining the condition of the track before turning on the speed.
   Trouble is, other things aren't standing still. ...
   Yet the new administration, which has been slow to fill
sub-Cabinet posts and in no rush to articulate its priorities, has
seemd content with followership rather than leadership, sounding
tough only in its defense of John Tower and in its opposition to new
taxes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 13
   Sun-Sentinel, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on Lee Atwater and Howard
University students:
   The GOP is eager to expand its appeal among minorities and the
Howard (University) administration appeared all too willing to
cooperate.
   (Lee) Atwater demonstrated his political acumen by withdrawing
before the incident could escalate into an even worse embarrassment
for his party and President George Bush.
   While the Republicans' effort to broaden their base is
commendable, it is difficult to feel much compassion for Atwater as
he keeps hitting sour notes in his attempt to play a new theme of
racial harmony after stirring up so much discord during the campaign.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 14
   Los Angeles Times on apartheid and religion:
   The white branch of the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa has
found apartheid a ``sin'' four years after officially rejecting the
concept of racial segregation, a finding that will at least postpone
a formal break with the larger black and mixed-race branches of the
church.
   But the white branch has once again shied away from agreement on
tactics, such as civil disobedience, that have been proposed to
accelerate the glacial progress away from apartheid. ...
   (But) disillusionment has followed so many official rejections of
apartheid. The rejections have not been matched by substantial
progress toward reform.
   Apartheid is officially opposed by the government of South Africa
and by most political forces. Only the far-right Conservative Party,
which advocates firm restoration of racial segregation, remains
firmly committed to apartheid.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 10
   The News-Review, Roseburg, Ore., on a youth service corps:
   A major test of whether a new social ethos is indeed emerging may
be the fate of proposals in Congress to establish a voluntary
national service. The concept is predicated on the belief that young
people can be motivated as much by altruism and civic obligation as
by the prospect of material gain. ...
   (Legislators) envision a corps of up to one million high school
graduates, age 18 to 26, who would volunteer to spend one or two
years performing community service, such as working in hospitals,
AIDS hospices, homeless shelters or child day-care centers.
   They would be paid only subsistence wages, about $100 a week. But
in exchange for their labors, they would be given education vouchers
worth $10,000 for each year of national service. ...
   The Citizens Corps would be ... a civilian GI Bill of Rights,
based on the sound premise of providing government benefits for
service rendered to the country.
   The idea dovetails nicely with George Bush's call to invigorate
``a thousand points of light'' in American society and at the same
time fosters a needed rebirth of American altruism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 8
   The Press, Atlantic City, N.J., on warring KKK factions:
   Pity the poor Ku Klux Kan. It has been defended many times over
the years, usually over its right to hold public rallies.
   Now the KKK wants lawyers to take its side once more. This time,
against the KKK.
   Richard Bondira, who calls himself the ``Grand Wizard'' of a
northern New Jersey chapter, says his group _ Invisible Empire,
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan _ is the real McCoy. Bondira says that
another group, which plans to hold a rally next month in Millville,
N.J., is an impostor. The other Klan group says that, no, it's the
real KKK.
   Bondira claims that he can't seem to find an attorney willing to
take his case. What a shame.
   It's a tribute to Americans ... when the Klan can have its day in
court ... without regard to its philosophy.
   Most Americans _ and most lawyers _ don't really give a hoot over
which group claims to be the real Ku Klux Klan. They wish both Klans
would simply go away. That's also a tribute of sorts.
</TEXT>
