<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   03-15 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: of sorts.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 11
   The Arizona Republic, Phoenix, on Soviet defense spending:
   According to the Soviet Union's published budget, the Kremlin's
defense spending this year will amount to about 20 billion rubles.
At the official rate of exchange, that is $10 billion, or $60
billion at the more realistic black market rate. The United States
defense budget approaches $300 billion.
   Thus Moscow's publicly declared defense budget is about one-tenth
of ours, but the Soviet Union maintains an army of 180 active
divisions compared with just 18 for the U.S. ...
   Writing in the current issue of Jane's Soviet Intelligence
Review, James Westwood notes that Moscow's defense budget seems
small because it includes only boots, gasoline, tires and the like
manpower costs and materials consumed in such operations as training
exercises and administration.
   Unlike the Pentagon's, the Soviet budget omits weapons
procurement, maintenance and repair, and research and development.
These military expenditures are integrated into the national ...
budget ... and made invisible. ...
   Understanding this Soviet peculiarity is important in trying to
assess Mikhail Gorbachev's new defense policy ``reasonable
sufficiency'' and his recent initiatives on troop and weapons
reduction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 12
   Roswell (N.M.) Daily Record on Lee Atwater and Howard University
students:
   A student mob barricaded in the administration building of
predominantly black Howard University has succeeded in driving
Republican National Committee chairman Lee Atwater from the school's
board of trustees.
   Specifically, the student protesters charged that President
Bush's Willie Horton campaign commercials on television were
intended to appeal to the racist fears of white voters.
   The racism allegation, which was first injected into the
presidential campaign by Gov. Michael Dukakis, Bush's Democratic
opponent, ignores the fact that Horton was never identified as black
in the GOP television commercials.
   People quick to accuse others of ``racism'' have another favorite
word for describing this affliction: ``Bigot.'' ...
   It's a term which aptly describes the view of the protesters who
hounded Atwater from the Howard University board because he is a
white Republican appointed to serve a black university.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 12
   The Reporter, Fond du Lac, Wis., on inmate release programs:
   The folly of letting loose on society known dangerous criminals
was proven again the other day _ and it was too close to home.
   Officials at Mendota Mental Health Institute in Madison (Wis.)
granted release time to a man who, police say, bought a shotgun,
stole a taxicab, slashed the driver with a knife and led officers on
a downtown chase.
   What's worse, this was the second time he had run amok.
   Paul J. Rasmussen was convicted of slaying a ... car salesman in
1974, while ... on conditional release from the old Central State
Hospital in Waupun. He was found innocent by reason of mental
disease or defect in the trial's second phase.
   Rasmussen was allowed to leave Mendota (March 7) to exercise at a
local health club and perform volunteer work at a church, where he
had worked for 2{ years. Police say he instead went on the rampage.
...
   President Bush made much of the Massachusetts early release
program in his campaign against Gov. Michael Dukakis and, we think,
quite ably showed then the folly of such tactics. It's too bad
Mendota officials did not heed his words.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 13
   The News &amp; Observer, Raleigh, N.C., on sports dreams:
   Poor youngsters have a tough time seeing the end of the tunnel
when they're told (to do) hard work in school. ... Flashy things
they do understand, like the sight of a professional basketball star
slamming the ball through the hoop. ...
   So the young people go for the flashy, believing that it is the
quickest and easiest way out. But here is the reality, and it's not
flashy at all.
   A study from the Institute of Sports in Society at Boston's
Northeastern University found that of 30 million children now in
youth sports programs in the United States, 198 will become
professional athletes. That's .0000066 percent. ...
   For young people with a gift for sports, there are promises on
promises _ from junior high coaches, from high schools. Make the
sacrifices, the line of logic goes, and you can be a star, kid. ...
   That it corrupts the spirit of what's supposed to be wholesome
recreation doesn't matter to many coaches. ...
   If the disturbing trend ... continues, the high schools will
become to colleges what colleges are to the pros _ free farm teams.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
