<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Orr     03-15 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Orr,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Indiana Governor in Line for Ambassadorial Post, Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate former Indiana
Gov. Robert D. Orr to be the next U.S. ambassador to Singapore, an
administration official said today.
   The official, declining to be named publicly, said the
annoncement would come later this month.
   Orr's likely appointment was first reported by The Indianpolis
Star in a report filed from Washington. It cited an unidentified
State Department official as confirming Orr's nomination.
   The official announcement likely will come after the government
of Singapore formally responds to the Bush administration's request
to post Orr as the U.S. ambassador to the Southeast Asian island,
the official told the Star.
   The Senate would then have to confirm Orr's appointment.
   The former two-term governor, an early supporter of Bush's
presidential bid, said Tuesday he knew he had been the source of
speculation and rumor but declined to confirm the appointment.
   ``The person on the receiving end really doesn't have much to say
about it until the person on the appointing end decides what he is
going to do and makes the announcement,'' Orr said.
   ``I have said all along, two days after the election, that, yes,
I have been interested in an appointment to a nation, preferably the
Far East,'' he added.
   During his eight-year administration, Orr, 71, made four trips to
the Far East, though never to Singapore.
</TEXT>
