<FIRST>r a PM-People-JoeClark     03-15 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Joe Clark,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Asks That Controversial Principal Be Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council wants the school board to
fire Joe Clark, the bat- and bullhorn-wielding principal portrayed
in the movie ``Lean on Me.''
   However, the board will not follow the recommendation, said board
attorney Robert G. Rosenberg.
   The council Tuesday approved by a 5-4 vote a resolution asking
the Paterson Board of Education to replace Clark, the Eastside High
School principal who gained praise from the Reagan administration
for roaming school halls with a bat and bullhorn.
   The resolution cites teacher layoffs and a school assembly last
month in which scantily clad dancers performed, said city clerk
Sylvia Ulmer.
   Rosenberg said the board at its meeting Thursday would ratify
Clark's five-day suspension, ordered by School Superintendent Frank
Napier.
   ``The Board of Education, in this instance, as well as previous
history in respect to Mr. Clark, will act only on fact and
responsible behavior, not on political influence or exterior
pressure,'' he said.
   Clark has said that during the school assembly, he was out of
town promoting ``Lean On Me,'' a movie about his tenure at Eastside,
and was not present to stop the dancing when it turned out different
than he expected.
</TEXT>
