<FIRST>r a PM-EastSt.Louis-Layoffs     03-15 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East St. Louis-Layoffs,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>600 Layoffs Expected in East St. Louis Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school district in this
impoverished city is laying off 600 of its 1,800 employees, a
newspaper reported today.
   The layoffs, including about 350 teachers, will take effect at
the end of the school year in June, and few will be asked back in
the fall, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch said.
   Superintendent Elmo J. Bush said the state board of education had
asked the district to trim about $12 million from next year's
budget. The district, whose budget this year is $70 million, has
more than $10 million in unpaid bills, he said.
   The district is two weeks behind in payments to employees, and
Bush said the delay was likely to continue for some time.
   East St. Louis, located across the Mississippi River from St.
Louis, Mo., has been plagued for years by a declining tax base and
other budget problems.
</TEXT>
