<FIRST>u a PM-MultipleKillings     03-15 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Petitioned to Halt Arkansas Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES W. BURTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court will review a
petition by a death row inmate trying to block the execution of mass
murderer R. Gene Simmons against Simmons' wishes, a spokeswoman said
today.
   The emergency appeal was filed by inmate Jonas H. Whitmore with
Justice Harry Blackmun, who referred it to the full court,
spokeswoman Kathy Arberg said.
   Simmons, scheduled to die by lethal injection at 7 a.m. Thursday
in Arkansas' first execution in 25 years, has waived an appeal,
saying he wants to die.
   Whitmore's attorney, Arthur Allen, said Tuesday that if Simmons'
sentence is carried out, it will open the way to more executions in
Arkansas.
   The state Supreme Court rejected Whitmore's petition Monday,
ruling that Whitmore lacked legal standing to address Simmons'
rights.
   State law gives Simmons the right to an automatic appeal of his
conviction and death sentence, handed down last month for the 1987
Christmastime murders of 14 family members.
   If Simmons changes his mind at any point before the execution,
the process will be stopped, said James Lee, spokesman for state
Attorney General Steve Clark.
   Simmons was arrested in 1987 in Russellville after a shooting
spree that left two people dead. When police went to his rural home
near Dover, they found the bodies of 14 of Simmons' relatives.
   Simmons was convicted separately and sentenced to death last year
for the two Russellville murders.
</TEXT>
