<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildCareSurvey     03-15 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care Survey,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Parents Want Federal Subsidies for Child Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most parents favor federal subsidies and tax
breaks for child care but say states should continue regulating the
service, according to a survey released Wednesday by Kinder-Care,
the nation's largest chain of day care centers.
   The national telephone survey, of 502 parents with children under
10, also indicated a trend toward wider acceptance of center-based
care. Fifty-five percent of the parents said they personally would
find it acceptable to place children under 3 in a child care center,
including 19 percent who said center care would be OK for infants
under 12 months.
   Asked how they felt about federal regulation, 56 percent
responded very or somewhat positive.
   But when asked whether states or the federal government should
should regulate class size, cost, professional training, class
activities and number of children per person providing the care,
more parents favored the state. They were evenly split on who should
set health and safety standards. More than half said federal
regulation would drive up the cost of child care.
   A full 88 percent of the parents said the federal government
should give tax credits or deductions for child care and 49 percent
said the current maximum tax credit of $4,800 per household should
be increased. Forty-one percent favored subsidies for low-income
families and 28 percent said they supported subsidies to all income
groups.
   The survey conducted by the New York firm of Research &amp; Forecasts
Inc. has a margin of error of 5 percentage points.
   Kinder-Care, based in Montgomery, Ala., runs more than 1,200
centers serving 130,000 children in 40 states and two Canadian
provinces. The company, which favors the current system of state
regulation, grossed $300 million last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
