<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vatican-Brazil     03-15 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vatican-Brazil,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Carves Up Sao Paulo Archdiocese, World's Largest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican on Wednesday carved up the
archdiocese of Sao Paulo, Brazil, the world's largest, into five
separate church districts.
   The move drastically reduces the domain of Cardinal Paulo
Evaristo Arns, considered a leader of the Brazilian church's
progressive wing.
   It shrinks Sao Paulo, Brazil's commercial center, from an
archdiocese of 14.5 million people to 7.1 million people, according
to Vatican figures.
   The other 7.4 million people are now divided up into the newly
created dioceses of Campo Limpo, Osasco, Santo Amaro and Sao Miguel
Paulista.
   Some Brazilians believe the action is part of a campaign by Pope
John Paul II to weaken the dominant progressive wing of the church
in Brazil and the powerful Brazilian Bishops Conference.
   The four new dioceses contain most of the church-run community
centers that often work with leftist political parties. Each will
get its own bishop, appointed by John Paul.
</TEXT>
