<HEAD>Live Shells Containing Chemical Weapons Unearthed In Pipeline Dig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen mortar rounds believed to
contain poisonous gases were unearthed at a World War II disposal
site by space agency workers digging a pipeline on Redstone Arsenal.
   Ed Peters, a spokesman for the Army Missile Command at the
arsenal, said the pipeline work remained shut down Wednesday as Army
specialists decide whether digging can safely continue.
   Peters said the 17 rusty, 4.2-inch shells were found Saturday in
the ``Boneyard,'' a field where stockpiles of chemical warfare
weaponry once were burned and buried. He said the field was a
post-World War II disposal site for arsenal-produced mustard gases,
choking gases and blistering agents as well as poison gases captured
from Nazi Germany.
   The shells were found by construction workers digging a new
helium pipeline for the Marshall Space Flight Center. Peters said a
bomb disa defense budget that would be approved for a
two-year period instead of one year at a time as is customary, an
argument Pentagon officials say will build stability into the
weapons-buying process.
   In introducing Cheney, Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., a member of
the Armed Services panel, said Cheney's ``sense of humility and a
sense of presence served him well and will serve America well.''
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel said he recommended the
nomination with a ``combination of pride and regret'' because he was
losing the No. 2 GOP leader in the House.
   Cheney conceded that the decision to leave the House had been
``wrenching.''
   ``I'm here not because I sought the job but because the president
asked me to take on a difficult assignment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
