<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Soviet     03-15 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Soviet,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Refers to Greater Ties With East Bloc</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The exchange of messages between Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev paved
the way for expanding of Iran's relations with the East bloc, the
speaker of the Iranian parliament said Wednesday.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani made the remark during a meeting in Tehran
with Milko Balev, chairman of Bulgarian National Assembly's foreign
committee, according to Iran's official news agency.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze was granted a rare
audience with Khomeini, Iran's spiritual leader, on Feb. 26.
Shevardnadze's message from Gorbachev was in reply to an earlier
letter from Khomeini.
   During the audience, Khomeini called for the expansion of ties
between Tehran and Moscow, according to the agency, monitored in
Nicosia.
   Balev, who arrived Saturday, told Rafsanjani that Bulgaria is
ready to set up a friendship association between Bulgarian and
Iranian lawmakers.
   Balev also repeated an invitation from President Tudor Zhivkov to
Rafsanjani to visit Sofia.
</TEXT>
