<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Massacre     03-15 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Massacre,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Officers Indicted in Peasant Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian judge today indicted
and jailed two army officers, accusing them of a role in the
massacre of 10 peasant farmers.
   It was the first time that armed forces officers had been
indicted for killing civilians in nine years of civil war during
which the armed forces have been accused of thousands of slaying.
   Judge Alcides Guandique also indicted seven soldiers for their
alleged role in the killings. Guandique, 33, handed down the
indictments in his office in San Sebastian, 30 miles east of San
Salvador.
   The United States, which provides most of the Salvadoran
government's funds, has lobbied for a credible investigation into
the slayings and punishment for those responsible.
   Maj. Mauricio Beltran Granados and 2nd Lt. Arnaldo Vasquez
Alvarenga were jailed pending their trials, which were likely to
begin in several weeks, Guandique said.
   The indictments came only four days before the March 19
presidential election in which Salvadorans, for the first time, will
have the chance to eject an incumbent civilian government in favor
of another party.
   The slayings occurred last Sept. 21, when troops used explosives
and rifle fire to kill 10 people in the hamlet of San Francisco,
four miles north of San Salvador, according to the indictments.
   Other villagers said the 10 were accused by the soldiers of
collaborating with leftist guerrillas waging a 9-year-old war
against the U.S.-backed government.
   The armed forces on Sunday, in an unprecedented step, admitted
responsibility for the massacre and submitted those implicated to
civilian jurisdiction.
   With Guandique's indictment and decree of provisional detention,
the officers became the first in Salvadoran history to be jailed on
the order of a civilian judge.
   The army originally said the ten peasants had died in ``fierce
combat,'' then said they had been killed in a guerrilla ambush that
injured nobody else.
   Guandique has won praise from human rights advocates for his
persistent investigation of the case.
   About 70,000 people have died during the civil war between the
leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, most of them
civilians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
