<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Cop-KillerParole     03-15 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cop-Killer Parole,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cop-Killer Paroled On His Third Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTISVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cop-killer whose 1985 grant of clemency
from Gov. Mario Cuomo was denounced by then-Vice President George
Bush was granted parole today.
   Gary McGivern, who was convicted of murder in the 1968 shooting
of a deputy sheriff, could be free by the end of the week, once the
paperwork is done, officials said.
   The decision followed an appearance by McGivern before a
three-member Board of Parole panel at the medium-security prison
where he is serving a life sentence.
   It was McGivern's third such appearance since Cuomo's New Year's
Eve 1985 clemency that was attacked by Bush and many New York law
enforcement officials. Twice McGivern was turned down because of the
nature of the crime.
   Edward Elwin, executive director of the Board of Parole, said the
penal cited McGivern's ``outstanding record'' in prison in voting
3-0 to release him under ``intense supervision.''
   Cuomo, as lieutenant governor, recommended clemency in 1979 after
McGivern passed two lie detector tests, but then-Gov. Hugh Carey
said no. Six years later, Cuomo granted clemency, making McGivern
eligible for an immediate parole hearing.
   ``It was a very difficult call,'' said Cuomo. ``This man is not a
cop killer.''
   For a time, McGivern was on death row, but an appeals court kept
him from going to the chair.
   Corrections Department spokesman James Flateau said McGivern was
refusing to grant interviews.
   In the past, the very idea that McGivern was even getting a
parole hearing brought out placard-carrying prison guards and law
enforcement officials. That was true again this week as members of
the state Sheriffs' Association protested outside parole board
offices in Albany on Tuesday.
   ``McGivern hasn't learned anything except how to work the system.
The people who will learn something from McGivern's early release
are the potential cop killers,'' Peter Kehoe, executive director of
the sheriffs' group, said in a statement.
   ``They'll learn that it's okay to kill a cop today _ society
won't care about the dead cop in a few years.''
   On Wednesday, there were no demonstrators at the parole board's
Albany office or outside the Otisville prison.
   Kavanagh has said McGivern's parole may boost efforts to override
a Cuomo veto of legislation restoring the death penalty. The state's
electric chair hasn't been used since 1963 and Cuomo has vetoed
death penalty legislation for the past six years.
   ``A reasonable, rule-abiding inmate,'' said state Corrections
Commissioner Thomas Coughlin last week when asked about McGivern.
``I think if Gary McGivern was paroled tomorrow, he would probably
never get in trouble again.''
   After three trials, McGivern and fellow inmate Charles Culhane
received life sentences for the shooting death of William
Fitzgerald, a Westchester County deputy, during an attempt to escape
while being transported to court.
   McGivern and Culhane have blamed a third inmate, Robert Bowerman,
for the slaying. Bowerman died of gunshot wounds in the escape
attempt.
   Culhane said today's decision should help his own bid for early
release. Cuomo has refused to grant Culhane clemency, and he's not
eligible for a parole hearing until 1991.
   McGivern and Culhane's first trial ended in a hung jury. Their
conviction in a second trial was overturned on appeal. A third trial
ended in conviction in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
