<FIRST>r w AM-FairnessDoctrine     03-15 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairness Doctrine,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Subcommittee Chairman Reintroduces Fairness Doctrine Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Daniel K. Inouye on Wednesday reintroduced
a Fairness Doctrine bill for broadcasters and then listened to
experts debate whether it is necessary in this diverse media age to
make stations air all sides of controversial issues.
   The Senate bill, with a half-dozen co-sponsors, matched
legislation already introduced in the House that would write into
law the Federal Communications Commission's 40-year-old rules that
the FCC repealed in 1987.
   The bill is expected to pass easily again this year, as it did
last year, and then face another presidential veto.
   Inouye, a Democrat from Hawaii who is chairman of the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee's communications
subcommittee, said the need for the bill was greater than ever. He
cited a recent article in Broadcasting magazine that ``concluded
that in the last year there has been a decrease in the amount of
time devoted to broadcast station editorials.''
   But Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., the top GOP member of the
subcommittee, said ``arguments for the Fairness Doctrine get weaker
and weaker.''
   Packwood said the doctrine first was promulgated in the 1940s on
the idea that the radio and television spectrum was limited.
   ``There were certainly fewer broadcasters than there are now ...
no cable, no videocassette recorders. Today we have such a plethora
of access to information that one is hard-pressed to say that if
every radio station in the country, every television station in the
country is not compelled by law to follow a content doctrine where
we impose the content that somehow the public is not going to be
well-informed.''
   But Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., said the number of outlets was not
the issue, it was the number of people a single outlet can reach in
an era in which, according to polls he cited, Americans watch an
average of four hours of TV daily and half the public gets all of
its news from television.
   ``I think that the broadcast (medium) has a unique role in its
ability to affect the thinking of the American people that's simply
not shared by the print media,'' Danforth said.
   But one witness before the panel, Thomas G. Krattenmaker of the
Georgetown University Law Center, said the doctrine was ``misguided
regulatory policy'' that tries to make ``every station behave in a
perfect way, to provide news and information for everyone who might
want that type of news or information in that listening market.''
   ``That's like telling a shoe store that it must provide every
kind of shoe that anybody might want to buy,'' Krattenmaker said.
   Jerome Baron of the George Washington University National Law
Center disagreed, saying the age of diverse media outlets has not
arrived and that cable is an ``unequal rival'' to broadcasting.
   ``Cable is now in its early adolescence,'' Baron said. ``If we
measure the contribution of cable from what it has in its own voice
been able to say, I don't think it's said very much.''
   ``I'm skeptical about claims that these new media will greatly
diminish the importance and power of the established prestige
media,'' he said.
   Scott Denman of the Safe Energy Communication Council questioned
claims that the Fairness Doctrine ``chilled'' discussion of
controversial issues. He said his group's surveys had found the
doctrine ``actually encourages more, and never less, coverage of the
issues,'' especially news.
   But he said very few broadcasters will actively seek opposing
points of view when it involves paid political advertising.
   Professor Anna Goldoff of the City University of New York said
her survey of 22 New York City radio and TV stations found that just
two of them considered the doctrine to have a chilling effect, while
82 percent said it had no effect one way or another.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., challenged that view.
   ``I know of several cases where the chilling effect was clearly
evident in a (political) race that I was in and several others,''
McCain said, noting that small radio stations facing large
attorneys' fees to defend themselves ``just opt out.''
   ``They just play music and that solves their problem, and
therefore the people within broadcast range of them don't receive
information on controversial issues,'' McCain said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
