<DOCNO> AP890315-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IRSErrors     03-15 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRS Errors,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Says Its Error Rate _ 31 Percent or 40 Percent _ Is Unacceptable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service is giving the
wrong answer to telephoned tax questions 40 percent of the time _
not the 31 percent claimed by the IRS, government auditors said
Wednesday.
   In a rare public airing of a dispute between government agencies,
the IRS told a congressional panel that both figures can be
justified, denied attempting to mislead anyone and said there is no
pride in either error rate.
   ``As far as the IRS is concerned, whether we are answering 30
percent of the questions wrong or 40 percent of the questions wrong,
either number is absolutely unacceptable,'' said Robert LeBaube, IRS
director of taxpayer services.
   The dispute between IRS and the General Accounting Office, an arm
of Congress, is over how to judge the accuracy of answers that IRS
telephone ``assistors'' give to some of the 62 test questions that
will be posed clandestinely by other IRS employees 15,000 times this
filing season.
   ``Many of the answers IRS wants to score as `right' are
incomplete and potentially misleading,'' Jennie Stathis of GAO told
the House Government Operations subcommittee on consumer affairs.
``Such answers would increase the likelihood of taxpayers making
errors.''
   In reporting the 31 percent error rate, the IRS disregarded an
agreement with GAO over how the answers should be scored, Ms.
Stathis said.
   Members of the subcommittee found the dispute troubling, but said
they were even more concerned about the error rate. ``We cannot
tolerate a situation in which the very agency which is charged with
the enforcement of our tax laws is responsible for providing
erroneous information to taxpayers attempting to comply with those
laws,'' said Rep. J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
   LeBaube advised taxpayers who call the IRS toll-free numbers to
write down their question, the date and name of the person who
provided the answer. If an answer leads to an incorrect tax return
and the taxpayer produces such a record, LeBaube said, the IRS will
waive any penalty.
   The subcommittee, chaired by Rep. Doug Barnard Jr., D-Ga., is
concerned about the dispute because the IRS and GAO, which in past
years had done separate tests of the telephone-assistance program,
agreed to work together on a single test this year. The IRS would
make the test calls, using questions worked out with GAO, and GAO
would monitor the results.
   The two agencies agreed on 62 questions and set up three
categories for scoring the answers: ``correct,'' the minimum
standard IRS expected its assistors to meet; ``correct and
complete,'' and ``incorrect.''
   After a few weeks of conducting the test, LeBaube said, the IRS
determined there should be a new category to cover about 8 percent
of the answers that, while not technically correct were sufficient
to allow a taxpayer to file a correct return.
   Such an answer might be given after the assistor asked probing
questions to assure the taxpayer was not leaving out essential
information.
   ``For example,'' LeBaube said, ``if the test caller says he is
from Des Moines, Iowa, speaks with a Midwest accent and asks whether
he can still be claimed on his parents' return, the assistor may
probe to determine age, income, whether he was in school and how
much support his parents provided.
   ``However, the assistor probably would not ask whether he was a
U.S. citizen. The failure to ask this might not meet our mutually
agreed-upon standard,'' LeBaube added. ``However, the assistor would
in all probability be providing an answer that would allow the
taxpayer to prepare his return correctly.''
   After GAO refused to change its scoring method to accept such
responses as correct, IRS decided on its own to count them as right.
Without informing GAO, the IRS held a news conference Friday to
announce that assistors were giving the correct answer 69.2 percent
of the time.
   ``In retrospect, and in fairness to GAO, we probably should have
announced both numbers,'' LeBaube said.
   He insisted, however, that ``the public is misled if you do not
characterize those answers (in dispute) as ... ones that would lead
to a correct return.''
   The IRS has about 5,000 employees, including 1,500 temporaries,
answering toll-free telephone calls for assistance. They must be
high school graduates and receive at least five weeks' tax training.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
