<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Derwinski-Vets 1stLd-Writethru a0468 03-15 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Derwinski-Vets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new from ceremony; picks up 7th graf, Veterans'
organizations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14th chair was pulled up to the Cabinet table
today with the formation of the Department of Veterans Affairs, and
President Bush noted that its new head started his government career
as an Army privte.
   The first secretary of veterans affairs, Edward J. Derwinksi,
took the oath of office in a private ceremony with Bush in the
Roosevelt Room of the White House.
   In a ceremony on the South Lawn of the White House immediately
afterward, Derwinksi told an audience of more than 500 people, many
of them wearing the caps of veterans' groups, that they had a right
to expect ``the best possible service.'' But he cautioned, ``This
isn't the world's best time in Washington for matters involving the
budget,'' a theme he has been sounding for weeks.
   Bush praised Derwinski as uniquely qualified to lead the new
agency because ``he has the skill of a seasoned legislator, the
patience of a practical administrator, the finesse of a diplomat and
the heart of a man who knows what it means to start his government
career as a private in the United States Army.''
   Derwinski is a former 12-term member of the House from Illinois
who served in high-level State Department posts in the Reagan
administration. He served in the Army in 1945-1946 and took part in
the occupation of Japan.
   The Veterans Department, formed from the old Veterans
Administration, is the second-largest agency of the government,
behind the Defense Department, with 240,000 employees. Its annual
spending of about $29 billion is the fifth largest among agencies.
It expects to keep the short title from its past, ``VA.''
   Veterans' organizations for years sought the greater clout they
thought Cabinet rank would give them, but it took an election-year
conversion by former President Reagan last year to put the idea
across.
   Derwinski has six months to make organizational changes he
believes necessary, but already he's decided they ``won't be
drastic.''
   In an interview earlier this week, he repeated a warning he has
been giving veterans' groups along with promises to drop in for a
beer at their local halls, that in the next four years ``there are
going to be some painful budget decisions.''
   ``My job is to see that the VA does better in the budget
infighting than it would have if I weren't aboard,'' he said.
   ``I don't believe in the short run we have any monumental
problems,'' Derwinski said. ``If there are shortfalls, it's mainly
because of the budget battle.''
   A year ago the National Academy of Public Administration said it
did not believe Cabinet status ``would significantly improve either
access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources or the
organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and
benefits.''
   VA officials told Congress last year the $10.8 billion allocated
for medical care in this year's $29.8 billion VA budget would be at
least $600 million short. Most hospitals already have begun to
curtail care to veterans where they have discretion to do so.
   Some of the agency's medical issues have been making news for
years. An estimated 479,000 Vietnam veterans, one in five who served
there, suffer from post-traumatic stress disorder bringing
flashbacks and disorientation.
   Much controversy and money have gone into studies of the Vietnam
defoliant Agent Orange, and the issue is not settled yet, though the
VA has said it can find no significant difference in cancer rates
between exposed veterans and others.
   ``The big problem is one, interestingly, where there is no
debate: aging,'' Derwinski said. ``The patients' needs start to
change. ... It ultimately means long-term health care rather than
dramatic surgical procedures.''
   There are more than 27 million veterans. Counting dependents, a
third of the nation is eligible for one or another of the services
provided by the huge, but fairly uncomplicated, bureaucracy
dispensing medical care and $17 billion a year in pensions and other
money benefits and operating 111 national ceremonies.
   With 172 hospitals, 229 outpatient clinics and scores of other
installations, the agency runs the largest medical care system in
the country, caring for 1.4 million hospital patients annually.
   The VA's motto comes from Lincoln's second inaugural address:
``To care for him who shall have borne the battle and for his widow,
and his orphan.'' The agency traces its history to the Plymouth
Colony law of 1636 for the maintenance of members disabled in the
Pequot Indian war, though the VA was formed only in 1930 to
consolidate veterans program in other departments.
</TEXT>
