<FIRST>r a PM-StudentShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0608 03-15 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Student Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0608,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Commits Suicide in Classroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `However, Principal ...' and last graf to CORRECT
to reflect that boy's mother remarried and does not share the same last
name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSH LEMIEUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old who shot and killed
himself in front of 21 classmates had undergone counseling for
undisclosed emotional problems earlier in the school year, the
principal says.
   Donald Payne shot himself in the head in a classroom at Jefferson
City High School on Tuesday, said police Sgt. Ray Bledsoe.
   The teen-ager had shown no unusual behavior the morning of the
shooting, said an administrator who talked with his parents, friends
and teachers.
   Bill Anthony, district director of secondary education, said the
boy's parents ``had not noticed anything abnormal about his mood or
activity that morning.''
   ``As far as they knew there had not been any girlfriend breakup
or any kind of loss in the family or any other problems in the
family,'' Anthony said.
   ``I have not heard anyone, either students, faculty or family,
that have indicated a reason'' for why the boy shot himself.
   However, Principal Richard Pemberton said school officials
recommended earlier in the school year that the boy's parents take
their son for counseling for emotional problems.
   Pemberton, who would not discuss the problems or the boy's
academic or disciplinary record, said the parents cooperated, and
the boy attended three days of sessions.
   The teen-ager had shown the .22-caliber pistol to friends before
school but said nothing before pulling the trigger as his science
class began, students told police. ``Nobody actually had seen him
come out with the gun,'' Bledsoe said.
   The students who were in the room received counseling from
administrators and psychiatrists, Pemberton said.
   Anthony said the boy's parents were sure he took the gun from
home.
