<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BusinessInventories     03-15 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories, Sales Continue to Rise in Tandem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories continued their steady
rise in January, accompanied by healthy growth in sales, the
government said Wednesday in a report that showed continued strength
in the aging economic expansion.
   Inventories held on shelves and backlots rose 0.7 percent to a
seasonally adjusted $766.2 billion in January, the 25th straight
month in which inventories have increased, the Commerce Department
reported.
   Sales, meanwhile, rose 1 percent to a seasonally adjusted $513.9
billion in January. The increase came despite a 1.7 percent drop in
auto sales that was accompanied by a 1.9 percent rise in stocks of
unsold cars during January.
   An advance report on February's retail sales said auto purchases
were down another 1.7 percent last month.
   Analysts said car purchases have been held down by rising
interest rates and reduced demand after strong sales last year.
Carmakers recently have boosted incentive offers in an effort to
spur sales, and General Motors Corp. has temporarily halted
production at two plants to reduce inventory.
   Overall, January's activity produced no change in the ratio of
business inventories to sales, which stood at 1.49, meaning it would
take 1.49 months to exhaust inventories at January's sales pace.
   Economist Robert DeFina of Security Pacific National Bank in Los
Angeles said the balance between inventories and sales signals
``continued moderate growth without the big imbalance that usually
precedes a major downturn.''
   Charles Renfro, chief economist at the Alphametrics forecasting
firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said the figures suggest the economy is
``still moving ahead,'' but at a moderate pace that shouldn't add to
inflationary pressures.
   Rising inventories, if not accompanied by corresponding increases
in sales, can lead to production cutbacks that would hamper economic
growth. But recent growth in inventories generally has been
accompanied by rising sales, with autos being the exception.
   Robert G. Dederick, chief economist for Northern Trust Co. in
Chicago, cautioned that businesses will have to be ``fast on their
feet'' to avoid an unwanted build-up of excess inventories in the
event of a sales slowdown.
   ``If demand doesn't remain as solid as it has been ...
inventories could quickly become heavy,'' Dederick said.
   January's increase in inventories included a 0.9 percent rise in
stocks held by manufacturers, a 0.2 percent boost in stockpiles at
the wholesale level and a 0.9 percent increase in inventories held
by retailers.
   The rise in sales included a 0.3 percent advance in sales by
manufacturers, a 2.3 percent increase at the wholesale level and a
0.7 percent increase in retail purchases, despite the slowdown in
car sales.
   Analysts said January's strong retail sales were due partly to
unusually mild weather that brought out more shoppers.
   February's advance report on retail sales, released Tuesday,
showed purchases were down 0.4 percent last month, held back by the
sharp drop in business at car dealerships.
</TEXT>
