<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Caesarean     03-15 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caesarean,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Physician Practice Styles Influence Caesarean Rate</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Individual physicians' styles of practice are an
important factor in determining whether pregnant women have
Caesarean sections, a study concludes.
   The doctors who conducted the study said that while their
findings were not a surprise, they were the first to document the
powerful influence of the so-called ``physician factor.''
   ``We demonstrated that given a very homogenous, low-risk,
affluent population, there was an extremely wide variation in the
rate of Caesarean section,'' said Dr. Gergory L. Goyert. ``The
conclusion is that an individual clinician is a major determinant of
the method of delivery.''
   The research was published in Thursday's issue of the New England
Journal of Medicine.
   The study, conducted at an unidentified community hospital in
suburban Detroit, was based on 11 obstetricians who delivered 1,533
babies during one year. Their rates of Caesarean section ranged from
19 percent to 42 percent. Among women who had not had previous
Caesareans, the rates ranged from 10 to 32 percent, depending on the
doctor.
   This variation could not be attributed to differences in the
patients, the degree of obstetrical risk or whether the physicians
had been sued recently for malpractice.
   The researchers could not prove that any of the Caesareans were
needless. However, the patients of doctors who did a lot of
Caesareans fared no better than those of physicians who performed
the operations more sparingly.
   Over the past two decades, the Casesarean rate in the United
States has increased from 5 percent of all births to 25 percent.
Many factors are thought to contribute to this increase, including
the safety of Caesareans, increasing concern for the welfare of the
fetus and fear of being sued if something goes wrong during a
vaginal delivery.
   The study did not determine why some doctors did more Caesareans
than others. ``I can only believe that they have the fetus's and
patient's best interests at heart,'' said Goyert, a physician at
Sinai Hospital of Detroit.
</TEXT>
