<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-15 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Claims Hundreds of Guerrillas Killed in Fight for Jalalabad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan jets bombed guerrilla positions
around Jalalabad on Wednesday, and Afghanistan's state-run radio
said hundreds of insurgents were killed in a failed attempt to
capture the strategic city.
   The guerrillas admitted that bombing by communist troops hampered
their advance on Jalalabad, but they claimed to have shot down five
airplanes and killed more than 100 government soldiers in the last
two days. They reported heavy civilian casualties from the bombing.
   Afghanistan's official Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said
government air and ground forces repulsed the guerrillas after they
fired 5,000 rockets and shells in an attempt to take the city in
eastern Afghanistan.
   It said that over the previous 24 hours, 560 guerrillas and
supporters were killed and 252 were wounded. It said the dead
included four Americans, a Saudi national, and some Pakistanis.
   Pakistan, the United States and Saudi Arabia back the Moslem
guerrillas in their war with the communist government but deny
having any nationals fighting in Afghanistan.
   The battle for Jalalabad, 42 miles from the Pakistan border, is
the first test of strength of Kabul's communist rulers and their
opponents since the last Soviet soldiers left Afghanistan on Feb. 15.
   Its fall would be a blow to the morale of the mainly conscripted
army and a big boost to the guerrillas, who have been fighting 10
years to establish an Islamic republic of Afghanistan.
   Observers believe a guerrilla victory could have a domino effect
on the country's other communist-held cities, including Kabul, the
capital.
   The guerrillas began their offensive March 6 and by last weekend
had captured the communist garrison at Samarkhel, six miles east of
Jalababad.
   The communists retaliated with heavy, high-altitude aerial
bombing.
   ``The (air) forces are taking a direct part in defending the
country and demolishing the gathering place of the invaders. ...
This success worried the enemy, and they are thinking: `These are
not Afghan pilots,''' Radio Kabul said Wednesday night.
   Guerrillas have claimed the fighter-bombers are piloted by
Soviets in violation of the U.N.-mediated accord that provided for
the Soviet withdrawal.
   Despite communist claims, guerrilla sources say they have lost
only about 150 men in the offensive and captured more than 700
government troops.
   Government and guerrilla versions of the fighting usually
contradict and tend to be exaggerated.
   However, journalists and witnesses have reported the battle for
Jalalabad has sent hundreds of wounded guerrillas and thousands of
civilians over the border into Pakistan.
   The guerrilla-run Afghan News Agency said insurgents also were
attacking communist posts around the northern city of Baghlan and
the southeastern city of Kandahar, the country's second-largest.
   It said attacks near Baghlan on Monday killed 70 communist
troops, wounded 50 and destroyed five tanks.
</TEXT>
