<FIRST>r a AM-FurloughKilling     03-15 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Furlough Killing,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Set at $945,000 for Inmate Who Killed While Out of Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bail was set at $945,000 for a man accused of
hammering an elderly woman to death and severely injuring his
ex-girlfriend while he was out of jail on a two-day furlough.
   Police have since acknowledged that Edward Beets, 29, was
overheard in the North Las Vegas Jail, arguing by telephone with
someone later identified as the ex-girlfriend.
   Beets is charged with murder in the death Friday of Oretha Hames,
71, and the attempted murder of her daughter, Vanita Hames, 28, who
is listed in stable condition at University Medical Center.
   Beets was sentenced to 45 days in jail earlier this year for
trespassing and domestic battery at the girlfriend's house. He was
given a two-day pass to attend an aunt's funeral, and the attack
occurred while he was on furlough.
   North Las Vegas Municipal Judge Gary Davis, who has a reputation
of being one of the area's toughest judges, approved the pass. Davis
said Tuesday he would not change the furlough policy, because to do
so would penalize deserving inmates.
   ``I've been doing a lot of soul-searching,'' Davis said. ``Should
I punish everyone in the future because this man did something
horrible? It was a kindness to (Beets') family that turned into a
nightmare.''
   Davis had sentenced Beets to 45 days in jail on charges of
misdemeanor trespass at the Hames home. The judge said the city
prosecutor had only asked for 10 days. Police said Beets had been
arrested previously at the address for domestic battery and
trespassing.
   Police were called to the Hames home in the pre-dawn hours by
Vanita Hames' 8-year-old daughter who said her grandmother had been
knocked out. They found the elderly woman dead and her daughter
suffering from a fractured skull and hammer wounds to the neck,
chest, arms and legs.
   Assistant Police Chief Ron Lusch said jail guards overheard Beets
having an angry phone conversation with someone last week. Beets
later told a guard he had been talking to his girlfriend.
   Lusch said such phone arguments are ``not uncommon'' at the jail.
   ``We're governed by law that we can't monitor (inmates') phone
calls,'' he said. ``If we had any inkling of (danger), proper
authorities would have been notified.''
   Davis said police often inform him of unusual circumstances
involving prisoners, but did not do so with Beets.
   ``If we'd have had that information, it would have made a world
of difference in what we had done,'' Davis said.
   The judge believes, however, that even if Beets had been denied a
furlough, it might simply have delayed the inevitable.
   ``If that was his intention, I don't think if we kept him in a
week longer or two weeks longer, it would have made any
difference,'' Davis said.
   Beets is to be arraigned March 23 on the latest charges.
</TEXT>
