<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-15 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The managers of an auditorium here have
cracked down on the chorus of winter coughers who have been crowding
out the music with their high-decibel hacks.
   The program for violinist Isaac Stern's performance at the
University of Iowa's Hancher Auditorium last week urged audience
members to calm their lungs.
   Ushers offered cough drops, but threatened to exile intransigent
coughers to soundproof booths.
   One member of the audience asked his neighbor, ``Are you ready?''
   ``Yes, I brought my cough drops,'' she whispered.
   The threat seemed to work.
   Barely a snivel competed with Stern's melodies, while the
sneezes, wheezing and barks swelled under the cover of applause
during breaks.
   The managers of the hall were haunted by a recent performance in
Buffalo, N.Y., by American soprano Jesse Norman, who was so
disturbed by coughing that she said to the audience: ``I hope you
can hear me as well as I can hear you.''
   ``I was really scared that that would happen at Hancher,'' said
Judith Hurtig, the hall's marketing director.
   Ms. Hurtig said she embarked on the cough reform campaign after
intense and constant coughing disturbed Japanese pianist Mitsuko
Uchida during a January concert at the auditorium.
   A local newspaper has dubbed crowds at the hall ``the Hancher
Hackers.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unsung Paterson welder went into a
``bowling coma'' and emerged with a near-perfect score to claim the
most coveted record in the game.
   Tom Jordan left only two pins standing at the Garden State Bowl
in Union on March 7, with scores of 300, 299, 300 and 299 over four
games.
   If certified by the American Bowling Congress, Jordan's 899 for
the first three games would be the highest recorded, his 1,198 for
the four also setting a record.
   ``It just seemed like I was in a bowling coma,'' said Jordan, 22.
``I was pretty well focused on what I was doing.''
   Mark Miller, a spokesman for the Greendale, Wis.-based bowling
organization, said Tuesday he expected a decision within a week.
   ``It is probably the most prestigious record in bowling,'' Miller
said.
   The previous three-game record, set in October 1939 by Allie
Brandt of Lockport, N.Y., was 887. Pat Landry of Lansing, Mich.,
tied that record last November.
   Jordan's partner, Ken Yonker Jr., bowled a 756 for the first
three games, and the pair's total of 1,655 would eclipse the
national doubles record of 1,642. Jordan and Yonker are left-handed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Yorkers eat out nearly twice as much as the
national average and favor Chinese when they order takeout meals.
   New York Newsday reported Wednesday that a poll conducted by The
Gallup Organization found that 74 percent of the city's residents
say they eat meals outside the home at least once a week.
   Some 22 percent said they had bought a takeout meal the day
before they were surveyed. Thirty-two percent favored Chinese food,
25 percent preferred Italian cuisine, including pizza, while 6
percent gave Mexican cooking the highest marks.
   A 1987 nationwide Gallup survey found only 4 percent had bought
Chinese food the previous day.
   Gallup interviewed 1,019 people ages 18 and over by telephone
Nov. 11-15 for the survey and reported a margin of error of 4
percentage points.
   Other findings:
   _ 39 percent of New Yorkers consider themselves overweight;
   _ 24 percent of New Yorkers say they are on a diet;
   _ 14 percent said they had purchased food from a street vendor in
the last week.
</TEXT>
