<FIRST>r a AM-Hostages-Say     03-15 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Say,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anderson's Sister, Ex-Hostage Jenco Plead for Public Awareness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of American journalist Terry
Anderson and a former hostage in Lebanon called Wednesday for
renewed attention to the plight of those still held captive in the
Mideast and urged conciliation with Iran.
   Peggy Say said she fears prospects for her brother's release have
worsened because his captors, pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists,
are angry about the publication of Salman Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses,'' which they consider blasphemous.
   ``Every event that takes place in the Middle East has the
potential effect. Hostages have died. Hostages have been executed.
So when things happen, the families are in an immediate panic,''
said Mrs. Say.
   She and the Rev. Lawrence M. Jenco, a hostage who was released in
1986, were interviewed on Cable News Network's Los Angeles-based
talk show ``Sonya.'' It was part of a series of appearances leading
up to Thursday's four-year anniversary of the day Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, was kidnapped in
Beirut.
   Anderson is the longest held of the 15 foreign hostages in
Lebanon. Nine are American.
   ``If this were a hundred Americans, would we be here on your
program today four years later debating what is the right thing to
do for these people?'' Mrs. Say asked. ``If we ignore nine today,
what will we ignore tomorrow? Will we then ignore 19 or 90? Some day
are we going to wake up and say, `My God, what's happened to our
world?'''
   She said the ``right thing'' was for the Bush administration to
open a dialogue with Iran and to seek reconciliation.
   A key element for the Americans' release would be a decision by
the United States to unfreeze Iranian assets it holds from arms
sales to the deposed shah, said Jenco.
   Mrs. Say said she believed her brother has been held hostage the
longest because he is a journalist.
   ``They counted on the fact that he is a journalist, that the
whole journalistic community would rise up in his defense as it has
for so many others,'' she said. ``They have never understood as I
guess I have never understood nor has Terry why that hasn't
happened.''
   Jenco said the United States should set an example for parts of
the world that don't understand America's ``framework of freedom.''
   ``In my own heart I believe that we should reflect to the world a
kinder, gentler nation, hoping that the world itself will become a
kinder, gentler world,'' the Roman Catholic priest said.
</TEXT>
