<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxReturns     03-15 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Returns,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number of Itemizers Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of taxpayers itemizing deductions is
down 2.5 percent this year, apparently because of the 1986 tax
overhaul, the Internal Revenue Service said Wednesday.
   About 41 percent of the long Form 1040 returns filed through last
weekend had itemized deductions, compared with 49 percent for the
same period last year.
   ``This suggests people may be finding it more advantageous not to
itemize'' because of a higher standard deduction and fewer itemized
deductions permitted under the new tax law, said IRS spokesman Steve
Pyrek.
   Overall, 43.3 million couples and individuals had filed their
returns through last week, 2.2 percent more than the 42.4 million
last year. The IRS has processed 29.3 million, also 2.2 percent more
than the 28.7 million at this time in 1988.
   The long form has accounted for 21.1 million returns this year,
or 49 percent of the total, compared with 21.7 million, or 51
percent a year ago. Filings of the short Form 1040-A are up 7.5
percent, to 10.7 million, and use of the single-page 1040-EZ for
single people is up 6.7 percent, to 11.4 million.
   The number of refunds is down 3 percent, to 18.4 million. The
average refund is up 3 percent, to $827.
   The IRS said 861,916 taxpayers had filed returns electronically
through professional return preparers. That compares with 362,000 in
the same period a year ago.
</TEXT>
