<FIRST>r i AM-India-Gandhi     03-15 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Gandhi,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Suspends Two-Thirds of India's Lower Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India on Wednesday refused to release an
inquiry on the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi,
prompting an uproar in the lower house of Parliament.
   The government rejected demands by opposition politicians to
release a secret report that allegedly links a powerful government
aide to the slaying.
   Some of the 90 opposition members in the 545-member lower house
chanted ``Dictatorship will not be tolerated!'' and ``We want the
report!''
   In a voice vote, the governing Congress Party suspended at least
63 of the opposition members for the rest of the week for
misbehavior. Most of the other opposition members walked out in
protest.
   All 93 opposition members in the 245-member upper house also
walked out.
   A newspaper said the report indicated the aide changed the time
of the television interview Mrs. Gandhi was heading toward when she
was killed, concealed the fact that he knew one of her assassins,
and let Mrs. Gandhi walk ahead of him just before she was gunned
down.
   Home Minister Buta Singh said a special team had investigated the
suspicions against Mrs. Gandhi's private secretary, Rajendra Kumar
Dhawan, and found that he was ``totally innocent.''
   Dhawan, 52, has refused to comment on the reports.
   Dhawan was dropped from his post after the assassination but was
brought back into the government last month as a key aide to Rajiv
Gandhi, Mrs. Gandhi's son and successor.
   The 1986 inquiry by Supreme Court Justice M.P. Thakkar was
supressed by the government in what it said was the interest of
national security.
   Several newspapers speculated Wednesday that the report may have
been leaked to the Indian Express, the country's largest selling
English-language newspaper, by Cabinet ministers who felt threatened
by Dhawan's return.
   Mrs. Gandhi was killed Oct. 31, 1984 in her New Delhi residence
by two of her Sikh bodyguards as she walked to a television
interview.
   One of the Sikhs was shot and killed by other bodyguards minutes
later, and the other was convicted of murder and hanged in January.
A third Sikh, who was convicted of conspiracy, was also hanged.
   The newspaper said he knew Beant Singh, the assassin who was
killed by other bodyguards, but he denied that during questioning.
   The government says Mrs. Gandhi was killed in revenge for an army
raid she ordered in June 1984 on the Golden Temple, the holiest Sikh
shrine.
   At least 1,200 people, many of them Sikhs, were killed in the
raid, which was aimed at flushing out Sikh extremists barricaded
inside the shrine.
   Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for an independent
homeland in Punjab, a rich farming state in northern India.
   Sikhs comprise only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but
are in a majority in Punjab. They claim they are discriminated
against by the Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
