<FIRST>r w AM-FoodLabeling     03-15 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food Labeling,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose More Nutrition Information on Food Labels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lawmakers proposed legislation Wednesday to
require food labels to disclose more nutrition information about the
content of cholesterol-raising saturated fats.
   ``The purpose of this legislation is to try to deal with the
problems consumers have when they are faced with a web of confusing
and misleading labels on the foods they are buying,'' said Rep. Dan
Glickman, D-Kan., who chairs the House Agriculture subcommittee on
wheat, soybeans and feed grains.
   At a news conference, he and Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, complained
that current labeling laws allow foods to make claims of ``no
cholesterol'' or ``100 percent vegetable shortening'' even though
they contain cooking oils with high levels of saturated fat.
   The American Heart Association, which supports the legislation,
says a diet low in saturated fat will help reduce the risk of heart
disease.
   The bill would require food labels to disclose nutrition
information, including saturated fat content by serving, if:
   _Packages display a claim about the product's cholesterol content
or say that it was made with vegetable oil.
   _Packages do not specifically identify which vegetable oil is
contained in the product. Some labels now show only that a product
was made with any of a variety of oils, including highly saturated
tropical oils like palm and coconut oil.
</TEXT>
