<FIRST>r w AM-DCDrugs     03-15 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC Drugs,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gun Law Signed; Police Asked to Work Six-Day Weeks; Mayor Allows
Teen Curfew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr., trying to curb
drug-related crime, signed legislation Wednesday to strengthen the
city's handgun law, asked police to work six-day weeks, and said he
will allow a curfew to become law in a bid to keep most teen-agers
off the streets late at night.
   He signed an emergency measure mandating a five-year jail term
for anyone convicted of even having access to a gun while committing
a crime in the city, and giving judges the option of denying
pretrial release of defendants caught with weapons.
   ``Tell all the criminals we're coming,'' Barry said at a news
conference. ``If you got your gun, you better get rid of it, because
if you get caught you're going to spend five years in jail.''
   The handgun law, which will be in effect for 90 days before being
reviwed by the city council, strengthens previous law which required
a jail term of five years only if a weapon was used to commit a
crime.
   Barry said the city's 3,920 police will be asked to work six-day
work weeks for the next five weeks, until recruits complete their
training. He said this step would cost the city about $2.6 million
in overtime. He also authorized the police department to hire 150
more people by May 1.
   Barry said he would allow an emergency curfew bill to take
effect, without his signature, on Thursday. It will not be enforced
until Monday to give police time to learn the rules. The curfew bars
anyone under 18 from gathering on streets from 11 p.m. to 6 a.m.
during the week and from midnight to 6 a.m. on weekends.
</TEXT>
