<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissent     03-15 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissent,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intellectuals: Release Political Prisoners; Police Stop Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-three Chinese intellectuals added their
voice Wednesday to the growing demands for democracy in an open
letter calling for the release of political prisoners.
   Police, meanwhile, in an apparent attempt to censure leading
intellectuals, stopped a meeting to discuss a new magazine from
taking place.
   Wednesday's open letter was the fourth sent to China's leaders
since January, and came five days before the opening of an important
political meeting, the National People's Congress.
   Su Wei, a 35-year-old scholar of literature at the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, said he wrote the letter because he
``could not stay silent any longer.''
   ``I have no interest in politics and I am not a hero,'' he said.
``Writing this letter should be a meaningless thing, but the way my
country works, it is a very serious thing.''
   ``As the country prepares to celebrate its 40th anniversary,''
the letter says, ``we urge the National People's Congress ... to
release a large number of detained prisoners.''
   The note also supports a recent call for the release of Wei
Jingsheng, China's most well-known political prisoner. He was
sentenced in 1979 to 15 years in prison for urging democracy.
   The signatories included scholars Liu Mingjiu, an expert on
French philosopher Jean-Paul Sartre, and Chen Jiaying, who
specializes in German thinker Martin Heidegger.
   Participants said the letter was written during a time of growing
political repression.
   They cited the recent police action that kept astrophysicist Fang
Lizhi, China's leading dissident, from attending a banquet President
Bush held on his visit to Beijing earlier this month.
   They said the government had warned them of unspecified
punishment awaiting those who write and sign public letters.
   On Tuesday, China's leading government spokesman, Yuan Mu, said
the state was ``not happy'' with such appeals for political reform,
and accused government critics of ``relying on foreign forces'' to
spread their message.
   Su said he would like his letter to be published in China, ``but
the press here is run by the state.''
   ``The government uses pressure to stop the news and then blames
us for contacting the foreign media,'' said Dai Qing, an author who
signed the letter.
   Amnesty for political prisoners was first proposed by Fang Lizhi
in January in an open letter to Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
   In February, 33 intellectuals signed a second letter. Hundreds of
people in Hong Kong and Taiwan and Chinese in the United States
signed petitions supporting the call. In March, 42 leading Chinese
scientists joined in.
   Chinese sources said several signatories of the February letter
had been invited to attend a meeting Tuesday to begin the first
issue of Ideologist magazine, but that police stopped the gathering
from taking place.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
meeting of about 50 of China's leading intellectuals initially had
been scheduled for a hotel in downtown Beijing.
   ``When I got there I saw a sign saying the meeting had been
canceled because there was no electricity,'' said one. ``But I went
upstairs and there was lots of electricity, just not in the room we
had reserved.''
   Organizers moved the meeting to a nearby restaurant.
   ``But when we got there, the meeting was canceled again,''
another participant said. ``Police said we needed permission to
meet.''
   The sources said they believed police stopped the gathering to
censure several of the signers of the February letter, most notably
Su Shaozhi and Wang Ruoshui.
   Su, a leading Marxist theoretician, was dismissed from his post
as head of China's Marxism-Leninism Institute because of his
liberalism. Wang was fired as deputy chief editor of the People's
Daily for advocating humanism.
   They sources said Ideologist, a Shanghai-based periodical, a
combination of political essays and literary criticism, probably
would not be affected.
</TEXT>
