<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     03-15 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Returns to Office, Power Struggle Remains Unresolved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha returned to
work Wednesday, eight weeks after suffering a stroke, but he didn't
say how he plans to resolve a power struggle with party members who
want a new head of state.
   Botha held a morning Cabinet meeting and was present in
Parliament during the afternoon when Finance Minister Barend du
Plessis announced the 1989-90 budget.
   Neither Botha nor any other members of the governing National
Party commented on the developments Wednesday.
   Botha has yet to make a public statement on a declaration by the
National Party parliamentary caucus, including the full Cabinet,
that it wants the new party leader, Education Minister F.W. de
Klerk, to take over as president.
   Botha and de Klerk sat next to one another during du Plessis'
budget speech Wednesday and exchanged a few words.
   Botha, 73, resigned as party leader Feb. 2 and was succeeded by
de Klerk, 52. Botha said he wanted to distance the presidency from
partisan politics so he could be more of a symbol of national unity,
but the caucus announced Monday that it wanted the party leader to
be head of state.
   The caucus has no formal means of forcing Botha out of the
presidency, barring evidence of misconduct or incapacity which could
prompt impeachment proceedings.
   Botha has the option of remaining in office against the wishes of
his party or deciding on his own to step aside from the government,
which he has led since 1978.
   The power struggle intensified Sunday, when Botha arranged an
interview with the state-controlled television network and said he
would not call an early election this year.
   The next election does not have to be held until March 1990.
Botha's statement, made without consulting party leaders, quashed
hopes that he would retire in the next few months in conjunction
with an early election.
   Some National Party officials have suggested that Botha might
agree to yield policy-making power to de Klerk while remaining in
office until next year. Other political observers have predicted
Botha will aggressively resist any concessions.
   There has been little public support for Botha during the
showdown.
   Botha and De Klerk appear to agree on most major policy issues.
However, de Klerk has been depicted as more pragmatic and
open-minded than Botha and more likely to accelerate the pace of
political change.
   ``A new man ... would be forced to do new things,'' said The
Sowetan, the country's largest black daily newspaper, in an
editorial Tuesday urging Botha to retire.
   Under the country's apartheid system, its 28 million blacks have
no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
