<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Massacre     03-15 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Massacre,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officers Indicted In Peasant Massacre In El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SEBASTIAN, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge indicted an army major
and a second lieutenant on murder charges Wednesday in the massacre
of 10 peasant farmers.
   The action against military officers by a civilian judge was
unprecedented. Security forces have been blamed for the torture and
death of thousands of civilians during a 9-year-old civil war, but
Maj. Mauricio Beltran and 2nd Lt. Arnaldo Vasquez became the first
officers to be indicted by the civilian authority for killing
Salvadoran citizens.
   Judge Alcides Guandique also indicted seven soldiers for their
alleged role in the slayings six months ago.
   Beltran has denied any role in the killings and contended the
case has been politicized. ``I had nothing against those people. I
did not even know them,'' he has said.
   The indictments followed heavy pressure from the United States,
which provides most of the government's funds and had told officials
that the army could no longer be allowed to kill civilians with
impunity.
   The indictments came in an atmosphere of rising violence only
four days before a presidential election Sunday, during which
Salvadorans for the first time have a chance to dump an incumbent
civilian government.
   Leftist guerrillas have threatened election workers and launched
attacks to prevent people from voting.
   The massacre took place Sept. 21 about 10 miles north of San
Sebastian, in the hamlet of San Francisco. According to the
indictments, troopers of the Jiboa battalion under Beltran's command
rounded up seven men and three woman and killed them with explosives
and gunfire.
   Asked why Beltran might have ordered the captives killed,
Guandique said: ``Psychosis of war.''
   Guandique, 33, conducted a patient investigation that eventually
disproved armed forces' versions of the massacre. He handed down the
indictments in his office in San Sebastian, 30 miles east of San
Salvador.
   The armed forces on Sunday, in another unprecedented step,
admitted responsibility. They had always denied involvement, and
they still deny involvement in a wave of death squad killings in the
early 1980s.
   Leftist guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, who are fighting the U.S.-supported government, have also
murdered civilians. But human rights groups say the rebels have
slain far fewer non-combatants than soldiers or death squads linked
to military units.
   With Guandique's indictment and decree of detention, Beltran and
Vasquez also became the first officers in Salvadoran history to be
jailed on the order of a civilian judge.
   The accused are likely to stand trial before a jury of five in
the coming months, Guandique said. He said charges could be dropped
against some of the defendants if new evidence exonerates them but
that Beltran had been implicated by many witnesses.
   Beltran and Vasquez are being held at military garrisons, said
the judge, but will be moved to a police facility pending trial.
   Lt. Manuel Galvez, second in command on the day of the killings,
broke the case open last week with testimony that Beltran ordered
the 10 people killed.
   Galvez said he refused to carry out the order, and 12 soldiers
backed him up with sworn testimony, said Guandique. Galvez, who had
been held with Beltran and Vasquez by military authorities, was not
indicted and will soon be freed.
   The incident began when about three dozen Jiboa troopers marched
into San Francisco and began rounding up the villagers. The soldiers
reportedly found rebel arms and mines in at least one house.
   The day after the killings, the villagers told The Associated
Press that about 45 of them had been herded into the small
schoolhouse. The troopers, working from a list, separated the 10
victims and marched them away.
   Guandique, citing testimony from Galvez and the soldiers, said
Beltran ordered the captured mines to be placed along a path and
detonated as the detainees were marched past, but the devices did
not explode on the first try.
   Several soldiers surrounded the prisoners and held them in place
while another trooper fetched a new battery to detonate the mines,
Guandique said.
   The mines were finally detonated, killing or wounding all the
prisoners, who were then riddled with rifle fire and dispatched with
a shot to the head, Guandique said.
   Guandique quoted Galvez and others as saying Beltran also ordered
the schoolhouse to be mined and blown up, but he was either
dissuaded or desisted when subordinates balked.
   ``It could have been 50 people instead of 10,'' Guandique said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
