<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Leaders     03-15 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Leaders,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ligachev Gets Most Critical Letters, Report Indicates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party received more letters critical
of Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev, a conservative counterweight
to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, than any other Soviet leaders,
Tass indicated Wednesday.
   The letters were received in connection with the election
campaigns of Ligachev, Gorbachev and other top party officials for
posts in the nation's new parliament, the official news agency said.
   Valentin Koptyug, chairman of the party's Electoral Commission,
made the letters public as the party's policy-making Central
Committee met to discuss agricultural policy and choose its
representatives to the parliament.
   The Communist Party is one of 30 organizations with the power to
choose one-third of the 2,250 representatives in the new Congress of
People's Deputies. The 100 deputies elected by the party in a secret
ballot include most members of the 12-man ruling Politburo, 26
workers and seven collective farmers, Tass reported.
   It said 25 letters sent to the Electoral Commission ``voiced
disagreement with some ideas voiced by Central Committee Secretary
and Politburo member Yegor Ligachev at the 19th National Party
Conference last summer.''
   Tass did not provide details of the letters.
   At a July 1 session of the conference, Ligachev said that with
all the criticism of events in the Soviet past, achievements had
been ignored and ``truth is often completely distorted.''
   Ligachev, 68, held the important post of ideology secretary,
making him No. 2 in the leadership structure after Gorbachev, until
Sept. 30, when he was shifted to a job with apparently less clout:
head of a new party commission on agriculture.
   Three letters criticized Gorbachev, Tass quoted Koptyug as saying.
   ``The party leader was blamed for the current situation in the
country because he was a member of the party leadership in the years
preceding the perestroika, or restructuring drive,'' Tass said.
   Gorbachev, 58, was named to the Politburo in 1979, during the
rule of Leonid I. Brezhnev _ an era now condemned as a ``period of
stagnation.''
   Tass said that of the other letters criticizing Politburo
members, nine were about Moscow party chief Lev Zaikov and two were
about Gorbachev ally Alexander Yakovlev.
</TEXT>
