<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Derwinski-Vets     03-15 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derwinski-Vets,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Veterans Cabinet Agency Starts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a flag-decked ceremony on the White House
South Lawn, President Bush on Wednesday marked the evolution of the
old Veterans Administration into the new Department of Veterans
Affairs after swearing in a former Army private to lead it.
   ``I consider the new department to have a vital mission. It is so
vital there is only one place for the veterans of America: In the
cabinet room with the President of the United States,'' Bush told
several hundred guests with the new secretary, Edward J. Derwinski,
by his side.
   On the podium with Derwinski was a former constituent he called
``the friend of the GI,'' Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist Bill
Mauldin of the Chicago Sun-Times, creator of the bedraggled Willie
and Joe characters of World War II.
   Derwinski, a 12-term Illinois congressman who filled high State
Department posts in the Reagan administration, was sworn in by the
president in a private ceremony in the Roosevelt Room. His wife,
Bonnie, and children Michael and Maureen accompanied him.
   The new secretary said Americans thought of veterans in terms
immortalized by Rudyard Kipling's tribute to the British ``Tommy:''
   ``For it's Tommy this, an' Tommy that, an' ``Chuck 'im out, the
brute!'
   ``But it's `Saviour of 'is country' when the guns begin to
shoot.''
   In praising Derwinski as ``uniquely suited'' to lead the new
department, Bush said, ``He has the skill of a seasoned legislator,
the patience of a practical administrator, the finesse of a diplomat
and the heart of a man who knows what it means to start his
government career as a private in the United States Army.''
   The 62-year-old Derwinski served in the occupation of Japan in
1945-1946.
   Bush said that if he does his job well as president, ``our armed
forces will be so strong and our diplomacy so wise that we will
never again need to erect another monument to the casualties of
war,'' and the resulting peace ``will be the truest monument to our
veterans.''
   The audience, many in the colored garrison caps of veterans
organizations, pledged allegiance to the flag at the beginning of
the ceremony, the first time it was remembered being done in the
Bush White House. Bush was a vigorous defender of the pledge during
the fall campaign, often attacking Michael Dukakis' veto as
Massachusetts governor of a bill requiring public school teachers to
lead the pledge each day.
   For years, the veterans organizations sought the status and clout
they thought Cabinet status would bring, but the general reluctance
of Congress and administrations to multiply Cabinet departments
prevented the change until President Reagan's election-year
conversion last year. A study by the National Academy of Public
Administration said greater influence was by no means certain.
   It is the second-largest government agency, with more than
240,000 employees. Formed in 1930 out of programs administered by
several departments, it expects to keep using its old short name
``VA.''
   Derwinski has been warning his constituencies and congressional
committees for weeks that when budget deficits have to come down,
his budgetary influence is uncertain. He repeated that warning
Wednesday: ``This isn't the world's best time in Washington for
matters involving the budget.''
   His department spends $29.8 billion a year and has budgeted $10.8
billion for the nation's largest medical care system, the 172
hospitals and hundreds of clinics, nursing homes and other
facilities operated by the VA.
   Officials have said their medical system will be $600 million
short this year, forcing delays in care for veterans with problems
not arising from their service.
   Derwinski has won approval in principle to submit a request for a
supplemental appropriation for $300 million, but warned in an
interview earlier this week ``We don't have the official Office of
Management and Budget blessing.''
   There was no sign of such a blessing in Wednesday's speeches.
   But Derwinski's willingness to fight for it has impressed the
veterans groups as exactly what they wanted. Jim Hanson, spokesman
for the American Legion, said: ``One thing that impressed most of us
was that before he was confirmed, even, he went over and asked for
more money. I don't know that anybody's ever done that before.''
   One of the audience, Charles Hohenstein of Veterans of Foreign
Wars Post 9619 in Morningside, Md., said, ``It's a little too early
to say'' whether the new department will carry more weight but ``I
hope it does.''
   The department's pension and benefit programs spend more than $17
billion a year and include the nation's fifth largest life insurance
system and loan guarantees for 12 million homeowners. In all, a
third of the population is a potential client of the agency, either
as one of 27 million veterans or as a dependent of one.

</TEXT>
