<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Transplants     03-15 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplants,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organ Donation On Rise, Network Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Kelle is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are donating livers, hearts and other
organs with growing frequency, national transplant network officials
said Wednesday after analyzing data covering 15 months.
   ``Organ donation is really steadily increasing,'' said Dr.
William K. Vaughn, director of technical services for the United
Network for Organ Sharing in Richmond, Va.
   Despite the gains, particularly in liver donations, such organs
are still in critically short supply because as transplant
techniques advance more patients are added to waiting lists for
organs.
   A record 16,792 people were awaiting transplants in the United
States as of Monday, the vast majority of them in need of kidneys,
said network spokeswoman Kelle Straw.
   In 1987, the latest year for which figures are available, 8,967
kidneys were transplanted nationwide along with 1,438 hearts, 1,199
livers, 142 pancreata and 41 heart-lung combinations, Ms. Straw
said. The number of kidney, pancreas and heart-lung transplants was
down slightly from the previous year, while the number of heart and
liver transplants was up.
   ``People may look at these figures and say, `Well fine, within a
couple of years, you should wipe everybody out waiting.' They don't
realize it's an evolving list,'' she said.
   The findings contradict earlier reports that donations were down
during the first half of 1988. Vaughn said those reports were valid
at the time because organ donation is cyclical.
   ``In the winter months, donation is down and it picks up in the
spring,'' he said. ``It's really high in the summer,'' the most
common time for accidents that leave victims brain-dead and their
other organs intact.
   The largest gain during the 15-month period was in liver
donation, Vaughn said. He estimated 160 livers were donated in
December 1988, the last month studied, up from 118 in October 1987,
the first month studied.
   Heart donations climbed from an estimated 170 to 200 a month
during the same period. Kidney donations jumped from an estimated
595 to 660 a month, while pancreas donations rose from an estimated
36 to more than 50 a month.
   The estimates are based on an analysis of seasonal and other
trends in data collected by the network from the nation's 72 organ
procurement agencies, Vaughn said. Only donated livers, hearts,
kidneys and pancreata were charted.
   The United Network for Organ Sharing, known as UNOS, began
compiling the information in October 1987, when federal guidelines
took effect for doling out scarce organs.
   At the same time, transplant centers and organ procurement
agencies began participating in the National Organ Transplantation
Network and the National Organ Transplantation Scientific Registry,
both computerized services administered by UNOS under contracts with
the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
   ``We can't compare prior to that time. No one has any data,''
Vaughn said.
   The figures do not represent the number of transplant operations
because some donated organs were discarded as unsuitable, Vaughn
said.
   Network officials did not attempt to characterize the donors or
learn what prompted the families' charity.
</TEXT>
