<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     03-15 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Afrikaner Church Declines To Actively Oppose Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main church of the ruling
Afrikaners on Wednesday said it would not support resistance to
apartheid, a decision almost certain to widen a split with its black
and mixed-race sister churches.
   The white branch of the Dutch Reformed Church also placed
qualifications on a statement it made last week declaring apartheid
a sin and heresy.
   The black and mixed-race churches last week prepared documents
calling for civil disobedience and outspoken opposition to apartheid
and presented them to the white church.
   The white church's General Synodical Commission, a high-level
policy-making body, on Wednesday named a committee to study the
apartheid issue further before taking a position, said Pierre
Rossouw, the church's chief executive.
   ``These are important and sensitive matters and we want to
consider them carefully,'' Rossouw said.
   With about 1 million adult members, the white Dutch Reformed
Church is the largest and most influential denomination among South
Africa's 3 million Afrikaners. President P.W. Botha and most members
of his Cabinet and Parliament are among its congregants.
   The black Dutch Reformed Church has 1.1 million members and the
mixed-race branch 680,000 congregants.
   The church's reluctance to become directly involved in opposing
apartheid is virtually certain to damage its already fragile
relations with black and mixed-race branches.
   ``The position of the white Dutch Reformed Church is very sad,''
said Rev. Nico Smith, one of the few white ministers who belong to
the black church. ``The white church is rapidly becoming irrelevant
to what's happening in South Africa.''
   The black and mixed-race churches include some of the country's
best known anti-apartheid campaigners, such as Rev. Allan Boesak and
Rev. Beyers Naude.
   Leaders of all three churches met last week, and the white church
declared for the first time that apartheid was a sin and asked
forgiveness for its longtime support of racial segregation.
   ``We confess with humility and sorrow the participation of our
church in the introduction and legitimation of the ideology of
apartheid and the subsequent suffering of people,'' the delegation
from the white church said.
   But the synod on Wednesday gave only a tepid endorsement of that
statement, noting it did not carry the weight of an official church
treaty and should be understood in terms of previous church policy.
   The synod specifically referred to a 1986 document that said
apartheid was a mistake, but stopped short of calling it a sin or a
heresy.
   Boesak said the white church commission must at least call for
the lifting of the country's 33-month-old state of emergency and the
release of all detainees held without charge.
   ``If they can't do these things, they will seriously jeopardize
our relationship, and their integrity will be seriously in
question,'' Boesak said Monday.
   The Dutch Reformed Church provided the scriptural justification
for apartheid when the governing National Party came to power in
1948 and began codifying racial segregation.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
 
</TEXT>
