<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     03-15 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarians Celebrate New-Found Freedom, Call For More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Hungarians took to
the streets Wednesday to celebrate new freedoms in one of the
biggest displays of nationalist sentiment since the anti-Soviet
revolt of 1956.
   Masses of people dressed in the national colors of red, white and
green and pre-communist coats of arms swarmed for hours through
central Budapest.
   It was the first time in 41 years communist officials made a
public legal holiday of the March 15 anniversary of Hungary's
unsuccessful revolt against Austria in 1848.
   Police did not interfere with the events, which included an
unofficial rally organized by 31 independent groups.
   An estimated 50,000 people jammed the square in front of
Hungarian state television offices for that rally. A 12-point
declaration calling for more freedom and independence was read, and
the throng moved to parliament chanting: ``Democracy! Democracy!''
   ``Not only should March 15 be a day of freedom, but the 16th,
17th, 18th and all the other days of the year!'' shouted independent
activist Denes Csegeny outside the television building.
   The 12-point declaration included demands for free elections, a
multiparty system, freedom of speech and press, the withdrawal of
Soviet troops and a neutral and independent Hungary.
   A call for a public holiday on Oct. 23, the anniversary of the
start of the 1956 revolt crushed by the Red Army, was greeted with
especially loud applause.
   ``March 15 and Oct. 23 are the holy days of the Hungarian
people,'' Imre Necs, who participated in the revolt, told the crowd.
   Jubilant crowds roved through the city singing national songs.
They also recognized the efforts of other East block nations to gain
more freedoms.
   One huge banner reading ``56, 68, 81'' and the national flags of
Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Poland recalled the violent suppression
of reforms in the countries in those years.
   At an official rally attended by 60,000, leading Communist Party
reformer Rezsoe Nyers criticized what he said were attempts by late
Soviet President Leonid I. Brezhnev to choke reform in Eastern
Europe after 1968.
   The Soviets led a Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia that
year to crush communist-led reforms. Similar reforms then were
stifled in Hungary.
   The Hungarian government has increasingly accepted independent
political groups in recent months, and leaders of the Smallholders'
Party and the Social Democrats shared the rostrum with Nyers.
   He drew applause when he charged that the Kremlin largely decided
Hungarian policy from 1948 to 1956.
   Dissident groups have staged unofficial anti-communist rallies on
March 15 since the early 1970s. But in 1986, riot police brutally
dispersed crowds that gathered for that year's events.
   Independent groups that staged Wednesday's unofficial rally in
Budapest refused to celebrate with the cCommunists, arguing that
party members were responsible for past suppression of independent
rallies.
   But Csengey said the separate celebrations did not mean the
independent groups would not work with the communists for reforms.
   Communist Party reformer Imre Pozsgay made similar comments in a
speech at a joint celebration of party and independent groups in
Gyoer in western Hungary.
</TEXT>
