<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-15 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Quick Solution To Budget Stalemate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators warned Wednesday that
their budget talks with the White House won't be resolved quickly.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley said the discussions could
cause Congress to miss its April 15 deadline for approving a fiscal
1990 budget resolution.
   ``I do not expect this to move very fast,'' Foley, D-Wash., who
was attending the talks that resumed on Capitol Hill. ``It has to
move over a period of time. It's a gradual process.''
   ``What we would like to do is meet the April 15 date for a budget
resolution,'' he said. But ``that often has not been possible'' and
a May 15 completion of a fiscal 1990 budget might be more realistic,
he said.
   An agreement by March 23, when the negotiating group is scheduled
to report back to President Bush and the House and Senate
leadership, would be ``very early,'' he said.
   Foley attended the closed-door talks with White House budget
director Richard Darman, the chairmen of the House and Senate budget
committees, and the senior Republicans from those panels.
   On Thursday, top lawmakers from the House and Senate committees
in charge of taxes and entitlements will join the talks.
   ``Simply because we meet with the tax-writing committees does not
in and of itself indicate we are discussing extensive taxes,'' said
Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., the Senate budget chairman.
   The negotiators were trying to learn ``what's realistic by way of
spending restraints or what might be realistic by way of revenue
enhancements, and then go on to judgement further on down the
line,'' he said.
   ``It's not something that's gonig to be resolved in a matter of
two or three days,'' he said.
   ``We haven't really begun what I would call serious
negotiating,'' said Darman, who said the group was making ``no
decisions on anything.''
   ``I would be very surprised if decisions are made as we go along.
I think that the way these things work or don't work is you agree at
the end on a package and it's unlikely that you get specific
decisions made (separately) along the way.''
   Wednesday's session included a review of the spending initiatives
Bush included in the $1.16 trillion spending plan for fiscal 1990,
which he proposed Feb. 9.
   However, at a White House meeting Tuesday with Bush and
congressional leaders, it was agreed the talks will not aim for
agreement on any specific policies. Instead, they agreed the talks
will aim for an overall balance between entitlements, other domestic
programs, military spending and foreign aid, and the amount of new
government revenue that will be raised.
   The talks will also focus first on only fiscal 1990, although
lawmakers and the administration have said it would be desirable to
achieve a two-year pact.
   For fiscal 1990, the Gramm-Rudman law calls for reducing the
deficit to $100 billion. Both Democrats and Republicans agree that
goal can be met without a tax increase, but many Democrats contend
the fiscal 1991 target of $64 billion can't reached without new
taxes.
   ``I myself think it is going to be much easier to reach agreement
on fiscal year 1990 than it is on fiscal year 1991,'' Sasser said
Wednesday, without ruling it out.
   The negotiators Wednesday laid out a schedule for discussing
taxes and entitlements on Thursday, discretionary spending on
Friday, and defense spending next Monday.
</TEXT>
