<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil     03-15 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Strike Ends in Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 48-hour nationwide strike sputtered to
a close Wednesday as millions of workers ignored the call by two
leftist labor federations to stop work in Latin America's largest
country.
   Although the strike tied up public transportation in many cities,
nearly all banks, shops, supermarkets, gas stations and department
stores were open for business.
   Scattered violence was reported in the protest of a
government-imposed wage freeze.
   In Sao Paulo, South America's biggest city, the subway and
commuter train service operated normally. About 1,500 of the city's
4,000 privately owned buses were on the streets Wednesday, compared
to only 800 on the first day of the strike. But the 3,500 buses
owned and operated by the city remained idle.
   Police in Sao Paulo said 30 buses were damaged by rock-throwing
demonstrators and 23 people were arrested on Wednesday.
   In Rio de Janeiro, Brazil's second-largest city, about 300 of the
city's 4,000 privately owned buses ventured out, despite incidents
of rock-throwing by strike supporters.
   However, Rio's subway, commuter ferry and government-run commuter
trains, which carry about 1 million passengers a day, were idle for
a second day.
   The Jornal do Brasil radio station reported three bus passengers
shot and injured two pickets who tried to stop the bus on Rio's poor
north side.
   Workers stuck without regular transportation formed carpools,
hitchhiked, rode bicycles or walked to get to their jobs.
   ``The strike is clearly petering out, and everything indicates a
majority of the state's factory workers are at their jobs,'' said
Luis Carlos Grenadero, a spokesman for Sao Paulo state's Federation
of Industries.
   Granadero said more employees went to work Wednesday than on the
previous day, when the federation said more than 70 percent of the 2
million factory workers in the state showed up at their jobs.
   The national strike command estimated that 70 percent of the
country's 60 million workers were on strike. It acknowledged,
however, that the stoppage had lost much of its momentum in Sao
Paulo.
   In the capital of Brasilia, banks reopened Wednesday after
shutting down the previous day.
   In Vitoria, capital of southeastern Espirito Santo state, police
used rubber truncheons to disperse a group of strikers blocking a
highway. TV footage showed images of police beating and dragging
away a city councilwoman.
   President Jose Sarney's office declined to comment on the strike.
On Tuesday, spokesman Carlos Henrique de Almeida Santos acknowledged
``isolated work stoppages'' in many cities.
   Organizers had pledged to stop all economic activity in major
cities.
   The strike was organized by Brazil's two largest labor movements,
the radical left Central Workers Union and the more moderate General
Workers Central, which claim to represent 35 million workers in
3,000 unions.
   The strike was called to protest a 2-month-old wage freeze, which
formed part of the government's latest economic package aimed at
controlling 1,000 percent inflation.
   Inflation dropped from 28.7 percent in Decemeber to 3.6 percent
for the first 11 days of February, the latest period for which the
government has figures.
   But the economic package slashed workers' purchasing power by up
to 49 percent, claimed Jair Meneguelli, president of the Central
Workers Union.
   More than half of Brazilian workers earn less than $50 a week.
</TEXT>
