<FIRST>r a AM-RecycledMemos     03-15 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Recycled Memos,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Hall To Recycle Memos Into Toilet Paper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Hall memos will be going down the toilet,
literally, in a new recycling program.
   ``You'll all be amused to learn that the memos you get from your
bosses are probably going to end up as toilet paper,'' Kirsten
Svare, spokeswoman for the Department of Streets and Sanitation,
said at training sessions for City Hall employees.
   At the sessions, which ended Wednesday, employees were shown
slides of the paper's uses, including paper towels and toilet paper,
Ms. Svare said.
   ``Everybody laughed,'' she said. ``It's a great laugh.''
   The city will collect the millions of miles of paper produced in
City Hall and sell it to Recycling Services Inc., officials said.
   The company will then sell the recycled raw material to paper
mills across the country to turn it into useable paper products,
officials said.
   ``Most of it is going to be turned into toilet paper,'' Ms. Svare
said in a telephone interview. ``We don't know where the toilet
paper is going to end up. It could end up in your bathroom.''
   At an average cost of $40 per ton for pick-up of office trash,
the City Hall program is expected to save $600 to $1,200 a month,
based upon the expected 15 to 30 tons a month of paper to be
recycled, according to a news release.
   Leroy Bannister, administrative assistant to Mayor Eugene Sawyer,
said the program is serious business.
   ``It is part of the city's overall waste disposal program,'' he
said, adding that last year the city spent $10 million for waste
disposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
