<DOCNO> AP890315-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FlagArt Bjt   03-15 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Flag Exhibit To End, Leaving Legacy of Spectators'
Opinions</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The storm of protest and debate sparked by an
American flag displayed on the floor at a student art exhibit has
become part of the work, as spectators record their opinions in
ledgers inviting comment.
   The exhibit at the School of the Art Institute closes Thursday,
but the disputed piece, ``What is the Proper Way to Display the U.S.
Flag,'' remained a work in progress Wednesday as visitors scribbled
words of anger or encouragement in the blank books.
   In its four weeks on display, the work by ``Dread'' Scott Tyler,
24, has triggered veterans' protests, debate on Capitol Hill,
censure by the state House and a lawsuit dismissed by a Circuit
judge who upheld the school's right to display it.
   Some samples among the hundreds of opinions, most unsigned, that
have been logged in the three ledgers that sit on a wall shelf above
the flag:
   ``You should be put on the floor and walked on.'
   ``Good work at provoking a reaction. That's what art is supposed
to do.''
   ``Don't tread on me.''
   ``This took guts. If you believe in what you did, good for you.''
   ``You skunk _ my father's flag was drapped (sic) over his coffin
...''
   ``It's only a piece of cloth. The idea behind it is good or bad.
I think this is a lot of fuss over nothing.''
   ``Other countries will see us defacing our flag. They will think
we are weak.''
   ``But you got people to think and that's what art is for.''
   ``Watch your back.''
   One visitor congratulated Tyler on enlisting viewers to help
complete the piece with their comments _ ``living history.''
   Another complained about the ``myopia'' of visitors who focus on
Tyler's work and ignore all the other art in the exhibit, which
featured 66 minority-student works, mostly paintings.
   Visitors Wednesday were admitted in small groups for security
reasons and allowed only about 10 minutes at the school's public
gallery, which prompted some grumbling. Many returned to the end of
the short line for another look.
   A few protesters turned out and proudly held American flags high
in front of the Art Institute as security guards sighed with relief
at the prospect of the exhibit's closing Thursday afternoon. Earlier
demonstrations drew more than 2,000 people.
   School spokeswoman Beth Sullivan said the flag is placed on the
floor every morning beneath a black-and-white photomontage and the
shelf containing the ledgers.
   During Wednesday's visit the flag sat neatly folded on the shelf.
   School officials said protesters opposed to the display often
take the flag off the floor soon after the exhibit opens in the
morning and it remains on the shelf until a spectator puts it back
on the floor, and that this is all a part of the work.
   ``It's an appropriate response to pick it up and fold it and for
others to take it down again,'' said Peter Brown, the school's vice
president.
   Veterans and others opposed to the display contend the flag's
placement on the floor invites visitors to walk on it _ a claim
disputed by school officials.
   Robert Mars, the Art Institute's vice president for
administration, successfully pleaded the museum's case before the
Chicago Park District Board's finance committee, which decided
Tuesday not to cut off funds for all eight museums in the city
because of the exhibit.
   ``The bad news is that the flag doesn't mean to the Scott Tylers
of this country what it means to so many of us,'' Mars told the
committee. ``The good news is that our system worked. The student
was allowed to make his statement.''
   Tyler has called his work revolutionary and says he had no
apologies, despite death threats he said he and his mother have
received.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
