<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Judge     03-15 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Judge,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge's Life Takes Him from Corn Patch to Historic Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador-Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SEBASTIAN, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judge Alcides Guandique, who
became the first civilian judge in Salvadoran history to indict
military officers, is proud of his peasant farmer roots.
   ``But I knew I didn't want to return to the corn patch, to
milking cows. I studied hard, because I knew if I didn't pass, I'd
have to go back to that. Studying was like vacation for me,'' he
said.
   The 33-year-old judge was born in a one-room mud brick house in
the village of San Pedro, in the eastern province of San Miguel. Of
his six brothers and sisters, one is a doctor and three are teachers.
   ``Another sister is a `mojada,' in the United States,'' he said,
using the slang for illegal immigrant.
   ``I'm campesino-born, and proud of it,'' said the slight,
engaging official in an interview. He told of how he would go to
school ``with blisters on my hands and my face burned by the sun''
after doing chores.
   The father of two, he credits ``the sacrifice of our parents''
for his and his siblings' success.
   Guandique set a historic precedent Wednesday when he indicted two
army officers in connection with the September massacre of 10
peasant farmers in the nearby village of San Francisco.
   ``It has taken on international transcendence. But to me it's
like any other case. Some people were killed. Campesino lives are
just as valuable as any other lives. Those who did it must be
brought to justice, regardless of their position or power,'' he said.
   The previous judge in San Sebastian resigned late last year,
unwilling to assume the risk involved in pursuing the investigation.
Several judges have been killed while probing alleged military
abuses.
   ``Of course I'm afraid,'' Guandique said. ``Only machines have no
fear. But if I have problems because I equitably apply the law, then
it is not only my problem, but the problem of all judges.''
   Arriving from work at his modest home in Ilopango, a two-hour bus
trip from San Sebastian, Guandique goes first to a hammock and lifts
out 10-month-old baby Alcides, Jr.
   ``And what would you do if they made you a little orphan?'' he
laughingly asks the wide-eyed child in the kind of morbid jest he
says helps him deal with the strain.
   Cecilia, his wife, said, ``I try to give him courage, especially
when his friends tell him to back off, to think about his family and
not get in over his head.''
   But sometimes the couple's resolve fails. As they escorted a
visitor from their home down an alley toward the street, Guandique
stopped at the intersection with another narrow alley.
   ``Here is the kind of place someone could be waiting for me some
night,'' he said.
   Mrs. Guandique, like her husband campesino-born _ stoic and
hearty _ stood silently in the midday sun with tears brimming in her
dark eyes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
