<FIRST>r i AM-Kuwait     03-15 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kuwait,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kuwait Charges 33 With Attempting To Topple Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Kuwait news agency said Wednesday that
33 people were charged with offenses ranging from spying to trying
to topple the government.
   KUNA said those indicted were 18 Kuwaitis, nine Iraqis, two
Iranians, two Lebanese, a Briton of Lebanese origin and a stateless
person.
   It quoted an unidentified spokesman for the state prosecutor as
saying 18 suspects were held, two were free on bail and 13 were at
large.
   The report did not say when the crimes or the arrests took place,
nor did it specify for whom the purported spying was done.
   The names indicated the defendants were Shiite Moslems, the
predominant sect in Iran. Scores of Shiite activists were arrested
and tried in Kuwait during the eight-year war that raged between
Kuwait's Persian Gulf neighbors, Iran and Iraq, until a cease-fire
last August.
   Kuwait accused Iran in the past of inciting acts of terrorism in
this tiny, oil-rich northern gulf state.
   KUNA said the 33 suspects belonged to illegal groups that called
for overthrow of the regime and demeaned Kuwait's emir, Sheik Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah. Some were also charged with divulging defense
secrets, embezzling public money and collusion to commit crimes
including assassination of public figures.
   Some of the charges are punishable by death.
</TEXT>
