<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Movie-CreditCards     03-15 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movie-Credit Cards,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie Patrons Now Can Say `Charge It, Please'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anxious to please the customer with
convenience, if not a good movie, a local movie theater on Friday
will take credit cards for advance and same-day ticket purchases and
for concession stand sales.
   The new AMC Courthouse Plaza 8 Theater is set to become the first
theater in the nation in which this method will be tried, according
to the National Association of Theater Owners.
   ``It's a great convenience, one that customers around the country
have been asking for,'' said Charlie Stoessel, manager of the
theater. He said the theater will accept Visa, MasterCard and
Discover credit cards.
   ``It was done in England, and was a big success,'' Stoessel said
Wednesday.
   According to the plan, a customer can buy tickets over the phone
or at the theater with a credit card. For those who buy their
tickets in advance, there will be a separate window where the
tickets can be picked up.
   Moviegoers also can buy food and drinks at the theater by
purchasing vouchers on their credit card and then cashing them in at
the concession stand. Change will be given in cash.
   ``In other words, you can go to movies without a dime in your
pocket,'' Stoessel said.
   But credit card purchasers can't reserve seats and they must pay
a handling charge of 50 cents per ticket.
   Regardless, Stoessel said AMC Theaters of Kansas City expects
that 30 percent of its sales ultimately will be done by credit card.
   AMC will expand the credit-card policy, which it considers a
test, to its theaters in Union Station in Washington, D.C., said
Dick Dodderidge, senior vice president for corporate marketing.
   Meanwhile, K-B Theaters of Washington said Ticket Center outlets
in May will handle phone reservations for tickets to screenings of
several movies that are expected to draw long lines this summer,
such at ``Batman'' and ``Star Trek V.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
