<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-MissileContract     03-15 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Missile Contract,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed Wins Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy awarded a contract Wednesday to a
division of the Lockheed Corp. for production of Trident II nuclear
missiles, completing a deal worth almost $1 billion to the
California contractor.
   The service, in a brief statement, said the Lockheed Missiles and
Space Co. of Sunnyvale, Calif., would receive a
``cost-plus-incentive-fee contract'' valued at $921.6 million to
produce 64 of the new long-range, submarine-launched missiles.
   ``The work will be performed in Sunnyvale and is expected to be
completed in September 1991,'' the Navy added.
   The award comes at a time when the Navy is preparing its first
test shot of the Trident II from a Trident submarine, the USS
Tennessee, off the coast of Florida. That first submerged test is
expected within the next week or so. Previous tests have been
conducted from launch pads on land at Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   The Trident II has been billed by the Navy as offering a dramatic
improvement in accuracy compared to the Trident I missiles now
deployed on ballistic missile submarines. Lockheed is the developer
and prime contractor of both missiles.
</TEXT>
