<DOCNO> AP890315-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearSecurity     03-15 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Security,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Vows Broader Security Probes Of Agency Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission, responding
to charges of inadequate security controls, told a congressional
panel Wednesday it will take new steps to weed out agency workers
deemed potential risks.
   The NRC said it generally accepted the conclusions of a study by
the General Accounting Office that criticized the practice of
allowing newly hired personnel to start work without security
clearances and of not reinvestigating all veteran workers. The study
said these practices could jeopardize national security.
   The report by the GAO, which is the investigative arm of the
Congress, was released by a House Government Operations subcommittee
that requested the study in 1987.
   Hugh L. Thompson, Jr., the NRC's deputy executive director for
nuclear materials safety, said that while the agecy's personnel
security system is ``essentially sound,'' improvements would be
sought by accepting some of the GAO's recommendations.
   The key change promised by Thompson was to begin regular
reinvestigations of the roughly 50 percent of employees for whom
followup checks are not normally conducted. The other half of
employees are reinvestigated every five years. The agency previously
had cited financial reasons for not doing more reinvestigations.
   The GAO said stricter security controls on NRC employees is
increasingly important in light of recent spy scandals that showed
national security was more likely to be jeopardized by ``insiders''
than by foreign agents or saboteurs.
   ``It is obvious that a substantial tightening is called for'' at
the NRC, said Rep. Chuck Douglas, R-N.H., a member of the House
panel.
   Thompson took issue with one point in the auditors' report. He
said the GAO had overstated the frequency of cases in which newly
hired workers resign or are fired after a belated disclosure of
personal problems such as drug or alcohol abuse.
   The GAO report said about 10 percent of newly hired workers since
1983 left the NRC after background investigations disclosed serious
personal problems. Thompson said the correct figure was 0.5 percent.
Mary Ann Kruslicky, a GAO group director, said later that Thompson's
figure was right, but that the main point was that more thorough and
earlier background checks are needed.
   Responding to suggestions from members of the subcommittee,
Thompson said the NRC will consider checking applicants' fingerprint
records and academic credentials before putting them to work. But he
stressed that it was not practical to wait the 10-12 months required
for a complete background investigation.
   ``NRC believes that without the use of authority to hire
individuals prior to completion of background investigations, the
agency will not be able to continue to attract highly competent
technical and support staff of the calibre we have today,'' he said.
   Thompson acknowledged that 99 percent of newly hired personnel
start work without security clearances.
   The GAO said that its review of personnel security files revealed
several examples of potential security breaches involving workers
who had not gotten security clearances.
   It cited the case of a nuclear reactor engineer who began work
without a clearance in 1985. The worker required a clearance that
would grant access to top-secret national security information, and
in the subsequent investigation it was disclosed that the employee
used heroin and had overdosed on the drug in 1984. The worker
resigned during a one-year probation period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
