<FIRST>u a AM-BombThreat     03-15 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bomb Threat,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Warns Passengers of Bomb Threat, Most Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers aboard a Pan Am flight to Paris were
warned a caller had claimed a bomb was on the plane, but the airline
said Wednesday the caution did not reflect a policy change since the
explosion of a Pan Am plane over Scotland.
   Aviation officials said they were not aware of a previous
instance of an airline warning passengers of a bomb threat. Only 17
of the 200 passengers on the plane chose to take another flight
Monday.
   Pan American spokesman Alan Loflin said the action had nothing to
do with criticism for not warning passengers about an anonymous bomb
threat made against the carrier before Flight 103 exploded over
Scotland Dec. 21.
   ``(Flight) 103 is a whole different situation,'' he said
   The threat called in against Monday's Flight 114 was unusually
specific, Loflin said.
   ``There was never anything that resembled a threat against Pan Am
103. This one on 114 was clearly a threat against 114 by number, by
departure city and by destination,'' Loflin said.
   However, a spokesman for a passenger group said the warning
likely followed pressure over Flight 103. On Dec. 5, an anonymous
caller to the U.S. Embassy in Finland warned a bomb would be aboard
a Pan Am flight traveling from Frankfurt to the United States within
two weeks. Government officials later said the call was a hoax.
   The information was relayed by the State Department to its
overseas employees and Pan Am, and relatives of some of the 259
people killed in the crash were critical that passengers had no such
warning.
   ``I would suspect that the Pan Am 103 flight in December had
something to do with the decision to disseminate the information,''
said David Jeffrey, spokesman for Airline Passengers of America.
``We're certainly glad to see that the airline took the
responsibility of relaying the information.''
   Workers checked the plane and luggage while passengers were taken
to a special room. After the crew agreed the plane was safe to fly,
passengers were told of the threat and given the option of taking
alternate flights. The flight was about 1{ hours late and arrived in
Paris without incident.
   Marilyn Harding, a passenger who switched flights after the
warning, said they weren't told until minutes before boarding.
   ``Who wants to spend eight hours up there just wondering? I think
those people took a real gamble,'' she said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration has no directive on whether
to tell passengers about threats, said agency spokesman Fred Farrar.
   ``Whatever they do is up to them,'' Farrar said.
   Thousands of bomb threats are called into airlines each year, but
virtually all are groundless, he said, adding that he did not know
of any previous passenger warnings.
   Jeffrey said that if all threats were relayed, ``anybody with a
quarter could throw the whole aviation system out of whack.''
   But he said the passenger association believes that if the
threats have been released from security agencies to the general
public, as in the posting of the state department warning, the
public should be told.
</TEXT>
