<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-FarmForecasts     03-15 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Forecasts,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dry Conditions May Continue In Some Prime Farm Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent precipitation and promising forecasts
show ``substantial improvement'' from dry conditions around the
country as the spring planting season nears, but a top federal
forecaster said Wednesday there are still some troubling exceptions
for prime farmland.
   Norton D. Strommen, the chief meteorologist at the Department of
Agriculture, said dry areas with unfavorable forecasts include
portions of central and western Kansas extending into the Oklahoma
and Texas panhandles, California and the Texas gulf coast.
   Another critically dry pocket of prime farmland, covering western
Illinois, eastern and southern Iowa and northern Missouri, however,
has good prospects for rain, Strommen said after a briefing with the
House Agriculture Committee.
   ``We've come a long way in terms of improving sil moisture (since
the devastating 1988 drought),'' Strommen said. ``The signs are very
encouraging we will not have that repeated as we approach the
planting season. It's a much more encouraging picture than we had
any reason to hope for.''
   Among trouble spots, however, are the Oklahoma and Texas
panhandles and an area of western Kansas, where moisture has been
less than 50 percent of normal throughout the winter months,
Strommen said.
   He is also concerned about the dryness that has developed along
the gulf coast, particularly in Texas and extreme southern Florida.
   And after a good early season start on the ``snowpack belt'' in
the West, there has been a ``sharp drying out in January and
February,'' Strommen said.
   Reservoir levels have been drawn down by last summer's drought,
and forecasts indicate it's doubtful California will see a
significant addition to its snowpack before the end of the winter
rainy season in April, Strommen said.
   ``It is an area of great concern to us at this point. They have
already started to restrict some of the water use patterns in
California,'' he said.
   Although this week's rains were ``highly beneficial'' in central
and northern Califoria as far as the winter wheat crop is concerned,
``they did not add a lot to the snowpack situation,'' Strommen said.
   Strommen said there is also concern some of the shallower wells
will not be able to provide adequate water across central portions
of the country, including the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles.
   ``We've seen an increase in top soil moisture, but not enough,''
Strommen said. ``It is enough now to germinate a crop, but it has
not added to deep soil moisture reserves. That means we have not
increased water table levels.''
   There is also concern about reservoir levels in the Southeast,
Strommen said.
</TEXT>
