<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     03-15 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tehran Says Iraq Captured Iranians During Cease-Fire, Denies Truce
Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Wednesday that Iraq captured
hundreds of troops during their cease-fire, and it denied Iraqi
accusations that Iranian troops violated the truce, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   The official Iranian news agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad Hussein Lavasani as saying Iraq
seized 700 troops and a number of civilians since cease-fire began
in August and ended eight years of fighting.
   Lavasani said in a note handed to the Tehran office of the
International Committee of the Red Cross that ``more than six months
have gone by and there has not been any news on the captivity of
these individuals,'' the agency said.
   He appealed to the Swidd-based ICRC to secure ``the immediate
release of these POWs, who were taken captive in violation of the
Third Geneva Convention.''
   Lavasani was quoted as saying Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz
promised Iraq would release these prisoners in the near future
during the first round of cease-fire talks in Geneva in August,
``but this claim had been proven to be a political gesture.''
   Tens of thousands of POWs were taken by Iran and Iraq during the
Persian Gulf war. The two countries are yet to agree whether the
POWs would be released before or as a part of an overall setlement
of their conflict.
   However, both sides have released hundreds of elderly and
war-crippled prisoners of war.
   Iran also denied Wednesday earlier Iraqi accusations that it
violated the cease-fire, IRNA reported.
   It quoted an unnamed source at Iran's Armed Forces Command
Headquarters as saying the cease-fire was violated by Iraqi forces
late Monday night when they shelled three Iranian cities across the
southern border.
   The source said Iraqi forces opened fire on the city of
Shalamcheh, and extended the shelling to the port of Khorramshahr.
The Iranians did not return fire until the Iraqis started shelling
Khorramshahr and then Abadan, a key industrial city, IRNA said.
   The source said the United Nations cease-fire monitoring force
watched the whole incident, in which five Iranian troops were
wounded.
   He said Iran reported 14 cease-fire violations between Feb. 20
and March 10 to the U.N. monitoring group.
   An Iraqi military spokesman said the Iranians shelled the
positions of an infantry division in the southern port city of
Basra, official Baghdad radio reported on Tuesday. The radio said
the U.N. observers did not comment on the incident but confirmed an
Iraqi complaint had been registered.
   The two belligerents agreed in January to form a joint military
committee to help the U.N. observers consolidate the cease-fire
agreement, but it has not yet held any meetings.
   On Tuesday, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati proposed
that peace talks with Iraq should resume in the third week of April.
   United Nations-sponsored peace talks in the 8-year gulf war
started five days after the U.N.-mediated cease-fire took effect
Aug. 20, but the talks broke down immediately over the issue of
Iraqi troop withdrawals and the status of the Shatt-Al-Arab waterway.
   According to United Nations estimates, Iraqi troops still occupy
about 260 square miles of Iranian territory.
</TEXT>
