<FIRST>u i AM-NATO-Soviet     03-15 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Soviet,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Report Says Soviets Unlikely to Close Technological Gap With
West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even if Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic
reforms succeed, the Soviet Union won't be able to bridge the
technological gap with the West by the year 2000, said a NATO report
released Wednesday.
   The report, drawn up by U.S. experts, said Gorbachev's drive to
restructure the economy will make some progress but not as much as
the Soviets predict.
   ``Even if Gorbachev wins, the gains from new technology and
enhanced labor productivity will not suffice to narrow the gap with
the West during the remainder of this century,'' said the report,
prepared for the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   It also said poor weather could ``trigger an agricultural failure
severe enough to exacerbate current consumer dissatisfaction and
threaten the success of Gorbachev's reform effort.''
   Another NATO report released Wednesday said the failure of
perestroika to produce major changes gives the Kremlin ``cogent
reasons'' to pare the amount of money devoted to defense in its
five-year plan for 1991 to 1995.
   ``Barring an unlikely turnaround in the economy,'' it said, ``we
would expect the pressure to hold down defense spending to continue
during 1991-95.''
   The report noted Gorbachev's promises to slash defense spending
by 14.2 percent but said no details have been released on where
those cuts would be made or during what period of time.
   It estimated Soviet defense expenditures grew at an average
annual rate of just under 2 percent during 1975-87. Outlays in 1975
were 90 billion to 95 billion rubles, or $145 billion to $153
billion at the official exchange rate. They rose to 110 billion to
120 billion rubles in 1987, or $178 billion to $194 billion. The
figures were adjusted for inflation.
   The analysts said the defense sector was a heavy drain on the
Soviet economy, absorbing 15 percent to 17 percent of the gross
domestic product, the total economic output, in the mid-1980s. In
comparison, U.S. defense spending was about 6.5 percent of economic
output, it said.
   ``The burden of defense falls unevenly across the Soviet economy
and is especially heavy in those civilian sectors where needs are
greatest if Gorbachev is to succeed in modernizing industry,'' it
said.
   Military development and production capture a large number of the
best scientists, technologists, engineers and skilled technicians.
Moreover, military facilities have better access to electronic
components, special steels, non-ferrous metals, chemicals and oil
products, it said.
   In the economic study, analysts used a CIA economic model to look
at three alternatives for growth from 1986 to 2000.
   The most positive _ ``Gorbachev wins'' _ projects the stagnant
economy will pick up to expand at a healthy 2.9 percent average
annual rate in the period from 1991 to 2000. To achieve that rate,
reforms would have to be successful and weather conditions good for
farming.
   A ``Gorbachev loses'' outlook sees the economy expanding at a
poor 1.6 percent annually from 1991 to 2000.
   A third scenario of ``Gorbachev doesn't matter'' predicts growth
of 1.5 percent annually in that same period.
</TEXT>
