<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soviet     03-15 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>American-Born Soviet Refusenik Arrives in Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago native who moved to the Soviet Union
in 1931 said he felt overwhelmed when he arrived in Israel
Wednesday, ending a 13-year struggle to emigrate.
   Abe Stolar, 78, landed at Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion Airport with his
wife, son, daughter-in-law and two grandchildren.
   ``It's all too much to take in at once,'' he told reporters.
   Stolar and his parents left Chicago for the Soviet Union when he
was 19 because ``my parents were Communists and they were
disillusioned with life in the United States during the Great
Depression,'' he said. ``My father believed he could help the Soviet
Union.''
   Stolar said he was a loyal Soviet soldier during World War II,
but he became fed up with life in his adopted nation after the war
ended in 1945.
   He said he found anti-Semitism rampant in Soviet society and
believed he was dismissed from a job with Radio Moscow's English
language division after the war because he is Jewish.
   ``I began to read literature about the Holocaust and Jewish
history,'' after leaving the radio station, Stolar said. ``I began
to identify with the Jewish people.''
   Stolar applied for a visa to leave the Soviet Union in 1974 and
was granted permission in June 1975.
   But as he and his family were about to board a plane to Europe,
the KGB stopped them, saying Stolar's wife, Gita, had access to
state secrets in her job as a chemist at a geology institute.
   Stolar tried to enlist the support of world leaders in his fight
to leave the Soviet Union after he was repeatedly denied another
emigration visa.
   Last year President Reagan made a personal appeal to Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev for Stolar's release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
