<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0736 03-15 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Stake New West Bank Settlement, Guerrillas Caught</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Taba, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th pvs, `Anti-Israeli...' with to UPDATE with another
wounded. Pick up 14th pvs, `Since the...' Edits throughout to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALMON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish settlers drove a mobile
home up a hillside through rain and hail Wednesday to stake a new
settlement in the occupied West Bank.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, two teen-age Palestinian guerrillas
were captured after they infiltrated from Egypt and attacked an
Israeli military outpost with a rifle and grenades. They were
wounded, but no troops were hurt, the army said.
   A handful of religious Jewish settlers arrived at Talmon, a
hilltop spot 12 miles from Jerusalem in the heart of the West Bank,
where Palestinians have been rebelling against Israeli rule for the
last 15 months.
   ``This place belongs to us,'' said one settler, Yachanan Indech,
25. ``All this land was mentioned in the Bible.''
   But he said the main importance of the site was strategic.
   ``If it were a clear day, you could see the whole city of Tel
Aviv from this hilltop, without a telescope,'' he said. ``With a
small weapon, you could hit any plane that lands at the
international airport.''
   Indech said that by the end of the week, 12 families with
children would move to the site.
   Soldiers were stationed on the hilltop to protect the new
settlement, and the settlers planned to circle the site with coils
of barbed wire before nightfall.
   The Jewish activists vowed that seven more of the controversial
settlements would be established in the occupied territory during
the next four years, as promised by the government.
   The United States has said the 130 Jewish settlements and 80,000
settlers already in the occupied lands constitute a major stumbling
block to peace. About 1.7 million Arabs live in the territories.
   Anti-Israeli protests continued in the occupied territories, and
at least eight Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes with
troops, Arab reports and hospital officials said. The army said it
was checking the reports.
   Since the beginning of the uprising in December 1987, 396
Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed.
   The two Palestinian infiltrators slipped across the southern
border before dawn, the army said.
   A military source who spoke on condition of anonymity said their
attack failed when a grenade hurled at the military outpost rolled
back onto the guerrillas' position and exploded, injuring at least
one of the Arabs. Soldiers opened fire after hearing an explosion,
the source said.
   The guerrillas, ages 15 and 17, were wounded and captured, the
army said.
   During interrogation the teen-agers said they were members of the
fundamentalist Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, the army said in
a statement.
   Military sources said they were planning to kill soldiers, take
hostages and return to Egypt.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, head of Israel's southern command,
charged that the attack was carried out with the knowledge of PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat and his Fatah guerrillas but without help
from the Egyptians.
   ``According to the terrorists being questioned ... (they went)
with the knowledge of Fatah, and with the knowledge of Abu Ammar,''
or Arafat, Mordechai said.
   He praised the Egyptians for helping find the route the
guerrillas had taken and mounting a search for accomplices.
   It was the third foiled guerrilla raid this week following two in
Lebanon. It came after U.S. officials reportedly sought to work out
a cease-fire between Israel and the Palestine Liberation
Organization to stop infiltrations from Lebanon.
   Attempts to arrange a cease-fire were reported by the
English-language Jerusalem Post newspaper before Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens left for the United States on March 10.
   Army officials say at least 30 guerrillas have been killed in
southern Lebanon this year while attempting to cross into Israel.
Five were killed in the two attempts earlier this week.
   The United States has asked the PLO to halt such attacks, but the
group has said that raids on military targets were not included when
Arafat renounced terrorism last year.
</TEXT>
