<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Buyers Bjt   03-15 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Buyers, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Possible Eastern Sale Becomes Stronger Option for Lorenzo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of Eastern Airlines is an increasingly
likely option for parent Texas Air Corp. as the crippling strike
against the carrier continues with no sign of resolution, experts
said Wednesday.
   On the 12th day of a bitter strike by Eastern's Machinists union,
the airline still was operating only a fraction of its normal
flights. Most of Eastern's pilots have continued honoring the strike
despite appeals and warnings from management, making it virtually
impossible for the airline to expand service.
   Eastern sought protection from creditors last Thursday under
Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act. But financial analysts and
other observers suggested that Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo
would have difficulty rebuilding Eastern through Chapter 11 and may
be reaching a point where he is obliged to sell the ailing carrier
to stem his losses.
   The strongest potential buyer remains financier Carl Icahn, the
owner and chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., according to labor
and financial sources close to the situation who asked not to be
identified.
   Icahn expressed interest in buying Eastern last October and the
Machinists said last week that they want him to explore a possible
buyout. By acquiring Eastern, Icahn could use the airline's
north-south routes as possible feeders into TWA's trans-Atlantic
routes.
   Another possible buyer is Grandview, a group of investors and
former corporate executives, the sources said. The group's strongest
suit is said to be management expertise, giving it the belief that
it could negotiate contracts with Eastern's unions that Lorenzo was
unable to get.
   Icahn and representatives of Grandview did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
   Some major airlines also have been rumored to be looking at
Eastern, but the stories have been denied by spokesmen for the
carriers.
   Eastern's value to potential buyers is its assets _ planes,
airport gates, lucrative New York-Florida routes. Other carriers
believe they could deploy them more effectively than Lorenzo has,
and thus turn the airline around.
   Lorenzo, who controls Eastern through his Texas Air holding
company, has become a lightning rod for employees' anger.
   Lorenzo has asked his investment bankers at Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. to gauge potential interest in buying Eastern among
investors and other airlines, according to the sources.
   Although Texas Air has attempted to gauge buying interest in the
past, the latest development seemed to indicate a more serious
attempt to find a potential buyer, some financial analysts said.
   Some airline union leaders saw it as a possible admission of
defeat by Lorenzo, but they conceded it could be a tactical maneuver.
   ``We'd love to see him find a buyer for Eastern,'' said Jim
Conley, a spokesman for the International Association of Machinists
at the union's Washington headquarters.
   Drexel declined to confirm that it had been approached by Lorenzo.
   Houston-based Texas Air said in a statement: ``Texas Air has
dealt with many investment bankers in the past, including Drexel
Burnham. Beyond that, Texas Air is only doing what it prudently
should in exercising its fiduciary responsibility to its
shareholders and its creditors.''
   Some observers say the pressure on Lorenzo to sell the airline
intensified Tuesday when the Air Line Pilots Association threw a
crimp into any Eastern effort to sell it piecemeal. ALPA, the
national pilots union, announced that its members would refuse to
fly Eastern routes for a carrier that purchased Eastern planes or
routes unless Eastern pilots were hired by that carrier.
   ALPA's executive board also said it had authorized strike benefit
payments of $2,400 a month plus interest-free loans for every
Eastern pilot honoring the Machinists' picket lines.
   The pilots' continuing refusal to cross picket lines has
``clearly limited (Lorenzo's) options,'' said Ron Cole, a spokesman
for the Eastern pilots union in Miami.
</TEXT>
