<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Appointments     03-15 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Appointments,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Name China Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has selected James Roderick
Lilley as his ambassador to the People's Republic of China,
succeeding Ambassador Winston Lord, the White House said Wednesday.
   Lilley, a longtime foreign service official, served as ambassador
to South Korea from 1986 until this past January.
   Previously he held a number of posts in Asia, including the
government's senior intelligence position on China, serving as
national intelligence officer for China in 1975.
   Bush was the U.S. liaison officer in China during 1975-76 before
the government had full diplomatic relations with the Chinese
   Lilley has served in U.S. missions in the Philippines, Taiwan,
Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, Hong Kong and China.
   In 1981, he worked for President Reagan's National Security
Council as political coordinator and senior east Asian specialist.
From 1984 to 1985 he was an international security consultant for
the Pentagon, and then during 1985-86 was deputy assistant secretary
of state for East Asian and Pacific affairs.
   Bush also announced Wednesday his choice of anti-abortion
activist Kay Coles James as assistant secretary for Health and Human
Services.
   Since 1985, Mrs. James has been public affairs director for the
National Right to Life Committee in Washington. She is also
president of BlackAmericans for Life.
   Her appointment is expected to assuage the concerns of
conservatives who were upset with Bush's selection of Dr. Louis
Sullivan as secretary of Health and Human Services.
   Sullivan had aroused their ire when he indicated a pro-choice
view in an interview. He has since said he shares Bush's position
opposed to abortion except in the case of rape,incest, or
endangerment to the mother's life.
</TEXT>
