<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 03-15 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0782,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Said to Have Approved Aid to Honduras for Helping Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: `Reagan made,' to CORRECT spelling
of Suazo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan in 1985 not only approved a
secret pact to give Honduras more than $110 million for helping the
Nicaraguan Contras but he also telephoned Honduras' president when
the Honduran military delayed an ammunition shipment to the rebels,
the Oliver North jury was told Wednesday.
   Reagan made a note of his call to Roberto Suazo that said the
Honduran ``will call his military commander to tell him to deliver
the ammunition,'' former national security adviser Robert McFarlane
testified at the Oliver North trial. The ammunition then got to the
guerrillas.
   Under questioning by defense lawyers, McFarlane detailed how
Reagan initialed a plan in mid-February 1985 that resulted in
Honduras getting speeded-up deliveries of rifles, ammunition and
machines.
   It was a ``quid pro quo'' arrangement that Reagan was advised
would ``provide incentives'' to the Hondurans for helping out.
   ``You're going to give them tens of millions of dollars to
cooperate?'' North lawyer Brendan Sullivan asked McFarlane.
   ``Yes,'' the witness said.
   ``There is nothing dirty about quid pro quo, is there?''
   ``No.''
   Later, reading from a previously secret memo, Sullivan referred
to ``$75 million in economic assistance.'' He also referred to $35
million in expedited militarty aid.
   The matter was so sensitive, McFarlane acknowledged under
questioning, that the arrangement was discussed verbally by the U.S.
ambassador in Honduras with Suazo and was not given to him in
writing.
   North's lawyers say the Reagan administration had a policy of
hiding such arrangements with other countries to support the Contras
during a two-year period in which the so-called the Boland Amendment
prohibited U.S. military aid to the guerrillas.
   Wednesday was McFarlane's fourth day on the witness stand and he
was admonished frequently by the judge to rely on his own memory,
rather than parroting documents that were shown to him to
``refresh'' his often vague recollection. His lawyer said afterward
that the witness had not seen some of those papers since they were
created in 1984 and 1985.
   McFarlane, who was North's boss at the National Security Council
until December 1985, will return Thursday for more cross-examination.
   Sullivan brought out that on May 29, 1987, testifying on Capitol
Hill long after details of the American dealings with Honduras had
become public, McFarlane clung to his story that no one in the U.S.
government had contacted Central American leaders to aid the Contras.
   ``Obviously we have embassies in all these countries,'' he said
then. ``I don't know of any direction from Washington to those
embassies to seek out aid to the Contras.''
   Asked Wednesday whether he regarded the arrangement with Honduras
acceptable in light of the Boland restrictions, McFarlane replied
that ``the president took that (action).''
   Sullivan: The amendment states that people involved in the
intelligence communities cannot assist the Contras.
   McFarlane: It didn't seem to me that he was in any way a member
of the intelligence community.
   Five of the criminal charges against North, the former National
Security Council aide, are that he made false statements and
obstructed Congress in 1985 and 1986 with regard to his activities
on behalf of the Contras.
   McFarlane had told the National Security Council staff, including
North, that the congressional amendment applied to the NSC.
   ``The president of the United States had a much more different
view of the Boland Amendment than you do?'' Sullivan asked.
   When McFarlane answered yes, Sullivan pressed: ``A much more
liberal view?''
   ``We were pretty close.''
   In a recent question-and-answer session with North prosecutors,
the former president maintained, as he had all along, that he relied
on a 1985 legal opinion that ``concluded that the Boland Amendment
did not apply to the actions of the NSC staff.''
   North has insisted he always acted with superiors' authority and
the questioning was an effort to show the wide knowledge among top
officials of his efforts in behalf of the Contras.
   Reagan initialed his approval of the Honduran plan on Feb. 18,
1985. On April 25, according to the testimony, McFarlane recommended
that Reagan phone Suazo because ``the Honduran military this morning
stopped a shipment of ammunition'' and that it ``must continue if
the resistance is to survive.''
   That day, Reagan wrote on the bottom of the memo that Suazo
``expressed his respect for me. He believes we must continue to
oppose communism. He will call his military commander and tell him
to deliver the ammunition.''
   At the time of the quid pro quo arrangements, Honduras was
harboring many of the Contras in camps along the country's southern
border, and Honduran officials feared Sandinista troops might come
across the border from Nicaragua.
   There was a temporary halt in the trial as North's lawyers tried
to introduce classified material while cross-examining McFarlane.
   Gesell said he will rule on a piecemeal basis in connection with
the information North's attorneys want to present in cross-examining
McFarlane, rather in advance as requested by chief trial prosecutor
John Keker.
   He also permitted North's lawyers to introduce the names of
Central American countries and Central American officials in
documents that spell out quid pro quo arrangements with Honduras and
other countries.
</TEXT>
