<FIRST>r a AM-Discovery-Boosters     03-15 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Discovery-Boosters,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Booster Joint Heater Failed Before Discovery Launch, NASA Official
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint heater on one of Morton Thiokol's two
booster rockets failed hours before the Monday launch of the space
shuttle Discovery, but a backup heater worked, a NASA official said
Wednesday.
   Royce Mitchell, manager of Thiokol's shuttle motor program for
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, said he learned
of cooling, indicating heater failure in the aft field joint of the
right booster, about midnight before the launch.
   ``It had all the appearances of a high-current short,'' Mitchell
said in a telephone interview from Huntsville, Ala. The cause of the
electrical surge was unknown Wednesday.
   The short apparently either damaged the heater itself or wiring,
Mitchell said. A backup heater was turned on.
   Overall, he said, officials were pleased with the performance of
the boosters.
   Flight data and a look at the motors, which were retrieved
Tuesday from the Atlantic Ocean, showed they performed well and did
not have any cork insulation loss like that suspected of damaging
orbiters on the previous two shuttle flights.
   ``They were certainly right down the line,'' Mitchell said.
   The boosters burned just 1.4 seconds longer than predicted during
the two minutes the boosters are used.
   ``We're very pleased with that kind of performance,'' Mitchell
said.
   ``We did not compromise any safety figures,'' Mitchell said of
the decision to proceed with launch. ``We had played this `What if?'
game'' before in tests of such an occurrence.
   On Dec. 8, a heater shorted on a booster being prepared for test
firing at Thiokol's Wasatch Operations plant west of Brigham City.
   The heaters, part of a redesign of the motors prompted by
destruction of the shuttle Challenger in 1986, maintain resiliency
of O-ring seals in the three field joints of each motor. Each heater
has a backup.
   External inspection of the motors after their return to land
Tuesday showed no evidence of hot exhaust gases escaping the seals,
Mitchell said.
</TEXT>
