<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Party 1stLd-Writethru a0689 03-15 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,0927</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Solution to Soviet Food Problem Years Away</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with details on Gorbachev speech.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Wednesday that
all Soviet farmers should be permitted to lease their land and
decide what to plant in a new national program to ease chronic food
shortages. But he said it will be years before the country can feed
itself.
   Gorbachev called food shortages ``our society's biggest wound.''
Meat, sugar and many other foodstuffs must be rationed in numerous
Soviet regions.
   In a tacit acknowledgement that one of his earlier attempts to
rejuvenate Soviet agriculture had failed, Gorbachev proposed
abolishing a government superagency created in 1985 to oversee the
country's farm sector.
   The Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee, convened
by party General Secretary Gorbachev, began a two-day meeting
Wednesday largely devoted to agricultural reform. It will look for
ways to increase the food supply and improve traditionally dreary
rural life.
   Gorbachev asked the committee to approve ``an agrarian policy
that will be able to restore the peasant as the master on the land,
and dependably solve the food problem.''
   ``Further delay in this matter is simply inadmissible,'' he said.
   The 58-year-old Kremlin leader, the former party overseer for
agriculture and the son of a southern Russian peasant, said
conditions in some rural regions were at a ``critical level,'' with
mass migration of their populations to cities.
   He said farm productivity is so low the Soviet Union must go
abroad to buy ``large quantities of grain, meat, fruits, vegetables,
sugar, vegetable oil and some other staples'' to meet demand at home.
   Losses of grain due to inefficiency total 40 million metric tons
_ equal to Soviet grain purchases abroad, Gorbachev said. He
endorsed focusing on making Soviet farming and food processing work
better, rather than on increasing the area under cultivation.
   In 1988, gross Soviet farm output rose only 0.7 percent, and the
grain harvest was only 195 million metric tons, 16 million below the
annual average achieved in 1986-87, according to Washington,
D.C.-based PlanEcon Inc., which studies Soviet economic performance.
   Gorbachev said the ruling Politburo would ask the 300-member
Central Committee for ``extensive transition to leasing,'' or
allowing work collectives and individuals to work state-owned
farmland in exchange for a fee.
   Western analysts say leasing benefits would be largely annulled
if Moscow-based bureaucrats retain the right to dictate which crops
should be planted on individual plots and in which quantities, but
Gorbachev said lease-holders should be given a virtual free hand.
   ``Let us not fix assignments, let us not set deadlines,''
Gorbachev said. Gorbachev, who first proposed leasing last June,
said ``all units of the farm'' should work on the lease principle.
He has said leasing guarantees higher production because
lease-holders can earn more if they work harder, rather than getting
a fixed salary regardless of output as has been traditional on
Soviet state and collective farms.
   Gorbachev said ``more flexible prices'' for crops purchased by
the state would go into effect next Jan. 1, and the number of
products for which prices are fixed by bureaucrats would be reduced.
   He reassured Soviet consumers prices will stay the same for the
next ``two or three years'' for bread, flour, cereals, meat, fish,
eggs, milk, sugar, butter, vegetable oils and baby foods, despite
the admitted pressing need for price reform to curtail state
subsidies.
   One proposal calls for abolishment of the State Agro-Industrial
Committee, created in November 1985, eight months after Gorbachev
was named Soviet leader.
   He said the giant agency would be replaced by a commission of the
Council of Ministers, or Soviet cabinet.
   While calling for urgent measures to improve the Soviet diet,
Gorbachev said a definite end to food shortages could not be
expected until the middle of next decade.
   Gorbachev's one-hour, 45-minute speech on agriculture was later
shown on state-run television.
   The Central Committee earlier moved to formally elect its top
leaders and other representatives, including Gorbachev, to the
nation's new parliament.
   The Communist Party is one of 30 organizations with the power to
choose one-third of the 2,250 representatives in the new Congress of
People's Deputies.
   Despite publicity touting this campaign as the Soviet Union's
first election with competing candidates, the party chose to
nominate just 100 persons for its 100 seats. Party members had
suggested more than 31,000 names.
   The food problem is likely to produce far more discussion at the
Central Committee plenum, since the party's conservative agriculture
chief, Yegor K. Ligachev, apparently disagrees with Gorbachev on a
solution.
   Ligachev has said little about Gorbachev's call for leasing,
instead emphasizing collective farming _ the system that has left
Soviets standing in line for meat and vegetables.
   Gorbachev said Wednesday increased investment to modernize
collective farms was not enough, that huge capital investments in
agriculture in recent years ``failed to yield equally substantial
results.''
   No one, however, proposed letting farmers own outright the land
they till, or the breakup of the giant collective and state farms
that have been the backbone of the Soviet agricultural system since
the days of Josef V. Stalin.
   Gorbachev said such farms can work with the right management
techniques.
   Living standards in the Soviet countryside are far lower than in
cities. Gorbachev said drastic improvements were needed.
   Tass said the Central Committee would reconvene Thursday to
discuss Gorbachev's report on agriculture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0789 03-15 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Allow Priests to Return, News Show to Reopen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to include Honduran plans to demobilize Contras;
picks up 4th pvs `In addition...' SUBS grafs 12-13 pvs, `Ortega also...Ortega
said' with 3 grafs with details. Pick up 14th pvs, `Government sources...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Wednesday
his leftist government will allow a Roman Catholic church radio news
program to resume and will let 10 expelled priests return to
Nicaragua.
   ``We are trying to create a better climate in our country that
strengthens the tendency towards total and definitive peace that the
Nicaraguan people demand,'' Ortega said after meeting with Cardinal
Miguel Obando y Bravo, head of the Nicaraguan church.
   In neighboring Honduras, President Jose Azcona Hoyo said his
government was working on a plan to demobilize thousands of
Nicaraguan rebels in camps near the border, and he denied reports
that the United States has asked the government to let them stay
another year.
   ``Honduras is interested in demobilizing the Contras because
their departure from our territory is in the benefit of national
security,'' he told reporters.
   Azcona Hoyo and the four other Central American presidents agreed
last month to repatriate the rebels or move them to third countries.
Nicaragua said it would move up elections scheduled for November
1990 and take other steps toward greater democracy.
   Ortega said Wednesday that Radio Catolica's ``Iglesia'' news
program, shut down by the Sandinista government July 11, would be
allowed to resume immediately.
   In addition to the shutdown, the leftist government in July
expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other U.S.
diplomats from Nicaragua, arrested at least 40 people at a major
opposition demonstration and closed the opposition newspaper La
Prensa for 15 days.
   Ortega announced the government would allow 10 priests to return
to Nicaragua and would review a list of other priests barred from
the country to determine whether they could return.
   The Sandinistas expelled the 10 priests between 1982 and 1985 for
allegedly plotting against the government.
   Those priests eligible to return to Nicaragua are: Francisco
Castelli, Vicente Caudeli, Francisco San Martin, Santiago de Anitua
and Luis Corrales of Spain; Vicente Huerta, Jose Montero and Jose
Maria Pacheco of Costa Rica; Mario Fiandri of Italy; and Mario
Madriz of Panama.
   Monsignor Bismarck Carballo, director of Radio Catolica, told The
Associated Press Wednesday the government might grant entry to five
more priests it had expelled. Carballo did not identify the priests.
   Obando y Bravo told Ortega that a government amnesty should be
extended to all jailed members of the former National Guard and
political prisoners, Ortega said.
   The National Assembly on Tuesday approved amnesty for 1,894
former guardsmen, most of whom had been jailed since the 1979
revolution that brought the Sandinistas to power.
   The assembly refused to grant an amnesty for 39 former guardsmen
who, it said, had committed ``atrocious crimes'' against the
Nicaraguan people.
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that Robert M. Kimmit, U.S.
undersecretary of state for political affairs, formally asked
Honduras on Monday to let the Contras stay for another year.
   But Azcona said Wednesday, ``We only talked about humanitarian
aid for the Contras.''
   Ortega said Wednesday that more U.S. humanitarian aid for the
rebels would violate the Central American peace plan. Only aid
designed to dismantle the guerrilla army is acceptable under the
regional accords, he said.
   Government sources in Washington and rebel leaders have said the
Bush administration plans to ask for a 12-month humanitarian aid
package for the rebels that totals between $40 million and $50
million.
   ``This runs against the accords we Central American presidents
signed in El Salvador, and we cannot let it pass peacefully,''
Ortega said of the reported aid request. He spoke with reporters
after a meeting with Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo.
   Ortega and the presidents of Honduras, El Salvador, Guatemala and
Costa Rica agreed at the Feb. 13-14 summit to draft a plan to
demobilize the Contras, about 11,000 of whom are in base camps in
Honduras.
   In turn, Ortega pledged to institute democratic reforms in
Nicaragua and move up general elections by 10 months, to February
1990.
   A $27 million package of rebel humanitarian assistance approved
by Congress last year runs out at the end of March.
   The United States has supported the Contras since 1981 in their
war to oust the leftist Sandinista government. The Contras fled to
Honduras after U.S. military assistance expired in February 1988.
   The Sandinistas and Contras signed a provisional cease-fire pact
in March 1988 that has been unilaterally extended on a monthly basis
by the government. The Contras have tacitly accepted the extensions,
but talks on a permanent cease-fire have stalled.
</TEXT>
