<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bechtel     03-15 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bechtel,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Global Master-Builder Stephen Bechtel Sr. Dead at 88</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those who knew him and the global works of
his construction dynasty took stock on Wednesday of the energetic
life of master-builder Stephen Bechtel Sr.
   ``This guy was a builder,'' said former San Francisco Mayor
Joseph Alioto. ``This was a guy who moved the Earth.''
   Bechtel, 88, died Tuesday in Merritt Peralta Medical Center in
Oakland after a brief illness.
   From the construction business his father built out of the ashes
of San Francisco's earthquake of 1906, Bechtel created one of the
world's largest engineering and construction firms, the privately
held Bechtel Group Inc.
   The company built Hoover Dam, pipelines, mines, whole seaports
and harbors, scores of hotels, towering buildings and transportation
systems on seven continents. Among its projects still under
construction is Jubail, an entire Saudi Arabian city of 250,000.
   In World War II, a Bechtel project turned out 560 ships for the
Navy.
   Fortune Magazine called him ``the boldest and maybe the biggest
builder in the world.''
   He retired as board chairman in 1965 but continued as senior
director and roving ambassador for the company. He never completely
retired.
   ``My father was a remarkable man,'' said Stephen Bechtel Jr., who
took over as chairman of Bechtel Group Inc. ``He was also the best
of fathers.''
   Born in Aurora, Ind., in 1900, Stephen Davison Bechtel was a
world business leader who knew presidents, prime ministers and kings
on a first-name basis.
   Bechtel in 1949 overheard an oil company executive remark that a
pipeline from Alberta, Canada, across the Rockies to the Pacific was
a great idea. Bechtel sketched out the plan on the tablecloth.
   A few years later, 80,000 barrels of oil flowed through the
718-mile Canadian Trans-Mountain Pipeline. It was called one of the
most remarkable pipeline engineering feats in history.
   Bechtel managed construction of the four-county Bay Area Rapid
Transit system, and the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, which
Bechtel commuted over from his Oakland home every working day.
   Despite the crush of bridge traffic, which sets most motorists
griping, Bechtel thought it was quite a nice thing to do every day
on the way to his 32nd-floor office in the company's San Francisco
headquarters.
   ``It's a very pleasant ride, and traffic isn't that bad'' he told
a reporter in a rare interview.
   Bechtel was one of the University of California at Berkeley's
most successful dropouts. In a hurry to get on with his vision, he
quit college in 1920, but the university named him Alumnus of the
Year in 1952.
   Berkeley Chancellor Ira Michael Heyman hailed Bechtel's ``loyalty
and generosity'' to the university, particularly in establishing a
$6.3 million engineering center.
   Bechtel leaves his widow, Laura, and their two children, Stephen
and Barbara Bechtel Davies. Funeral services were private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-McGivern     03-15 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McGivern,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Cop-Killer Granted Parole in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTISVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted cop-killer awarded clemency by
Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1985 won parole Wednesday, in a case that has
fed the controversy over efforts to restore the death penalty in the
state.
   Gary McGivern, 44, could leave the medium-security prison here by
the end of the week, parole board officials said. He was convicted
13{ years ago in the 1968 shooting death of William Fitzgerald.
   Michael Kavanagh, who prosecuted McGivern and co-defendant
Charles Culhane, said the parole board's decision was ``a real
tragedy'' and ``a sad commentary on our criminal justive system.''
   McGivern had twice previously been denied parole.
   Some law enforcement officials who critisized McGivern's parole
said it might nudge state legislators who are considering whether to
override a Cuomo veto of legislation to restore New York's death
penalty.
   ``That's just wishful thinking,'' Cuomo said at a news
conference. ``Advocates of the death penalty will tell you that a
leaf that fell from the tree was a sign.''
   The state's electric chair hasn't been used since 1963; Cuomo has
successfully vetoed death penalty legislation for the past six years.
   While McGivern was viewed by many as an unrepentant cop-killer,
he had some well-known and vocal supporters, including folk singer
Pete Seeger, conservative columnist William F. Buckley and civil
rights lawyer William Kunstler.
   ``It's been a long haul. I've been in this for 13{ years,'' said
Kuntsler. ``I'm happy for Gary, his wife and his family.''
   Through three trials, McGivern and Culhane have steadfastly
maintained their innocence in the death of Fitzgerald, a Westchester
County deputy.
   Fitzgerald was shot during an escape attempt by McGivern, Culhane
and a third inmate, Robert Bowerman, who were being driven to a
court date by Fitzgerald and another officer.
   At the time, McGivern and Culhane were serving sentences for
robbing a gas station together. They claimed Bowerman acted alone;
Kavanagh said McGivern fired the shot that killed Fitzerald.
   McGivern wasn't granting interviews Wednesday, but Culhane said
``that's wonderful'' when told the news.
   ``It's about time. He'll do good out there,'' said Culhane, an
award-winning prison poet and dramatist.
   Culhane was not eligible for a parole hearing until late 1991.
   The parole board said it was releasing McGivern for good conduct.
   ``It was felt that Mr. McGivern could live and remain at liberty
without violating the law,'' said an statement read by Edward Elwin,
the board's executive director.
   McGivern plans to live with Marguerite Culp, a former newspaper
reporter who met McGivern in prison and married him in a prison-yard
ceremony a decade ago, Elwin said.
   McGivern and Culhane's first trial ended in a hung jury. Their
second ended with death sentences, but those convictions were
overturned. The two were convicted after a third trial in 1975.
   ``It was a very difficult call,'' Cuomo said of his clemency
ruling. ``This man is not a cop killer.''
   Cuomo's action drew criticism from then-Vice President George
Bush.
</TEXT>
