<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-O'Connor-Christians     03-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-O'Connor-Christians,1st ld-writethru, a0713,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 18th graf to CORRECT spelling of Frankfurter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said
Wednesday she regrets a letter she wrote that has been used by
conservative Republicans in her home state of Arizona to support
their claim that the United States is ``a Christian nation.''
   ``I regret that a letter I sent to an acquaintance in response to
her request for information was used in a political debate,''
O'Connor said in a brief statement. ``It was not my intention to
express a personal view about the subject of the inquiry but merely
to attempt to respond appropriately to one of the many requests for
information which come across my desk.''
   O'Connor declined further comment.
   The letter prompted some harsh criticism of O'Connor by legal
scholars and People for the American Way, a group that promotes
separation of church and state.
   Arthur J. Kropp, president of People for the American Way, wrote
to the justice:
   ``Like many Americans, I was surprised to read about your letter
... suggesting that three Supreme Court decisions have held that the
United States is a `Christian nation.'
   ``The Christian nation movement has emerged in recent years as a
force for religious intolerance. Its effect is to make
non-Christians feel excluded from society and to define `Christians'
on the basis of narrow political views.''
   Bruce Fein, a conservative lawyer who closely follows Supreme
Court developments, said the letter ``creates an ugly image in
having such a sensitive issue treated in such a cavalier way.''
   He said the letter is ``grossly improper'' because O'Connor
``gratuitously intruded herself into the political process.''
   Issues of religious freedom ``are perhaps the most inflammatory
that have ever reached the Supreme Court,'' Fein said. ``Judges must
have not only actual impartiality but the appearance of it.''
   Laurence Tribe, a liberal law school professor at Harvard
University, said in an interview with the Washington Post, ``It is
astonishing for any justice in the late 20th century to treat the
court's references to the religious character of our country as
somehow equivalent ... to the proclamation that this is a Christian
nation.''
   O'Connor's letter, dated May 19, 1988, was sent to Annetta
Conant, author of a resolution characterizing the United States as a
Christian nation that was adopted in January by the Arizona
Republican Party.
   The resolution is a rallying point for backers of former Arizona
Gov. Evan Mecham, a Republican who was removed from office last
year. Moderate Republicans and prominent Jewish Republicans in the
state have expressed dismay over the resolution, which also said the
nation is ``a republic based upon the absolute laws of the Bible,
not a democracy based on the changing whims of people.''
   O'Connor, a former state legislator in Arizona who has been on
the high court since 1981, said in her letter to Ms. Conant, ``You
wrote me recently to inquire about any holdings of this court to the
effect that this a Christian nation. There are statements to such
effect in the following opinions.''
   The letter then cites three high court rulings. In one, handed
down in 1892, the court said, ``We are a Christian people and the
morality of the country is deeply engrafted upon Christianity.''
   But two more recent opinions do not refer to the United States as
a Christian nation in the pages cited by O'Connor.
   One opinion, written by the liberal William O. Douglas when he
was a member of the court in 1952, said, ``We are a religious people
whose institutions presuppose a Supreme Being. We guarantee the
freedom to worship as one chooses.''
   The other, a concurring opinion written in 1961 by then-Justice
Felix Frankfurter, said ``religious beliefs'' in America ``shall
continue ... to exist, to function ... free of the dictates and
directions of the state.'' Frankfurter was Jewish.
   O'Connor's statement Wednesday did not say whether she actually
did the research or wrote the letter to Ms. Conant.
   But the Supreme Court's public information office said O'Connor's
letter was similar to one written in 1975 by the court's librarian
in response to a request for information by an Oregon woman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
