<DOCNO> AP890315-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-15 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>March Winds In Northeast; Thunderstorms In Michigan, Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Warm March winds whipped across portions of the Northeast on
Wednesday, while powerful thunderstoms lashed Michigan and parts of
the Appalachians.
   Winds gusted to 58 mph at Buffalo and Rochester, N.Y., and
Dubois, Pa., and to 61 mph at Johnstown, Pa. High wind warnings were
in effect for central New York and along the Champlain Valley
bordering New York and Vermont.
   The winds were accompanied by balmy temperatures. But a cold
front swept down from Canada across the Appalachians, bringing
temperatures in the 30s and 40s from the Great Lakes to the Ohio
Valley.
   Very strong thunderstorms, accompanied by some small hail, hit
the mountains of eastern Tennessee and western North Carolina.
Thunderstorms in Michigan triggered a fire in a church and pushed
the Rogue River to near flood stage at Rockford.
   More than 16 inches of wet, heavy snow fell at the K.I. Sawyer
Air Force Base, shutting down routine operations at the Lake
Superior post in Michigan's Upper Peninsula.
   However, the stormy weather was fairly short-lived.
   ``This is a typical March storm,'' said meteorologist Fred Keyes
of the National Weather Service bureau in Ann Arbor, Mich. ``You
have all sorts of weather and then it moves out as quickly as it
came. It doesn't hang around like a real winter storm does.''
   In the West, snow fell throughout much of the morning over parts
of central Montana. Snow was occasionally heavy in the Great Falls
area, with up to 2 inches of snow per hour at times.
   Rain was scattered across the Pacific Northwest.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included three-quarters of an inch at Astoria, Ore., and six-tenths
of an inch at Chattanooga, Tenn.
   Mild air brought some record high temperatures to the East.
Temperatures warmed into the 50s and 60s over much of New England,
the 70s over the mid-Atlantic coastal states and to the 80s over
portions of the Carolinas.
   The temperature hit 83 degrees at Martinsburg, W.V., 62 in
Binghampton, N.Y., 71 in Newark , N.J., and 69 in Williamsport, Pa.
   Some of the dust that was lifted into the air from the central
high plains on Tuesday settled over eastern New Mexico and western
Texas, cutting visibility in places down to one mile.
   Dust also settled in a band from Tennessee across northwest
Alabama, northern Mississippi, southern Arkansas, northern Louisiana
and south-central Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11
degrees at Marquette, Mich., and Duluth and International Falls,
Minn., to 89 degrees at McCallen and Harlingen, Texas.
   For Thursday, the National Weather Service was predicting rain
along the Pacific Coast from Washington to central California, and
rainshowers scattered across northern portions of the Plateau, with
snow at higher elevations. Light snow was expected from the northern
Rockies across portions of the Dakotas, Minnesota and Wisconsin to
upper Michigan. A few flurries were expected in New York State and
northern New England.
   High temperatures were expected in the teens along the Canadian
border from Montana to Minnesota; in the 20s and 30s from the
northern Rockies across the Dakotas, the upper Mississippi Valley
and much of the Great Lakes region to northern New England; and in
the 70s and 80s from the desert Southwest across the southern plains
to the Gulf Coast states. Elsewhere, highs were expected in the 40s,
50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BurningFertilizer 1stLd-Writethru a0715 03-15 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burning Fertilizer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burning Fertilizer Forces School Evacuation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE interstates reopened; no reports
of injuries; officials expect to extinguish fire Wednesday night. Picks
up 4th graf, pvs: `Jack Isch, ... </HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities evacuated a high school and
briefly closed parts of two interstates Wednesday to protect people
from a cloud of thick orange smoke from burning fertilizer,
officials said.
   There were no reports of injuries, said Deputy Fire Chief Jon
Hansen. Officials said late Wednesday afternoon they expected to
have the fire out by early evening.
   About 60 firefighters contained the blaze at the Douglass High
School football stadium on the east edge of downtown Oklahoma City,
said Fire Department Dispatcher Harvey Weathers.
   The firefighters were keeping their distance from the fire and
were allowing the blaze to burn itself out, Hansen said.
   Wind pushed the orange cloud to the south. Fire officials urged
people south of the stadium to avoid the cloud, and the Oklahoma
Highway Patrol closed sections of Interstates 40 and 35 through the
city for a little more than two hours.
   Jack Isch, in charge of the Oklahoma City school district's
service center, had said recently that the district has stored for
20 years some fertilizer donated to the school.
   The fertilizer at the stadium covers an area about 20 feet wide
and 30 feet long. Isch said he didn't know how many bags are in the
pile.
   The school board voted unanimously last week to hire a firm to
remove the fertilizer, which is ammonium nitrate. The federal
Environmental Protection Agency has said the fertilizer may have a
low level of toxicity.
</TEXT>
