<FIRST>b w AM-Scotus-Simmons     03-15 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Simmons,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday blocked
Thursday's scheduled execution in Arkansas of convicted mass
murderer R. Gene Simmons, who has said he wants to die.
   The justices, without dissent, granted an emergency request made
by another Arkansas death row inmate in Simmons' behalf.
   The request was granted without comment.
   Simmons was scheduled to receive a lethal injection at 7 a.m.
Thursday.
   He would have been the first prisoner executed in Arkansas since
1964.
   Simmons was convicted last month of the 1987 Christmas-time
slaughter of 14 members of his family. He has given up his right to
appeal, saying he wants to die.
   Simmons was convicted in 1988 of the deaths of two Russellville,
Ark., residents on Dec. 28, 1987. After the shooting spree which
left the two dead, Simmons was arrested and lawmen went to his home
near Dover, Ark., and found the bodies of the family members.
   The request to block Simmons' execution was made by death row
inmate Jonas H. Whitmore.
   The Arkansas Supreme Court ruled Whitmore lacked legal standing
to challenge Simmons' execution.
   Whitmore then appealed to U.S. Supreme Court Justice Harry A.
Blackmun, who referred the matter to the full court.
</TEXT>
