<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-15 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Writers Meet To Discuss Political Situation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Czech Writers' Union ended a
two-day meeting on Wednesday that was marked by controversy, and
state-run media called for ``differentiated'' treatment of banned
and emigre authors.
   The meeting was the latest in a series of discussions between
intellectuals and Communist Party and government figures following
signs of increasing discontent among the nation's artists.
   Thousands of actors, musicians, writers and cultural workers
recently signed a petition asking authorities for a meaningful
dialogue, more truthful media coverage of urgent political issues,
and the release of playwright-activist Vaclav Havel and other
political prisoners.
   Havel, whose plays were banned in Czechoslovakia after the 1968
Soviet-led invasion crushed ``Prague Spring'' reforms, was jailed in
February for nine months on charges of incitement and obstructing a
police officer.
   The state news agency CTK said speakers at the writers' meeting
``tackled again, from different and sometimes controversial
standpoints, the ... contemporary situation in Czech literature . ..
and also the general context of the political climate.''
   It said that Culture Minister Milan Kymlicka and the recently
elected head of the federal Czechoslovak Writers' Union, Miroslav
Valek, attended the meeting of the Czech Writers' Union. The two
organizations are separate.
   Valek, a Slovak poet, was made head of the Czechoslovak Writers'
Union after resigning late last year as Slovak minister of culture
following an article he wrote urging more reform.
   Czechoslovakia's leaders, installed after the 1968 invasion, have
found it difficult to follow Kremlin reforms. Moscow at one time
asked the leaders to quash many of the same reforms.
   One problem is how to deal now with the hundreds of intellectuals
barred from official cultural life and the 500,000 people expelled
from the party after 1968.
   ``We must not be silent about some controversial names from our
literature, especially from the end of the '60s, we mustn't walk
around the works of these authors as if they didn't exist,'' Michal
Cernik, head of the Czech Writers' Union was quoted as saying by the
Rude Pravo daily on Wednesday.
   Offical historians consider the Czechoslovak Writers' Union as
having spearheaded the short-lived period of reform in 1968.
   Some of the foremost members of the union, such as writer Milan
Kundera, left the country after the 1968 invasion. Others continued
writing in underground publications.
   The meeting also ``dealt with the activities of emigre writers .
.. and recommends evaluating their work and differentiating,'' Rude
Pravo reported.
   ``Our society doesn't renounce any artist, unless he himself
renounces the society and turns his back on it,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
