<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Taxes 1stLd-Writethru a0848 03-15 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0848,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pushes for Tax Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Updates with speech delivered, adds 5 grafs new material on
Millie, schoolteachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, calling Wednesday for
implementation of his plan to lower the capital gains tax, said U.S.
companies ``should not have to run an uphill race against the rest
of the world.''
   In an upbeat speech about the nation's economic future, the
president also said the United States ``stands at a special moment
in our history'' when his economic programs can empower more people
to partake in the American dream.
   Highlighting his proposal to reduce the capital gains tax in the
face of competition from nations that have little or no tax on such
gains, Bush called on Congress to sign on to his plan. He said, ``I
challenge the Congress to join with me and level that playing
field.''
   ``America's entrepreneurs should not have to run an uphill race
against the rest of the world,'' he said speaking to a gala dinner
of the Electronic Industries Association.
   Bush estimates the capital gains cut would add $4.8 billion in
revenue for the 1990 fiscal year, money which he said can be used
``to expand economic freedom, and help people help themselves.''
   ``Yes, America faces immediate problems _ problems like ocean
dumping, the homeless, illiteracy,'' Bush said in the speech.
   But said he intends to address those problems, but added, ``Let
us move beyond the immediate. For today, America is prosperous and
at peace.''
   The president said the government should seize this moment to
``solidify economic freedom'' through his proposals to reduce the
deficit, invest in the future and address ``urgent priorities''
without raising taxes.
   ``Let us recognize that we stand at a special moment in our
history. It is a moment not for complacency, not to sit back and
reflect upon what has bene, but to reflect upon what might be,'' the
president said.
   Bush pushed for his plan to reduce the capital gains tax to 15
percent on long-held assets and eliminate the capital gains tax for
people with incomes under $20,000 a year.
   ``Restoring the capital gains differential will lift revenues,
help savings, and free American businesses, without distorting world
markets,'' he said.
   The United States should keep in mind that some Pacific Rim trade
competitors, including Hong Kong, Singapore and Korea, exempt
capital gains from taxes while Japan ``scarcely taxed them during
her meteoric rise,'' he said.
   On the other hand, he said competitors that tax capital gains
punitively, ``by punishing risk takers, they stifle opportunity. Les
opportunity means less capital to invest. Less capital, in turn,
makes countries less competitive.''
   Bush also urged ``alternative certification'' of school teachers
so that people without the usual certificates can teach.
   ``It is simply a shame that the brightest among you men and women
here tonight, coming out of science, wanting to give of yourselves
to teach the kids, couldn't qualify because you didn't have the
required number of formal education degrees,'' he said. ``It is time
we take a new look and permit those who want to give of themselves
to teach in our public schools.''
   Bush joked about the impending birth of pups to the Millie, the
first family's dog.
   Speaking of his wife Barbara, Millie's principal caretaker, who
joined him at the head table, Bush said, ``This is the most relaxed
I've seen Bar since our dog got pregnant.''
   He said that when he asked his wife if she would join him on his
Thursday-Friday trip to Colorado and Texas, she replied that she
wouldn't dream of it with the English springer spaniel expecting to
deliver any day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
