<HEAD>Eleven Survivors From Missing Cargo Ship Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passing vessel found 11 survivors
marooned on a small central Philippine island six days after their
cargo ship was reported missing with 28 crewmen aboard, a shipping
official said Thursday.
   Jose Agujar, general manager of the Lorenzo Shipping Corp, said a
sketchy, radio message from a cargo ship said it picked up the 11
survivors of the 1,025-ton Lorcon V on Cavili island about 370 miles
south of Manila in the Sulu Sea.
   The report quoted survivors as saying three crewmen were dead and
the remaining 14 were missing. All crewmen were Filipinos.
   Officials reported the Lorcon V, a container ship, missing on
March 9 on a voyage from Manila to Iligan on Mindanao island. He
said the vessel reported engine trouble and was being towed to
Iligan when the cable snapped in bad weather and the ship vanished.
   Agujar said the report quoted survivors as saying the vessel sank
in the Sulu Sea after being buffeted by strong waves but did not
give the date of the sinking.
   Agujar said the crewmen reported three of their companions
drowned. He said it the survivors either swam or sailed aboard a
liferaft toward Cavili. He said the crewmen will be brought to the
port of Cebu.
   He said the search for the missing crewmen is continuing. The
U.S. Air Force have sent a helicopter to join the search in the
area. Several company ships and Philippine Coast Guard rescue
vessels are also are continuing the search.
