<FIRST>u i AM-GanderCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0815 03-15 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gander Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0815,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversy Renewed Over Gander Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `Bruce Pultz...' with 10 grafs to UPDATE with
comments by head of safety board and by Transport official who ordered
study. Pick up 10th pvs, `The crash...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The controversy over a 1985 crash in Newfoundland
that killed 256 Americans was revived Wednesday with the leaking of
a Transport Department report questioning the conclusions of the
official investigation.
   The Canadian Aviation Safety Board concluded after a three-year
investigation that ice on the plane's wings probably caused it to
crash.
   But the Ottawa Citizen reported Wednesday that an internal report
by the Transport Department, or Transport Canada, rejected the
safety board's majority conclusion and said the investigation was
mismanaged.
   ``The Transport Canada review does not substantiate the
conclusion that the aircraft stalled probably due to
ice-contaminated wings,'' the Citizen quoted the report as saying.
``It is the opinion of the Aviation Safety Programs Branch that the
cause of this accident is considered to be undetermined.''
   Transportation Minister Benoit Bouchard announced last week he
had accepted the board's conclusion. He ruled out a judicial inquiry
into the board's handling of the investigation.
   Sandra Wood, spokesman for Transport Canada, said Bouchard made
his statement last week based on recommendations from aides and did
not know about the critical study.
   Claude LaFrance, an assistant deputy transport minister, told a
news conference he ordered the Transport Canada study in December.
But he said he didn't tell the minister or deputy minister about it
when Bouchard was briefed on the department's response to the
board's report on the crash.
   LaFrance said his study, despite its sharp criticisms of the
safety board's investigation, did not mean to second-guess the
Gander report.
   ``We were looking for anything else that we might use to promote
aviation safety,'' he said.
   LaFrance didn't answer questions about what authority the
department has to do a detailed review of the board report. In
practice, the department is only supposed to review the board's
safety recommendations.
   Bruce Pultz, a member of the safety board which was formed in
1983 to carry out investigations independently of Transport Canada,
blamed the study on bureaucratic infighting.
   He said Transport Canada ``didn't have the evidence to be able to
reject the icing conclusion.''
   ``They keep trying to discredit us to get themselves more
power,'' Pultz said.
   Ken Thorneycroft, head of the safety board, said he had not read
the Transport Canada report and had no idea such a report even
existed.
   He said his board's report into the Gander crash was not flawed
in any way, and emphasized the investigative team did not arrive at
the crash site with pre-conceived notions of the cause of the
accident.
   A judicial inquiry would not shed any additional light on the
cause of the accident, he said.
   The crash on Dec. 12, 1985 at Gander, Newfoundland, killed 248
U.S. servicemen returning to Fort Campbell, Ky., from the Middle
East and eight American crew members of the Arrow Air charter DC-8.
   Since then, it frequently has been the subject of dispute.
   The final report on the crash was approved by five of the board's
members. Four supported the minority conclusion that an in-flight
fire or explosion was the cause.
   Brian Tobin, transportation critic in the Chamber of Deputies for
the opposition Liberal Party, said the latest controversy showed a
judicial inquiry is needed to determine the cause of the Gander
crash and whether the safety board carried out the investigation
properly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
