<FIRST>u i AM-SAfrica-Budget     03-15 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Budget,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Presents Austerity Budget, Promises Harder Times Ahead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government presented its new
budget Wednesday with a blunt warning that South Africans face
rising taxes and a higher cost of living.
   ``Every South African will have to make a sacrifice in the battle
against an economic onslaught which is being organized against the
country internationally,'' said Finance Minister Barend du Plessis
in a speech to Parliament, referring to anti-apartheid sanctions.
   The budget totaling 63.6 billion rand, or $25.4 billion, is up
12.5 percent from last year and the biggest allocations once again
are for the military and education.
   Defense spending is projected at $3.6 billion, up 13.7 percent,
and total spending for education is projected at $4.7 billion, an
increase of 19 percent.
   Du Plessis announced that the general sales tax, already one of
the world's highest, would rise from 12 percent to 13 percent and
said excise taxes on liquor and cigarettes also would increase.
   He said the ``unacceptably high'' 1988 inflation rate, which
averaged 12.9 percent, was certain to increase in 1989. Experts have
forecast a 15 percent inflation rate later this year.
   Total revenues are projected at $21.64 billion, with a third
coming from the general sales tax and the fuel tax. Du Plessis said
the deficit would be 4.1 percent of the gross domestic product, but
he did not provide that projected figure.
   Regarding sanctions imposed on South Africa to protest apartheid,
or the government's policy of racial separation, du Plessis said the
economy has managed to survive but he conceded that opportunities
for growth are being lost.
</TEXT>
