<FIRST>u a AM-Shuttle-Edwards 2ndLd-Writethru a0833 03-15 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Edwards, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0833,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Looks Good For California Shuttle Landing Saturday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with emergency landing concluded;
pickup 12th graf pvs, `Lovato said ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A make-believe fire swept
the cabin of a space shuttle mockup Wednesday, and airmen posing as
injured astronauts were evacuated by ground crews practicing for
Saturday's landing of the real shuttle Discovery.
   ``We want to ensure all our people are professionally trained and
can respond to any emergency,'' said Joe D'Agostino, airfield
support coordinator for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. ``Our goal is to safely remove astronauts. We like
that good warm feeling.''
   The simulated shuttle landing emergency went well, D'Agostino
said. NASA routinely conducts such exercises before real shuttle
landings.
   Discovery is scheduled to end its five-day mission by landing at
6:34 a.m. PST Saturday at this Mojave Desert military base 80 miles
north of Los Angeles.
   ``Saturday looks good for a landing,'' with sunny skies and mild
winds likely, NASA spokeswoman Nancy Lovato said.
   D'Agostino said Discovery might touch down on a concrete runway
to conduct braking and crosswind landing tests needed to pave the
way for eventual resumption of shuttle landings at Kennedy Space
Center in Florida. Shuttles normally land here on the 7-mile-long
Runway 17, an unpaved, hardpacked clay surface strip at Rogers Dry
Lake.
   About 200 NASA and Air Force personnel and 30 vehicles converged
on concrete Runway 22 to start Wednesday afternoon's mock landing
exercise.
   During the simulation, ground crews pretended that a normal
landing was followed immediately by a cabin fire inside the shuttle
orbiter. The five fake astronauts pretended to be incapacitated and
were carried out by Air Force firefighters, D'Agostino said. They
were placed aboard helicopters and flown over a nearby ridge as if
they were being transported to a hospital, he added.
   ``We're looking to see if the (Air Force) fire department can
correctly extract the people,'' Agostino said.
   Discovery is scheduled to return to Earth after orbiting Earth 79
times. That's one less orbit than planned due to the one-hour,
50-minute delay in the shuttle's launch Monday caused by fog and
strong high-level winds at the Kennedy Space Center.
   Lovato said Edwards forecasters predicted unobstructed visibility
and no rain Saturday, with scattered clouds at 25,000 feet and
northwest winds at about 12 mph until 8 a.m. _ well after the
scheduled landing _ increasing to 14 mph with gusts to 21 mph.
   But Friday's forecast calls for west-northwest winds 23 mph
gusting to 35 mph, probably too high for a landing, Lovato said.
   NASA prefers to land the shuttle on the Runway 17, an unpaved dry
lake, where there is plenty of room for error if brake or steering
problems develop. If the lakebed is wet and muddy, a paved runway at
Edwards is second choice, followed by White Sands Missile Range in
New Mexico, and then the concrete runway at Kennedy Space Center.
   The lone shuttle mission diverted from Edwards was the Columbia,
on the third shuttle mission in March 1982, when rain turned the
lakebed to muck and the Colombia landed at White Sands, Lovato said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 2ndLd-Writethru a0816 03-15 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0816,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lights Come Back on Aboard Discovery, Mission To Continue As Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9, `But flight ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
tank running properly all day; pickup 10th graf pvs, `Earlier Wednesday
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HTN3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lights came back on the Discovery space
shuttle Wednesday after Mission Control apparently fixed a
troublesome hydrogen tank and told the astronauts not to worry about
conserving energy.
   Discovery's five astronauts had switched off unnecessary lights
and computers because of concern about erratic pressure readings
from one of three hydrogen tanks aboard the shuttle. The tank, which
helps supply electricity, was taken out of service Tuesday while
engineers studied the problem.
   The crew turned the tank back on Wednesday morning but used only
one of its two heaters. Mission Control told the crew that early
pressure readings showed the tank was working properly.
   ``That's good news to hear,'' replied Discovery commander Michael
Coats.
   The hydrogen is combined with oxygen in the fuel cells to produce
electricity for shuttle systems, with water as a byproduct.
   Ground controllers were concerned that without use of the third
hydrogen tank, there may not be enough electricity to support a
five-day flight, plus two days for contingencies.
   But flight director Chuck Shaw said Wednesday night that the tank
operated properly with one heater all day, meaning Discovery is
headed for a 6:34 a.m. PST landing time Saturday at Edwards Air
Force Base, Calif., as planned.
   ``There are absolutely no problems at all,'' Shaw said, adding
that the tank would continue running while the astronauts slept.
   The tank presented no constraints ``to flying all the way to the
end of the mission and landing on Saturday,'' he said.
   Granvil Pennington, another flight director, also said weather
conditions for a Saturday landing look very good.
   Earlier Wednesday, the astronauts were told they didn't have to
continue to conserve electricity.
   The astronauts could turn on lights and use them ``as they see
fit.''
   Similar erratic pressure readings were noted on the same hydrogen
tank on Discovery's flight last fall and posed no power problems to
the vehicle's operations, Pennington added.
   NASA officials said the problem did not pose any safety threat to
the crew.
   The five astronauts went about the business of monitoring
experiments and trying to photograph environmentally damaged areas
of the Earth, including scars from a recent fire in the Florida
everglades and an erupting volcano in Guatamala.
   They also conducted medical tests on each other. While floating
on the flight deck, Dr. James M. Bagian took Coats' blood pressure,
checked his pulse and pressed a small device to his temple to
measure the blood flow in his head.
   The tests were to help determine what effect zero gravity has on
blood flow.
   Mission Control awoke the crew with a full brass band rendition
of the Marine Corps Hymn.
   ``We got two Marines standing at attention up here,'' joked
Coats, a Navy captain. ``What do we do now?''
   Astronauts James F. Buchli and Robert C. Springer are Marine
colonels. Bagian is a physician, and pilot John E. Blaha is an Air
Force colonel.
   Discovery's primary mission _ deployment of a $100 million
communications satellite _ was completed Monday several hours after
the shuttle rocketed into orbit.
   The Tracking and Data Relay Satellite completes a network that
will allow ground controllers almost unbroken radio contact with
shuttles and other satellites. The satellite deployed Monday and
another launched last year will provide the nearly continuous
coverage, while a third one above the Earth will act as an in-orbit
spare.
   The Discovery flight is the first of seven shuttle missions
planned this year and the 28th overall. It also is the third shuttle
flight since the Challenger exploded and killed its seven astronauts
more than three years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
