<FIRST>u i AM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru a0870 03-15 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0870,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subway Strike Hits Seoul, Police Arrest Hundreds of Strikers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Earlier, hundreds...' CORRECTING to specify
day student clashes occurred. Pick up 3rd pvs, `In Seoul...' SUB 10th pvs,
`About 700...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police stormed a subway depot and
arrested at least 1,600 strikers after a walkout on Thursday
paralyzed most of the capital's subway system and stranded hundreds
of thousands of commuters.
   On Wednesday, hundreds of radical students fought riot police
with firebombs, clubs and rocks in three cities. Groups from 38
colleges announced a nationwide campaign to defeat President Roh
Tae-woo in a referendum next month on Roh's reforms.
   In Seoul, the government organized emergency transport and urged
commuters to try to get to work as about 6,000 subway workers struck
to demand dismissal of the subway system's president. About 3
million of the capital's 10 million residents use the system daily.
   About 4,000 police firing tear gas stormed a depot occupied by
about 3,000 strikers. The state television network said police
arrested about 2,600 strikers. Police officials put arrests at about
1,600.
   Strikers armed with lead pipes and clubs had occupied the depot
and put up barricades, demanding that the city government meet their
demands. Police with bulldozers knocked down the barricades and
overpowered strikers hurling firebombs and rocks.
   About 15,000 riot police were deployed at subway stations to
prevent protests by strikers and to protect management and
non-striking workers, who struggled to maintain partial service on
some lines.
   Some non-union workers reported for work and the government
drafted locomotive operators from the national railways to help keep
some subway trains running. Subway officials said about 6,000 of the
system's 7,732 staff were involved in the protest.
   Subway union officials and the city government earlier reached an
agreement on new pay and working conditions. The unionists then
struck after accusing subway corporation president Kim Myong-nyon of
acting in bad faith during negotiations, and demanding that he be
fired.
   They wanted Mayor Koh Kun to sign the labor accord, saying they
did not trust the subway people, but Koh said he does not represent
the subway corporation.
   About 700 students, many shouting ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!,''
battled police for an hour Wednesday outside the main gate of
Seoul's Sejong University. Police responded with tear gas. No
arrests or injuries were reported.
   Fighting also broke out at Dankuk University in southern Seoul
where about 500 students, demanding Roh's resignation and a halt to
joint U.S.-South Korea military exercises now being held, tried to
march into the streets.
   Police tear gas dispersed the protesters after a two-hour battle.
   In the central city of Taejon, about 1,000 students, hurling
firebombs and rocks, battled riot police. In the southern city of
Kwangju, the South Korean news agency Yonhap reported, about 5,000
students held an anti-Roh rally.
   Roh made a 1987 campaign pledge to seek a midterm appraisal of
his performance after the Seoul Olympics, which ended in October. He
said last week he will fulfill the pledge by holding a referendum.
   Roh says that in the referendum, people will simply be asked to
assess the progress of democratic reforms he introduced after his
inauguration 13 months ago.
</TEXT>
