<FIRST>a w AM-Senate-Recruiting Adv20   03-15 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Recruiting, Adv20,0930</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, March 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Political Names Recruited for 1990 Senate Races</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big political names like Walter F. Mondale,
Pete du Pont and Lamar Alexander are attracting renewed attention as
party leaders try to recruit star-quality candidates in their
efforts to tip the balance in 1990 Senate races.
   Success in recruiting a Mondale, du Pont or Alexander could force
an otherwise safe incumbent into a tossup race for re-election.
   For example, if Democrats succeed in convincing Mondale to run
for the Senate, Republican Sen. Rudy Boschwitz of Minnesota would
shift from being a good bet for re-election to being an endangered
incumbent.
   The 1990 Senate elections also offer some tempting targets for
Republican recruiters looking for a chance to embarrass potential
1992 Democratic presidential contenders.
   High on that list was Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, the Democrat who
led the fight to defeat President Bush's nomination of John Tower to
be secretary of defense.
   ``It's about time we had a strong opponent against Mr. Nunn,''
said Lee Raudonis, executive director of the Georgia Republican
Party, a goal easier contemplated than achieved. Nunn received 80
percent of the vote in 1984 and 83 percent six years before that.
   Also on that list were Democrats Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee,
Joseph Biden of Delaware and Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
   But the main focus in 1990 will be control of the Senate rather
than the White House.
   There is virtually no chance the Republicans can regain next year
the majority they lost in 1986. Democrats now control the Senate by
a margin of 55 to 45, and of the 33 seats contested next year, 17
are now held by Republicans and 16 by Democrats.
   Republican dreams of narrowing the Democratic hold on the Senate
were jolted this winter when two GOP incumbents regarded as sure
bets for re-election _ William Armstrong of Colorado and Gordon
Humphrey of New Hampshire _ announced they wouldn't run again.
   Three other Republicans considered possibilities to join the
ranks of voluntary retirements were Jesse Helms of North Carolina,
Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas and Mark Hatfield of Oregon.
   On the Democratic side, no incumbent is expected to step down
voluntarily.
   Ironically, Democratic efforts to recruit former North Carolina
Gov. Jim Hunt to run for the Senate could have the effect of
convincing Helms to seek another term.
   Helms beat back a challenge from Hunt in 1984, a contest that was
not only one of the most bitter in memory, but also still ranks as
the most expensive Senate race in history. Helms spent nearly $17
million and Hunt almost $10 million.
   Friends of Mondale describe the 1984 Democratic presidential
candidate as agonizing over whether to challenge Boschwitz, a
decision Mondale has said he would make this summer.
   The former vice president and senator is getting conflicting
advice from former aides, some of whom argue that a Boschwitz
challenge would be very expensive and difficult to win despite early
polls that give Mondale a nine-point lead. Others argue that Mondale
ought to run because he yearns to return to public service and they
are convinced that although the race would not be easy he would win.
   Basil Battaglia, the Delaware Republican chairman, said he has
talked to du Pont about challenging Biden.
   ``That would be a classic race,'' he said, while not sounding
optimistic that it will take place. Du Pont was a popular two-term
governor of Delaware and was an early contender for the 1988 GOP
presidential nomination.
   ``Pete has never been receptive to the United States Senate for
some reason,'' said Battaglia. ``He has always shied away from it.''
   In Tennessee, GOP party official Tommy Hopper was no more
optimistic about convincing former Gov. Lamar Alexander to take on
Gore.
   ``He probably wouldn't consider it,'' Hopper said of Alexander,
who now is president of the University of Tennessee.
   Was anyone else considering a Gore challenge?
   ``I don't know anybody who's looking at it,'' said Hopper.
   Greg Edwards, executive director of the New Jersey Republican
Party, couldn't name a high-visibility prospect to challenge
Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley.
   ``I have not been a party to any discussions about candidate
recruitment for the Senate race,'' he said. ``Nor have I heard of
any potentials mentioned.''
   Republicans may have better luck persuading Rep. Claudine
Schneider to run against veteran Democratic Sen. Claiborne Pell of
Rhode Island. Schneider resisted attempts to get her to challenge
Pell in 1984 and is giving no hints what she might do this time.
   A Republican in the category of ``a shoo-in unless'' was Sen.
John Warner of Virginia. The only potential stumbling block in his
path was Gov. Gerald Baliles, whose term ends in January 1990.
   Despite the hunger Georgia Republicans have for seeing Nunn
forced to work for re-election, the prospects aren't high.
   ``There hasn't been a meeting of the long knives to go out and
try to find someone,'' said Raudonis when asked about the prospects
of a strong challenge to Nunn.
   He listed Mack Mattingly, the Republican who served one Senate
term and then was beaten for re-election in 1986 as ``a formidable
candidate.''
   ``I'm sure there are others around,'' said Raudonis. ``I just say
we haven't gone out and tried to find anybody yet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 20</NOTE>
