<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Oscar-FilmPreservation Adv19   03-15 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Oscar-Film Preservation, Adv 19,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Breathing Life Into Old Movies</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: The Academy Award might be the most sought-after
prize in the movie world, but even Oscar _ or an Oscar nomination _
hasn't been able to save some old movies from fading away.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HILLEL ITALIE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Gone Wih the Wind'' looks better than ever.
``Lawrence of Arabia'' is a feast for the eyes. The new print of
``Casablanca'' has hardly a scratch.
   But the rerelease of those Academy Award-winning classics has
overshadowed the fact that thousands of old films are in need of
restoration or are damaged beyond repair.
   Curators from the nation's four major preservation centers agree
that quick and comprehensive action is needed. They also see another
problem emerging over the next few years: the fading of color films.
   The original negative of ``Stagecoach,'' the 1939 John Ford
Western that made John Wayne a star, no longer exists, and only
inferior copies are available. The same is true of the 1937 Cary
Grant-Irene Dunne comedy, ``The Awful Truth,'' which earned an Oscar
for director Leo McCarey. And the master of ``Double Indemnity,''
Billy Wilder's 1944 landmark film noir, is incomplete. It was
nominated for best picture but lost to another McCarey production,
``Going My Way.''
   Until 1950, movies were printed on nitrate stock, a highly
flammable material that decomposes almost instantly, and without
proper care can disintegrate within a few years. But when the
negatives are transferred to acetate, known as ``safety stock,''
they can have a shelf life of 100 years or more if kept under
climate-controlled conditions.
   ``I think with over 110 million feet of nitrate film held in the
nation's archives that are either unique copies or the best
surviving ones, we are very close to confronting a crisis,'' said
Robert Rosen, director of UCLA's Film and Television Archives. ``All
of this material, unless it's copied, is going to be gone.''
   Peter Williamson, preservation officer at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York, cited other major problems: ``We need additional
funding because our funding levels have basically been frozen at a
fixed dollar amount for the last 10 years,'' he said. ``Also, the
laboratory capacity to correctly duplicate for preservation has
undergone a dramatic shrinking. Fifteen years ago there were at
least two dozen laboratories, now we're down to six or seven.''
   Switching from one stock to the other costs the preservation
centers 40-60 cents per foot, double the rate of 10 years ago.
Meanwhile, federal funding has stayed at $500,000 during that time.
And with the government operating under a large budget deficit, the
prospects for increased revenues in the near future are dim.
   ``I'm going to shoot for the same kind of funding that I had this
year,'' said Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., a major supporter of film
preservation and a member of the House subcommittee on Interior and
Related Agencies.
   ``I don't think there's a possibility of getting a real major
increase of funding for any program under the current fiscal
climate. If perhaps we can get an inflation recognition (an increase
at the rate of inflation), we will have been doing pretty well.''
   But even with financial assistance, curators see another problem
emerging over the next few years: the fading of color films.
According to Paul Spehr, the assistant chief of the Library of
Congress' Motion Picture, Broadcasting and Recorded Sound Division,
the negatives for early color films have a shelf life of 30-40 years
and can be extended by cold storage.
   Since color first had widespread use in the '50s, many original
negatives are now ready to be transferred to the current, more
durable stock.
   ``Most of the colors fade very badly,'' Spehr said. ``We're at
the point now where it's beginning to see a crunch.''
   Moving pictures first became popular at the turn of the century
when people poured into nickelodeons, and for 5 cents could watch
images flicker by. By the '20s, such stars as Charlie Chaplin and
Mary Pickford had helped make motion pictures a major industry. But
no one really thought those movies were worth saving.
   According to Williamson, less than one-third of all silent movies
remain. The films of actress Theda Bara, a major star from the
silent era, have almost completely vanished.
   ``We have 12 to 15 million feet of nitrate and only about a third
of that is preserved,'' said Ed Stratmann, the assistant curator in
charge of preservation at the George Eastman House in Rochester,
N.Y. ``Time is running out for it.''
   Movie studios have received mixed grades for their efforts in
transferring stock. Curators praised Turner Entertainment, which
controls MGM, RKO and pre-1949 Warner Bros. films, and Walt Disney
Studios for maintaining their libraries.
   Ted Turner, chairman and chief executive officer of Turner
Broadcasting Systems Inc., outraged the film community by colorizing
``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``It's a Wonderful Life'' and other
classics. However, his company has done extensive restoration,
including the heavily-publicized ``Gone With the Wind'' project.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1639EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Oscar-FilmPreservation Adv19-1stAdd   03-15 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Oscar-Film Preservation, Adv 19-1st Add,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK _ ``Gone With the Wind'' project.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   According to Dick May, Turner's director of film services, the
entire MGM catalog _ about 1,000 movies _ has been transferred to
safety, including 1938's ``The Adventures of Robin Hood,'' which was
in danger of being lost forever.
   ``There was no protection. The safety negative wore out from use.
We had to go back to the original nitrate material,'' May said.
   Disney has recently reissued the much-loved animated movies,
``Bambi'' and ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' and is currently
at work on a new print of ``Fantasia.''
   ``We have in addition to the negative material, the original
artwork,'' said Paula Sigman, assistant archivist at the Disney Co.
``If we want to do something special, we can go back to the
original-release versions. All that material has been preserved.''
   MCA, which controls the Universal and pre-1948 Paramount
libraries, has been less thorough. Two early Marx Brothers films,
``The Cocoanuts'' and ``Horse Feathers,'' are available only in
badly scratched versions. ``Double Indemnity'' is also a Paramount
movie.
   ``It's not like there are any titles that have been lost because
the nagative is incomplete, but as far as what the quality would be,
there's no way of saying,'' said John Previti, who supervises
preservation of old Universal and Paramount titles. ``The longer you
wait, the more of a risk there is. All this nitrate has been sitting
in the vault for years.''
   Spehr was also less than satisfied with Universal's library.
   ``We certainly don't have a full representation of their film
production. Some films ... are in very bad shape. They don't have
the snap and sharpness you would like to see.''
   But all the dire predictions have produced a positive side
effect: an increased awareness of the importance of preservation.
   Projects are underway throughout the United States: The Library
of Congress is currently restoring the films of Frank Capra; Turner
is at work on the Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers musicals; UCLA has
discovered a series of Laurel and Hardy films in Spanish; and the
American Film Institute is putting together a comprehensive data
base with information on all available prints and where the
negatives can be found.
   ``We're working with the other archives in trying to pool a few
things,'' said Stratmann, who noted that the Eastman House, the
Museum of Modern Art and Turner are collaborating on the restoration
of the 1944 musical, ``Meet Me in St. Louis.''
   Spehr is encouraged, too: ``One of the things that's interesting
is we detect a much stronger and broader interest in preservation in
general. More interests are being expressed from a wider variety of
sources.''
   For Rosen, restoring old films goes beyond any entertainment
value the movies might provide. He sees it as a way of preserving
history.
   ``For the 20th century, the moving image is in a real sense our
collective memory,'' he said. ``It's the popular art form most
characteristic of our century. It's a way people measure their own
lives.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
