<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-EXP--RainForests-Asia Adv19   03-15 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Rain Forests-Asia, Adv 19,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Asian Efforts to Save Vanishing Rain Forests Uneven</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Explorations Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts had warned for years that
uncontrolled logging and clearing in Asian rain forests could lead
to disaster. The warnings went unheeded until November's rains
brought floods and mudslides to Thailand.
   More than 350 people were killed, including scores in the
worst-hit area, Nakhon Sri Thammarat, as mud and felled trees rolled
down hillsides and buried entire villages. Environmentalists blamed
loggers, who blamed farmers they said moved illegally into steep
forests and burned away trees to plant crops.
   The government in January banned logging on 38.4 million acres.
   Regardless of who's to blame, government spoksman Charnchai
Chairungrueng said Thailand's virgin forest has dwindled from 43
percent of the nation's land cover in 1972 to 27 percent.
Environmentalists say it's more like 20 percent.
   About 25 percent of the world's remaining tropical forests are in
Southeast Asia _ 65 percent in Indonesia. The rest are spread among
Malaysia, Burma, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand and the
Philippines.
   In 1982, an international meeting of conservation groups in Bali
heard that rain forest loss had caused floods in India and drought
in Indonesia, clogged Thailand's traditional waterway support
system, devastated Haitian farms and reduced efficiency of
hydroelectric systems in the Philippines.
   Measures to reduce deforestation are promised in Indonesia, the
world's largest supplier of tropical wood, but the chainsaws cut as
much as ever.
   Hasjrul Harahap, Indonesia's forestry minister, said at least
1.24 million acres are destroyed each year in his country. Only
about 100,000 acres a year are being reforested. Harahap blamed a
``lack of discipline among those holding forest concessions'' for
the destruction. Most of the 544 concession holders are retired
military officers or former government officials.
   Environmentalists say 133 million acres have been lost over 20
years. In addition to logging, other factors are mining, nomadic
farmers and resettlement of millions of ``transmigrants'' from Java
to clear forests on other islands.
   Indonesia banned export of raw logs in 1985 to help the forests
recover and force the manufacture of plywood and other finished
products. Scores of plywood mills opened as expected, creating badly
needed jobs _ but increasing logging.
   Selective logging rules require that only trees of more than 20
inches in diameter be cut. But timber firms have logged over a wider
area to find enough of the larger trees, destroying many others in
the process.
   Timber companies are supposed to pay into a reforestation fund
for every tree felled, but the Forest Conservation Network of
Indonesia says there has never been a proper accounting of the fund.
   Malaysia, the leading exporter of raw logs, ships them from
Borneo Island's Sabah and Sarawak states. Environmentalists say the
timber harvesting rate in Sabah is four times that of natural
regeneration. Logging comprises 13 percent of the gross national
product, and Malaysia exported $1.6 billion worth of logs and sawed
wood in 1987.
   Malaysia also is sensitive to charges that logging in Sarawak
displaces the Penans, the last known tribe of nomadic hunters on
Borneo's north coast. The Penans started blocking logging roads in
April 1987 to protest the cutting of tropical hardwoods that provide
a canopy for their highland hunting grounds.
   Penans claim they are not recognized as owners of their
traditional lands, which were handed down by earlier generations.
Officials say 81 have been arrested this year; environmentalists put
the figure above 100.
   Kuala Lumpur vigorously defends its logging policy and denounces
critics. Protests last year at nine Malaysian diplomatic missions
were dismissed by Foreign Ministry Secretary-General Yusof Hitam as
attempts ``to sabotage the country for political reasons.''
   Environmentalists accuse Japan, the world's biggest consumer of
tropical timber, of wasting it on items like chopsticks that could
be made from other timber or non-timber materials.
   Late last year, Japan began obtaining raw wood from Brazilian
forests. The Worldwide Fund for Nature said that would undercut
trade with countries such as Malaysia and Indonesia, forcing them to
slash prices.
   Motokatsu Watanabe, a Japanese Foreign Ministry officer, said the
private sector in Japan has not recognized the danger of
deforestation. A major goal for the government, he said, is to
increase public awareness.
   The timber trade in the Philippines has fallen and officials in
Manila blame runaway logging for shrinking forests. The Department
of Environmental and Natural Resources estimated only 3 million
acres of virgin forests remained of the 40.4 million acres in the
1940s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for March 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
