<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-15 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0884</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deficit in the broadest measure of American
trade improved dramatically last year, narrowing to $135.3 billion,
as a surge in merchandise exports was enough to offset a sharp
worsening in the U.S. investment balance sheet, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday the deficit in the current
account shrank 12.1 percent in 1988 after hitting an all-time high
of $153.96 billion in 1987.
   The current account, also known as the balance of payments, is
the most important trade statistic because it measures not only
trade in merchandise but also transactions in investments and other
services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales dropped 0.4 percent in February,
the government said in a report some analysts read as a sign that
consumers are wary of a broader economic slowdown.
   Held back by a sharp drop in business at car dealerships, retail
sales fell to a seasonally adjusted $138.2 billion last month after
rising 0.7 percent in January when good weather brought out more
shoppers, the Commerce Department said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration intensified
its testing of grapes and other Chilean fruit while the Bush
administration worked with officials of the South American country
to determine the scope of an apparent cyanide poisoning attempt.
   Meanwhile, FDA Commissioner Frank Young advised Americans Tuesday
to be ``safe rather than sorry'' by discarding all fruit in their
refrigerator unless they are certain it was grown somewhere other
than Chile.
   The FDA on Monday announced that traces of cyanide had been found
in two seedless red grapes that were part of a batch of about 2,000
grape bunches sampled at the port in Philadelphia, where they had
been shipped from Chile three days before a poisoning threat was
telephoned to the U.S. Embassy there.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ignoring a veto threat by the administration, a
House committee rejected President Bush's minimum-wage proposal and
instead joined a Senate panel in backing legislation calling for a
bigger increase.
   The Democrat-controlled House Education and Labor Committee voted
22-13 along party lines Tuesday to reject Bush's call to raise the
minimum from $3.35 an hour to $4.25 by 1992 while allowing employers
to pay new workers $3.35 an hour for their first six months on the
job.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Depositors withdrew a record $10.7 billion from
savings and loans in January, when controversy swirled around a Bush
administration proposal to levy a fee on deposits, the government
said Tuesday.
   James Barth, chief economist of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
said four out of five of the nation's 2,945 S&amp;Ls experienced net
withdrawals in January. The total, in one month, exceeded net
withdrawals for all of 1988, which were $8.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airline pilots asked a federal judge to appoint a
trustee to run Eastern Airlines, alleging that Frank Lorenzo,
chairman of parent Texas Air Corp., was stripping Eastern's assets
to bolster affiliated companies.
   In other developments in Eastern's Chapter 11 proceedings
Tuesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland approved Eastern's
plan to compensate holders of unused tickets, and striking
Machinists asked the judge to order payment of $10 million in back
wages and medical claims.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association, easing the way
for 3,600 pilots honoring Machinist union picket lines at Eastern
Airlines, said it will give its members nearly $9 million a month in
strike benefits.
   The pilots union also said Tuesday its 41,000 members would not
fly planes or routes sold to other airlines by Eastern unless a
comparable number of Eastern pilots were also hired, and at full
seniority.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge approved the settlement of the
government's civil racketeering case against the Teamsters union,
saying it meant the union's ledership is pledged to keep it ``free
from the influence of organized crime.''
   U.S. District Judge David N. Edelstein on Tuesday signed the
agreement, hammered out just before a trial was to begin Monday,
noting that the Teamsters union ``has had a long and sordid career
of corruption and involvement with criminal elements.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales were down by 14.8
percent in early March from the same period last year as U.S.-based
automakers continued their slow 1989 sales start, the companies said.
   Automakers said Tuesday they sold vehicles at an average daily
rate of 31,090 during the March 1-10 period this year, compared with
a daily rate of 36,493 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned in a dull performance Tuesday, with
prices barely budging. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ended
the day unchanged at 2,306.25.
   The dollar was weaker against most key currencies in quiet
trading. Gold prices strengthened.
   Bond prices were mostly higher as fears of inflation waned amid a
report of slower retail sales.
   Energy futures rose after reports that one major oil producer cut
supplies and another halted production of 150,000 barrels a day.
Precious metal rose; cocoa prices climbed; and grain and soybean
prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
