<DOCNO> AP890315-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Pilots Bjt   03-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pilots, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Wide Demand For Pilots Could Hinder Eastern Rebound</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots are caught in a Catch 22.
   The fliers could easily find jobs at other carriers, thanks to a
shortage of commercial pilots stemming from airline deregulation and
explosive growth in passenger traffic, many experts say.
   But leaving strikebound Eastern requires them to sacrifice
seniority and accept lower pay and benefits.
   For Eastern's management, the pilot shortage could make it even
more difficult to replace the 3,600 pilots at the carrier, experts
said Tuesday.
   In order to attract new pilots, Eastern would have to offer
competitive salaries and quick promotions _ and it would need lots
of time to do so, said Peter Cappelli, a professor at the University
of Pennsylvania's Wharton School and the University of California at
Berkeley who studies airline labor relations.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell in Miami declined to comment on
the issue.
   Eastern's pilots earn an average of $70,000 to $85,000 a year.
Average pilot wages at healthy carriers such as United Airlines and
Delta Air Lines are higher _ pilots pull in as much as $167,000 at
the highest seniority levels.
   Observers also say the rock-bottom morale at Eastern, where
employees' anger toward boss Frank Lorenzo has reached fever pitch,
compounds the difficulty of luring replacement pilots. The carrier,
which has been crippled by the Machinists strike since March 4,
filed for protection from creditors under federal bankruptcy law
Thursday.
   One airline industry executive who asked not to be identified
admitted that the low morale at Eastern and the support of pilots at
other carriers for their colleagues at Eastern and against Lorenzo
would make it tough to replace the rebellious fliers.
   That solidarity was demonstrated Tuesday, when the executive
board of the Air Line Pilots Association announced it had authorized
strike benefit payments of $2,400 a month plus interest-free loans
for every Eastern pilot honoring the Machinists' picket lines.
   ``Today there really is a shortage'' of pilots, said Mark Kahn,
professor emeritus of economics at Wayne State University in
Detroit. Airline deregulation and growth in demand, plus a shrinking
of the traditional source of pilots _ the military _ have
contributed to this trend, experts say.
   Kit Darby, executive vice president of Future Aviation
Professionals of America in Atlanta, calls the job market for pilots
``extremely good.''
   Some airline executives say there is no pilot shortage.
   ``I am not aware of any of my member carriers having trouble
hiring qualified pilots,'' said Jerrold Glass, vice president of the
Airline Industrial Relations Conference, an airline trade
association focused on labor relations.
   If there actually is a nationwide pilot shortage, it would be
only a mixed blessing for Eastern's captains. They have highly
marketable skills but are hostages of the seniority system, forced
to start at the bottom of the ladder if they move to other airlines.
   Before the Machinists strike, Eastern pilots were deserting the
ailing carrier at the rate of about 500 a year, according to ALPA.
Some of them had as many as 20 years' seniority, the pilots union
says.
   Many of them went to work for healthier carriers such as American
Airlines, Northwest Airlines, USAir, Piedmont, United Parcel Service
and Federal Express, said Daniel Vician, vice chairman of the master
executive council of Eastern's ALPA branch.
   Some of the more experienced pilots who left Eastern saw their
salaries cut from about $5,833 a month to $1,800 a month, Vician
said.
   ``I think we're beginning to look at'' other jobs, Eastern pilot
Vince Garland said recently as he walked a picket line at Atlanta's
Hartsfield International Airport.
   Garland, 40, who's flown for Eastern for 10{ years, said he's
been told he would have to take a 60 percent pay cut to move to a
competitor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Matsushita-American Bjt   03-15 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Matsushita-American, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Matsushita Takes A Step Toward Americanization</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28 of March 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Ltd.
has named an American as second-in-command of its U.S. operations,
but observers say it may be years before big Japanese companies put
an American in their top U.S. post.
   Richard A. Kraft, 60, was named Tuesday as president and chief
operating officer of Matsushita Electric Corporation of America, the
U.S. arm of the world's biggest consumer electronics company.
   Kraft is a 15-year veteran of the company, which sells products
under the Panasonic, Technics and Quasar brand names. He has served
as president of Matsushita Industrial Co. of Franklin Park, Ill.,
Matsushita's U.S. manufacturing division, since 1979.
   Kraft will run day-to-day operations under Akiya Imura, 54, who
will continue as chief executive of the U.S. company, based in
Secaucus, N.J., and assume the new title of chairman. The changes
take effect April 1.
   American companies are much more likely than Japanese companies
to give their top jobs overseas to foreign nationals. For example,
International Business Machines Corp. spokesman Peter Thonis said
IBM does business in 130 foreign countries and has Americans in
charge at fewer than five of them.
   In contrast, the chairman of Sony Corp. of America is Masaaki
Morita, younger brother of Sony co-founder Akio Morita. The U.S.
operations of Fujitsu Ltd., Hitachi Ltd. and the biggest Japanese
banks and brokerage houses all are headed by Japanese as well.
   ``When push comes to shove, Japanese and Americans are not on the
same (promotion) track,'' said Richard Ozaroff, an analyst who
follows Japanese companies. ``For all the claims that they are
multinational companies that just happen to be based in Japan, I
don't buy it.''
   Matsushita has been striving to achieve a reputation as a good
corporate citizen in the United States by promoting Americans and
building U.S. factories.
   The company's image suffered a setback in January when its
Panasonic Co. unit agreed to pay consumers $16 million to avoid New
York state charges that it fixed retail prices on electronics
products.
   While the company maintains its innocence, some analysts said the
unfavorable publicity may have added urgency to promoting an
American to a top job as an image-building move.
   Matsushita has more than 7,000 employees in the United States,
scattered from Hawaii to California, Illinois, Washington, Tennessee
and New Jersey. It sells televisions, videocassette recorders,
microwave ovens and other products. It also sells business and
industrial equipment.
   Kraft said that as an American he could be more effective than
his predecessors in dealing with American employees, government
bodies and communities where Matsushita has operations.
   ``The American public today seems to be ambivalent about foreign
companies in the United States,'' Kraft said. By building
Matsushita's reputation, he said, ``We can ultimately overcome any
possible friction and be welcome in this country.''
   Matsushita, which had $38.5 billion in sales last year, has 102
companies in 37 countries outside Japan. Thirty of the companies in
14 countries already were headed by non-Japanese, and Imura said
picking an American to be president of the U.S. operations had been
a high priority for him in his two-year stint as president.
   Kraft said he understands the Japanese attitude of caution about
promoting an American to the top job.
   ``I think it's only natural that the company would be
conservative about turning over that kind of power until they had
developed the confidence in the person enough to be comfortable,''
he said.
   Could Kraft ever get the top job in Matsushita's U.S. company?
``This is America. Anything is possible. It certainly could happen.
I would just be overjoyed if I could develop that kind of
confidence,'' he said. ``Whether it will happen in my lifetime or
not, I don't know.''
   Kraft, a Chicago native, holds 13 U.S. patents as inventor or
co-inventor of electronics related to television.
</TEXT>
