<FIRST>r f PM-VirginIslands-Eastern     03-15 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Virgin Islands-Eastern,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Strike Costing Virgin Islands $5 Million Weekly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAM DiMEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strike against
Eastern Airlines is costing the U.S. Virgin Islands about $5 million
a week and has cut short the heavy tourist season by nearly a month,
a Hotel Association spokesman said Tuesday.
   Tom Bennett, spokesman for the St. Thomas-St. John Hotel
Association, said the loss of 35 Eastern flights every week has
translated into about 6,200 fewer tourists per week.
   The situation was aggravated when Flyfare, one of the largest
travel agents dealing with the Caribbean, filed for bankruptcy.
Flyfare dealt almost exclusively with Eastern, Bennet said.
   ``We're certainly looking at a very serious time for the entire
economy,'' he said.
   ``We are doing what we can to make it as easy as possible for
Eastern to come back in or to assist other existing carriers to
increase their flights or to welcome a new carrier into the
islands,'' he added.
   Bennett also said negotiations were under way with the Caribbean
Hotel Association to fill the void left by Flyfare.
   While the hotel association and the Virgin Islands government
were moving to increase flights with other carriers and to seek the
aid of the Caribbean Hotel Association, losses through Tuesday
topped $5 million, he said.
   ``We've lost the lift of about 6,000 people and according to
statistics from the Division of Tourism, that calculates to be a
loss of $5 million a week,'' Bennett said.
   The figure includes $500,000 in various taxes lost to the local
government, which earns millions from the more than $600 million
generated annually by 2 million visitors, he said.
   ``Each week that this continues you are going to see that
happening,'' Bennett said. ``I think for all intents and purposes
the tourist season has come to an abrupt halt.''
   In addition, the 62 hotels and guest houses that are members of
the association are reporting sharp drops in occupancy this month,
Bennett said.
   ``Those hotels that were enjoying nearly full houses at the
beginning of March are now looking at 60 and 70 percent occupancy,''
the hotel association spokesman said.
   In addition, Bennett said, the impact is being felt among
seasonal hotel employees, who are working shorter hours and are
being laid off a month ahead of schedule.
</TEXT>
