<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     03-15 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0308</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices headed higher in the stock market today
after the government reported a slightly smaller-than-expected U.S.
trade deficit for January.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.50 to 2,313.75 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 495 up, 363 down and
567 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.23 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit narrowed to $9.49 billion in January from a revised
$10.99 billion the month before.
   The data, which were formerly reported in two ways, are now
posted only under a method that excludes costs of freight and
insurance.
   The latest figure came in below most Wall Street economists'
estimates, prompting some buying by traders.
   But enthusiasm was muted by worries that less favorable news
might be looming when the monthly figures on the producer price
index of finished goods are issued on Friday.
   Sea Containers Ltd. gained 1] to 45~ on top of an 8{-point jump
Tuesday, when investors learned that Stena AB of Sweden has acquired
an 8.17 percent interest in the company and may seek to gain control
of it.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.41 to 166.34. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .56 at 331.09.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average was unchanged at
2,306.25.
   Declining issues narrowly outpaced advances on the NYSE, with 722
issues down, 670 up and 554 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 139.97 million shares, against 140.40
million in the previous session.
