<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   03-15 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail and Auto Sales Decline, Trade Deficit Improved in 1988, Reports
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on stock prices and January business inventories;
picks up 5th graf pvs, The Commerce .... Federal Reserve report on February
factory has been postponed until Thursday.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit shrank to $9.49 billion in
January, with the nation posting a rare trade surplus with Western
Europe and the imbalance with Japan declining to its lowest point in
about four years, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department attributed the 13.7 percent improvement
in the overall shortfall _ the best showing since October _ to a 6.9
percent drop in imports that was enough to offset a 4.3 percent
decline in U.S. export sales.
   The monthly improvement was better than many analysts had been
expecting, although they cautioned against reading too much into a
one-month swing in the figures.
   The $9.49 billion January deficit would translate into an annual
imbalance of $114 billion, compared with a deficit for all of 1988
of $119.76 billion.
   Stock and bond prices were slightly higher today after the
report. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 5.54 at
2,311.79 after an hour of trading.
   Separately, the Commerce Department said business inventories
rose 0.7 percent in January while sales advanced at a strong 1
percent pace. The report indicated steady economic growth.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that retail sales
dropped 0.4 percent in February. The decline was sparked by a sharp
drop in sales at car dealerships, which account for almost 25
percent of total retail sales.
   The nation's automakers had more bad news: Sales continued to
drop in the first 10 days of March. Analysts speculated the 14.8
percent drop in car and light truck sales from the same period last
year was due in part to rising interest rates.
   Chrysler Corp. said its sales dropped 35.9 percent in early
March, while Ford Motor Co. reported a 21.4 percent decline and
General Motors Corp. said its sales slipped 13.4 percent.
   Economist John Hagens of the Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa.,
economic forecasting service, said that while the economy entered
1989 with strong momentum, consumers may be cautious in anticipation
of slower economic growth or recession.
   ``A slowing of consumer spending is consistent with the
expectation of a recession,'' Hagens said. ``Consumers are typically
very smart. They know these things, often before economists.''
   However, a drop in consumer spending could by itself cause an
economic slowdown. Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the
gross national product.
   The falloff in sales was welcome news to many financial markets,
which have been concerned that the economy is growing too fast to
avoid a flare-up of inflation. The Federal Reserve has been driving
interest rates higher to try to restrain inflation.
   Stock prices rallied in early trading in response to the Commerce
Department report, but ended the day little changed as investors
looked forward to today's release of January trade deficit figures.
The Dow Jones industrial average ended the day at the same level
where it closed on Monday, 2,306.25.
   On the bond market, the price of the Treasury's closely-watched
30-year issue rose $5 for every $1,000 in face amount as investors'
fears of inflation were calmed by the retail sales report.
   However, the dollar fell in response to the sales report because
of the prospect of lower interest rates. Lower interest rates make
the dollar less attractive to foreign investors.
   While the markets were anticipating the January trade figures,
they got a report on the 1988 deficit on Tuesday. The Commerce
Department said the broadest measure of American trade, the current
account, improved dramatically last year, narrowing to $135.3
billion from a record-high $153.96 billion in 1987.
   A surge in merchandise exports offset a sharp worsening in the
U.S. investment balance sheet, the government said.
   The current account, also known as the balance of payments, is
the most important trade statistic because it measures not only
trade in merchandise but also transactions in investments and other
services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
