<FIRST>u f PM-Chile-Fruit 3rdLd-Writethru f0042 03-15 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Fruit, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0042,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile's Fruit Industry Paralyzed By Scare</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `The 12-nation ...' to CORRECT that EEC
sted United States asked European nations if they had received reports
of contamination. Pickup 11th, `Dansk Supermarked ... Also moving on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chile's booming fruit export industry was
paralyzed today as growers and sellers halted all shipments and
began scouring their stocks in response to a worldwide cyanide
contamination scare.
   The military government harshly criticized the U.S. ban on
Chilean fruit imports as ``another roguish act of the United
States'' but promised to check all fruit before it leaves the
country.
   The Independent Democratic Union, a supporter of the military
regime, announced a ``national day of fruit eating'' for Thursday.
Joaquin Lavin, party vice president, said the group is asking
Chileans ``to show the world that our fruits are healthy and of
superior quality.''
   Exporters and growers said Tuesday night they had voluntarily
halted packing and shipping for 72 hours to check inventories.
   Chile's Exporters Association said all fruit should be submitted
to government inspection and none would be exported until it
receives approval from health officials.
   Scores of trucks loaded with fruit were reported idle Tuesday
night in Valparaiso, Chile's principal port city. At many vineyards,
grape pickers were sent back home.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration on Monday announced that
traces of cyanide had been found in two seedless red grapes from
Chile that were in a batch at the port in Philadelphia.
   The discovery came during spot checks by federal officials after
the U.S. and Japanese embassies in Santiago received anonymous
telephone calls earlier this month saying fruit exports would be
poisoned.
   Health officials in the United States, Canada and Japan warned
consumers not to eat Chilean fruit, and stores began removing from
shelves fruit imported from Chile.
   The 12-nation European Economic Community today said it has
received no reports of contamination of Chilean fruit. A spokesman
for the trade bloc, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the EEC
asked its members if they had any evidence of any such contamination.
   Dansk Supermarked, Denmark's second-largest supermarket chain,
has removed Chilean fruit from its shelves as a precaution.
   President Augusto Pinochet sent his ministers of foreign affairs,
Hernan Errazuriz, and Agriculture, Jaime de la Sotta, to Washington
to discuss the crisis with U.S. officials.
   In Hong Kong, health inspectors on Tuesday seized nearly 6.7 tons
of Chilean seedless red grapes from importers and wholesalers for
testing. The government said health inspectors had contacted local
importers to stop sales of the Chilean grapes.
   Chileans reacted strongly to what they saw as a major blow to
their skyrocketing fruit export industry, which was expected to earn
about $850 million this year, up from $581 million in 1988.
   Nearly 65 percent of Chile's fruit exports _ grapes, melons,
apples and peaches _ go to the United States.
   The fruit industry now employs around 500,000 people, and union
leaders reported scattered layoffs on Tuesday.
   The government said the poisoning of the grapes was the work of
``terrorism backed by the Communist Party.''
   Jose Sanfuentes, a spokesman for the Communists, denied his party
was in any way involved. Speaking at a news conference, he
criticized the government for faulty controls of exported fruits.
   Many Chileans said the U.S. reaction was exaggerated.
   ``I don't think an anonymous phone call and two grapes may be
allowed to endanger the entire world trade. It may even be a testing
error,'' de la Sotta said.
   Chile is at the height of the harvesting season and De la Sotta
said it expected to export about 103 million crates of fruit. He
said about 47 million crates had been shipped and another 17 million
were in warehouses awaiting shipment or en route to various
countries.
   Adm. Jose Merino, navy commander and a member of the ruling
military junta, blamed both the Communists and the United States.
   ``This is yet another roguish act of the United States,'' he told
reporters. ``Americans think we are all banana republics. Chile is
not a banana republic.''
   He said Chile should find alternative markets for its fruit and
forget the United States.
</TEXT>
