<FIRST>u f PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0032 03-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Says Quick Budget Accord Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs with comments today; picks up at pvs 3rd graf, ``I
believe ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quick agreement between congressional and
administration budget negotiators is unlikely and Congress may miss
its April 15 deadline for drafting a spending plan, House Majority
Leader Thomas S. Foley said today.
   ``I do not expect this to move very fast,'' Foley, D-Wash., said
as the closed-door talks resumed on Capitol Hill. ``It has to move
over a period of time. it's a gradual process.''
   Foley said he did not expect agreement by March 23, when the
negotiating group is scheduled to report back to President Bush and
the House and Senate leadership. ``I think the 23rd is very early,''
he said.
   ``What we would like to do is meet the April 15 date for a budget
resolution,'' he said. But ``that often has not been possible'' and
a May 15 completion of a fiscal 1990 budget might be more realistic,
he said.
   Bush and congressional leaders agreed at a White House meeting
Tuesday that the talks would aim to develop a consensus on broad
generalities instead of specific programs in hopes of finding
progress before the end of next week.
   ``I believe it is a historic step,'' said Sen. Pete V. Domenici,
R-N.M., the senior Republican on the Budget Committee who gave the
most bubbly assessment following the meeting. ``I look forward to
the beginning of earnest negotiations,'' he said.
   The Democratic chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, Jim
Sasser, D-Tenn., was upbeat but less sanguine.
   ``I think we've got at least a 50-50 chance at this juncture of a
successful negotiation,'' said Sasser. ``I don't want to overstate
the chances of success, however.''
   White House aides have been meeting steadily with congressional
budget writers since Bush on Feb. 9 released his $1.16 trillion
spending plan for fiscal 1990. However, the discussions have dwelled
on the scope and format of their mission as neither side has been
willing to propose either new taxes or new spending cuts to reduce
the deficit.
   At Bush's invitation, the budget negotiators, key committee
chairmen and the party leaders of the House and Senate met Tuesday
at the White House to see if the talks could be moved forward.
   They agreed the talks would aim for an overall balance between
entitlements, other domestic programs, military spending and foreign
aid, and the amount of new government revenue that would be raised.
They would produce overall numbers, but not decide on the policies
needed to implement them.
   ``We (budget negotiators) have in thepast devoted way too much
time concerning ourselves with the details of programs,'' said
Domenici. The details were rightly left to the House and Senate
committees with jurisdiction over the specific programs, he said.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said that
while the product would be only broad numbers, the discussions would
of necessity touch on many specifics and the going could be tough.
``In order to reach these, we have got to have policy discussions
about what's do-able,'' he said.
   Domenici said the talks would also focus first on only fiscal
1990. After that, he said, negotiators might see if there was a
chance for a two-year pact.
   For fiscal 1990, the Gramm-Rudman law calls for reducing the
deficit to $100 billion. Both Democrats and Republicans agree that
goal can be met without a tax increase.
   However, many Democrats contend the fiscal 1991 target of $64
billion can't reached without new taxes, something Bush has
continuously said he would oppose.
   The current talks involve Bush's budget director, Richard Darman,
and the chairman and senior Republicans of the House and Senate
budget committees. The group has said it hopes to reach some
consensus by March 23, when the House begins its Easter reess.
   With the talks moving slowly, the Democratic-controlled Congress
has begun moving ahead with its own budget process.
   The Senate Budget Committee plans to begin public drafting of a
spending plan on Friday, and the House Budget Committee staff is
putting together a package for that panel to consider following the
Easter recess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
