<HEAD>Hospital Management Corp. Shareholders Approve Buyout Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS equity to cost of financing in 6th graf prvs, HCA spokesman
... Picks up 7th graf pvs, A $1.3 billion ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital Corporation of America
shareholders today overwhelmingly approved selling the nation's
largest hospital management company to a management-led group for $5
billion.
   More than 41.7 million shares of common stock were voted in favor
of the debt-financed acquisition. About 5 million shares were voted
against the sale.
   HCA Chairman Thomas Frist Jr. told a standing-room-only group of
shareholders, ``This has been a fantastic 20-plus years.''
   ``It's exceeded many times over the founders' dreams for the
company,'' he said.
   Shareholders voted on the offer of $51-a-share by TF Investments
Inc., the management-led group headed by Frist.
   HCA spokesman Victor L. Campbell said the transaction can be
valued at $6 billion if both debt and equity in the new company is
counted. If the cost of financing isn't counted the pricetag is
about $3.6 billion, he said.
   A $1.3 billion short-term loan must be repaid within two years,
and Campbell said some HCA assets will be sold to meet that
obligation. The loan helped finance the buyout.
   Campbell said a decision still has not been reached on which
assets will be sold.
   HCA is the leading hospital management company in the United
States, with properties that include 79 medical-surgical hospitals
and 48 psychiatric hospitals.
   He said the company's proxy statement to shareholders indicated
subsidiary properties likely will be the first to go.
   ``It would be fair to say the company has no agreement to sell
any of its hospital facilities at this time,'' Campbell said.
   The management group submitted the only buyout proposal by a Nov.
18 deadline set by HCA's board of directors. The board approved the
buyout Nov. 22.
   Co-arrangers for TF Investments' purchase are Morgan Guaranty
Trust Co. of New York and The Chase Manhattan Bank.
   Additional loan commitments were obtained from Continental
Illinois National Bank &amp; Trust Co. of Chicago, General Electric
Capital Corp., the Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Toronto -Dominion
Bank and Deutsche Bank.
   The group received equity commitments from Frist, HCA management
and Richard Rainwater for $125 million, the HCA stock bonus
retirement plan for $75 million and $100 million from ``affiliates
of certain of the lenders,'' a HCA statement said.
   HCA is the leading hospital management company in the United
States, with properties that include 79 medical-surgical hospitals
and 48 psychiatric hospitals.
</TEXT>
