<FIRST>r f BC-Maxwell-European     03-15 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Maxwell-European,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maxwell Says New European Paper Due This Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Robert Maxwell said Wednesday his new
newspaper, The European, originally scheduled to be launched in May
as a daily, will begin publishing this autumn as a weekly.
   Maxwell told the Foreign Press Association that The European
would initially be a weekend paper.
   The owner of Mirror Group Newspapers said research has convinced
him the paper should begin as a weekly ``to establish a base from
which daily publication could begin.''
   Maxwell said differences between the French and British
executives of The European were part of the reason for postponing
its launch.
   ``I could hardly launch a newspaper dedicated to the concept of
European unity with a warring crew,'' he said.
   ``I think I can now see my way toward preserving the peace or, if
not, ensuring that any hostility which remains is constructive,' he
said.
   Maxwell said The European, ``printed mostly in English,'' would
be published on Fridays to create a ``firm footing in a new market
from which we can later begin a daily publication.''
   ``Our purpose is to inform, enlighten, entertain and propagate
the ideals of a Europe united from the Atlantic to the Urals,''
Maxwell said.
   ``The weekly edition will be more able to analyze and report the
issues which affect the daily lives of the people of Europe, as well
as their interests in the arts, sport, fashion and humor, savings,
finance, politics, science, medicine and agriculture.
   ``We will be a good and exciting newspaper and a must for all
those who recognize that Europe is our only true future,'' he said.
</TEXT>
