<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NYSE     03-15 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-NYSE,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYSE Earnings Fall 69.4 Percent In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange said Wednesday its
profit fell 69.4 percent last year because of a decline in trading
from the record level of 1987.
   The Big Board said it earned $10.4 million, down from $34.1
million, as revenue from the NYSE and its subsidiaries fell 7.4
percent to $323.5 million from a record $349.4 million in 1987.
   Trading volume of 40.8 billion shares was the second highest ever
but down 14.5 percent from the record of 47.8 billion shares a year
earlier. Trading in 1987 was swollen by the bull market that
prevailed for most of the year and then by the crash that occurred
in October.
   Average daily trading volume fell to 161.5 million shares in 1988
from 188.9 million in 1987, the exchange said.
   The decline in trading was partially offset by increased revenue
from new listings. A record 155 companies joined the NYSE last year,
it said.
   The exchange, a not-for-profit company, gets most of its revenue
from fees charged to companies for being listed on the exchange and
fees on daily trades. It reports its earnings annually.
</TEXT>
