<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Trade 4thLd-Writethru f0082 03-15 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade, 4th Ld-Writethru, f0082,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mechandise Trade Gap Narrows in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead and 10th graf, The trade ... to CORRECT that deficit
with Japan is lowest in 2{ years sted of almost four years. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed to
$9.49 billion in January, as the nation posted a rare trade surplus
with Western Europe and the imbalance with Japan declined to its
lowest point in 2{ years, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the sharp 13.7 percent improvement
in the overall trade deficit, the best showing since October,
reflected a 6.9 percent drop in imports that was enough to offset a
4.3 percent decline in U.S. export sales.
   While the trade improvement was hailed by the Bush
administration, many private analysts said the figures did not
change their view that America's trading performance would most
likely weaken in 1989 as the U.S. boom in export sales slows and
America's oil bill increases because of higher world oil prices.
   The $9.49 billion January deficit would translate into an annual
imbalance of $114 billion, compared with a deficit for all of 1988
of $119.76 billion.
   Michael Evans, head of a Washington forecasting firm, said he
expected this year's deficit to rise to around $130 billion,
reflecting in large part the fact that world oil prices have not hit
$18 per barrel, up from lows approaching $12 per barrel last year.
   ``That is a huge increase in the price of oil and will likely add
$1 billion to our oil bill each month,'' Evans said. ``When you
combine that with the fact that our export boom has run out of
steam, the January report is going to be the last reduction we get
in our trade deficit for quite some time.''
   But the Bush administration's top trade officials, Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher and U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hills, called the January improvement an encouraging sign that the
deficit is continuing to decline.
   ``The year is starting on a plus note,'' Mosbacher said in his
statement. ``Our aim should be to build on this improvement in the
months ahead, and I will do all in my power to encourage businesses,
large and small, to sell U.S. products abroad.''
   The January deficit reflected a rare surplus of $46.5 million
with Western Europe, the first trade surplus there since September
1983.
   The trade deficit with Japan dropped to $3.5 billion. While this
was, as usual, the highest imbalance the United States had with any
country, it was the lowest deficit with Japan since June 1986, when
it was $3.37 billion. The Commerce Department had originally said
the deficit with Japan was the lowest since February 1985 but after
further checking corrected that statement.
   The $9.49 billion January trade imbalance followed a $10.99
billion deficit in December and was the smallest imbalance since
$8.78 billion in October.
   Starting with the January report, the government is removing the
cost of shipping and insurance from the import totals, a bookkeeping
change that has the effect of lowering each month's trade deficit by
about $1.5 billion. The adjustments were also made to the prior
months' data to conform with the new reporting system.
   With shipping and insurance charges included, the 1988
merchandise trade deficit was $137.3 billion and with those costs
removed the deficit totaled $119.76 billion.
   The January performance reflected a 6.9 percent decline in
imports, which fell to a seasonally adjusted $37.29 billion.
   The smaller import figure reflected declines in sales of foreign
consumer goods, down $1.4 billion, and a drop in sales of foreign
cars, down $700 million.
   U.S. imports of oil were up sharply in January, rising 6.1
percent to $3.5 billion, reflecting higher petroleum prices. The
price per barrel jumped to $14.46 from $13.10 in December, while the
number of barrels fell to 7.8 million barrels per day from 8.11
million barrels in December.
   U.S. export sales fell 4.3 percent to $27.8 billion, down from a
record $29.06 billion in December.
   The drop reflected declines in sales of capital goods, down $1.2
billion, and industrial supplies, which fell $600 million.
   The measurement change removing the costs of shipping and
insurance, adopted by Congress at the urging of the Reagan
administration, will return the government to the trade accounting
procedures used before 1979.
   Starting in that year, the government included the costs paid to
foreigners to ship and insure their products as part of the
country's total import bill. Former Sen. Russell Long, D-La.,
sponsored an amendment making the change.
   However, Reagan administration officials argued that the shipping
costs were actually payments for services and should be included in
the services category of the current account trade report, which
breaks U.S. trade down into trade in merchandise and trade in
services.
   The government released data on Tuesday showing that the current
account deficit for 1988 totaled $135.3 billion, a 12.1 percent
improvement from the all-time high of $153.96 billion set in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-15 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0347</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices edged higher on Wall Street today after
the government reported a slightly smaller-than-expected U.S. trade
deficit for January.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.89 to 2,312.14
by 2 p.m. EST. Earlier, the closely-watched index was up nearly 15
points, but gave back some of its gains.
   Advancers ran slightly ahead of losers in nationwide trading of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 652 up, 633 down and 586
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 122.52 million shares at
mid-afternoon.
   The Commerce Department reported that the nation's trade deficit
narrowed to $9.49 billion in January from a revised $10.99 billion
the month before.
   The data, which were formerly reported in two ways, are now
posted only under a method that excludes costs of freight and
insurance.
   The latest figure came in below most Wall Street economists'
estimates, prompting some buying by traders.
   Michael Metz, a market analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co., said
traders were pleased by declines in U.S. imports and exports, which
investors interpreted as indicating a possible cooling off in the
economy.
   But the market gave up ground as traders worried that less
favorable news might be looming when the monthly figures on the
producer price index of finished goods are issued on Friday.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Hospital Corp. of
America, which rose [ to 49\ after the company's shareholders
approved a buyout by a management group.
   Sea Containers Ltd. gained 1\ to 45} on top of an 8{-point jump
Tuesday, when investors learned that Stena AB of Sweden has acquired
an 8.17 percent interest in the company and may seek to gain control
of it.
   Among the blue chips, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose \ to 32
while International Business Machines slipped { to 117].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.22 to 166.15. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.64 at 331.17.
