<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0056 03-15 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0056,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices ended lower Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange, a day after Britain's fiscal 1990 budget was
unveiled.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 4.2
points, or 0.02 percent, to 2,121.2. The index was down as much as
16.4 points at midmorning.
   Volume accelerated to 619.5 million shares from Tuesday's 587.1
million shares.
   Share prices were depressed from the outset of trading, but later
picked up following news that the U.S. trade deficit narrowed in
January.
   Strong gains in early Wall Street business also pulled up
equities toward the end of the London session.
   While most traders on Tuesday cheered the government's tight
fiscal policy in the face of inflationary pressures in the economy,
worries began to emerge Wednesday that such fiscal caution could put
the pinch on corporate profits in coming months.
   Others dealers, however, dismissed such concerns, saying the
market was merely taking a breather after running up strongly ahead
of the budget.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 6.8 points at 1,754.3
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 2.57 points
to close at 1,208.63.
