<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Trade 1stLd-Writethru a0651 03-15 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Merchandise Trade Deficit Narrows Sharply</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 2, ``The Commerce ... and 14, ``The trade,'' to CORRECT
historial reference on deficit with Japan. Also moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed
sharply in January to $9.49 billion, the lowest imbalance in three
months, as a big decline in consumer imports offset a higher oil
bill, the government reported Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said that the imbalance between imports
and exports fell by 13.7 percent from a revised December deficit of
$10.99 billion as the United States posted a rare trade surplus with
Europe and the deficit with Japan fell to its lowest point in 2{
years.
   The Bush administration hailed the development as an encouraging
sign of progress in whittling down the country's huge trade deficit,
but many private economists were far less encouraged.
   Some analysts called the January figure a one-month fluke in what
they believe will be an otherwise dreary outlook for U.S. trade
prospects this year.
   In 1988, the U.S. trade deficit declined by 21 percent to $119.76
billion as a boom in export sales helped provide two-fifths of the
year's total economic growth.
   But analysts are forecasting that export sales, despite
aggressive market-opening efforts on the part of the administration,
will slow significantly in 1989 while America's foreign oil bill
increases, reflecting rising world oil prices.
   ``The January report is going to be the last reduction we get in
our trade deficit for quite some time,'' said Michael Evans, head of
a Washington forecating firm. ``Our export boom ran out of steam
some time ago and now we are seeing the effect of higher oil
prices.''
   Evans predicted that the U.S. trade deficit would actually
increase to $130 billion this year, based on the adverse trends.
That would be a blow to the administration, which is counting on
export-led growth to help keep the U.S. economy moving forward at a
rapid clip, bringing in the government revenues needed to lower the
federal budget deficit.
   Both Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills, the administration's top trade
officials, issued statements hailing the January decline as an
encouraging development.
   ``The year is starting on a plus note,'' Mosbacher said. ``Our
aim should be to build on this improvement in the months ahead.''
   The administration has adopted a tough trade stance, pledging to
work aggressively to open foreign markets to more U.S. products. But
many private economists expressed doubt that there is much room left
for American exports to grow, given the 27 percent jump in export
sales which occurred last year.
   ``We have to get a decline in imports for us to mount another
significant improvement in our trade deficit,'' said Allen Sinai,
chief economist of the Boston Co. Sinai said any lasting drop in
imports was unlikely until there is a significant slowdown in the
U.S. economy.
   The January deficit reflected a surplus of $46.5 million with
Western Europe, the first trade surplus there since September 1983,
primarily reflecting higher U.S. sales in Britain and France.
   The trade deficit with Japan dropped to $3.5 billion with
two-fifths of that decline reflecting a drop in Japanese car
imports. The Japanese deficit, as usual the largest of any country,
fell to its lowest point since a $3.37 billion imbalance in June
1986.
   William T. Archey, the top trade expert with the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said it remained to be seen whether this decline was just
a blip in the monthly statistics or reflected the fact that more
Japanese cars are being manufactured at plants in the United States.
   Starting with the January report, the government is removing the
cost of shipping and insurance from the import totals, a bookkeeping
change that has the effect of lowering each month's trade deficit by
about $1.5 billion. The adjustments were also made to the prior
months' data to conform with the new reporting system.
   With shipping and insurance charges included, the 1988
merchandise trade deficit was $137.3 billion. The measurement change
removing the costs of shipping and insurance, adopted by Congress at
the urging of the Reagan administration, will return the government
to the trade accounting procedures used before 1979.
   The January deficit of $9.49 billion reflected declines in both
imports and exports, which had hit all-time record levels in
December.
   U.S. imports fell by 6.9 percent to $37.29 billion as sales of
foreign consumer goods declined by $1.4 billion and foreign car
shipments declined by $700 million.
   U.S. imports of oil, however, were up sharply in January, rising
6.1 percent to $3.5 billion, reflecting rising prices. The price per
barrel jumped to $14.46 from $13.10 in December, while the number of
barrels fell to 7.8 million barrels per day from 8.11 million
barrels in December.
   Analysts said with world oil prices already at $18 per barrel,
America's oil bill would be rising even higher in the future.
   U.S. export sales fell 4.3 percent to $27.8 billion, down from a
record $29.06 billion in December. The drop reflected declines in
sales of capital goods, down $1.2 billion, and industrial supplies,
which fell $600 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
