<FIRST>r f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-15 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Varied In Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against most currencies in
European trading Wednesday after the U.S. government released its
latest trade data. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market was calm after it was
reported that the January U.S. trade gap shrank to $9.49 billion
from a revised deficit of $10.99 billion in December.
   ``Overall, the trade figures were non-controversial,'' said the
chief dealer at a U.S. bank in London. ``They were neither good nor
bad, and they opened the way for the market to do what it wanted to
do naturally _ buy dollars.''
   Another dealer agreed: ``The dollar is being boosted by natural
business.''
   The U.S. Federal Reserve reportedly intervened when most trading
in London had ended for the day.
   The British pound continued to benefit from Tuesday's national
budget presented by Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who
indicated interest rates would remain high to combat inflat.
   Dealers predicted the pound will continue upward.
   Late Wednesday, one British pound closed at $1.7235, more
expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7170.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Tuesday's
late rates: 1.8670 West German marks, up from 1.8630; 1.6038 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5935; 6.3200 French francs, up from, 6.3125;
2.1065 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1010; 1,369.37 Italian lire, up
from 1,366.12; and 1.1935 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1970.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.88 Japanese yen, down
from 129.92. In London the dollar traded higher at 130.27 yen.
   Gold bullion prices declined on profit-taking in light trading.
   The late bid price for gold in London was $392.25 a troy ounce,
down from $395.75. The late Zurich bid price was $393.25 an ounce,
down from 395.25.
   Earlie,r in Hong Kong, gold closed at $395.91 an ounce, up from
$395.37.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.12 a troy ounce, down
from $6.17.
</TEXT>
