<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed to
mostly lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat was hampered by profit-taking early, and stayed under
pressure most of the day because of selling by a large commission
house and traders' indifference to some forecasts for less rain this
weekend for the winter wheat growing regions of the Plains.
   With little news on either side, beans and corn held to narrow
ranges throughout the day.
   ``We just marked time all day,'' said Vic Lespinasse, a floor
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds, Chicago. ``There was no real
definition in any of the markets.''
   On the close, wheat was 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
lower to } cent higher, with March at $2.77 a bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 1{ cents lower, with March at $2.08\ a bushel; and soybeans
were 2{ cents lower to 2 cents higher, with March at $7.66{ a bushel.
