<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-15 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Claims Polaroid's Self-Tender Offer Is Misleading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. claimed Wednesday that
Polaroid Inc.'s tender offer for 16 million of its shares is
misleading under Securities and Exchange Commission rules, but
Polaroid called the complaint a delay tactic.
   In U.S. District Court in Wilmington, Del., Judge Caleb Wright
heard arguments from lawyers representing the two companies, which
have been embroiled in a hostile takeover battle for months. Wright
reserved judgment on the matter until later this week.
   Shamrock representatives said the self-tender offer, at $50 a
share and expiring March 20, is misleading because Polaroid hasn't
released a full and fair disclosure of its pertinent information,
such as records of the company's settlement with Kodak over instant
photography technology. But Polaroid said Shamrock wants to delay
the closing and gain a tactical advantage by buying all the
available shares for $45 each.
   ``What Shamrock wants desperately here is delay,'' said Polaroid
attorney Robert S. Rifkind.
   Polaroid's stock repurchase offer is subject to various
conditions, including definitive financing, an absence of adverse
decisions in lawsuits with Shamrock, and changes in Shamrock's
hostile bid.
   Polaroid has been resisting Shamrock's hostile takeover bid since
July, when the Burbank, Calif., company made a friendly but
unsolicited offer of $40 a share. In January, it upped the bid to
$45.
   Polaroid last July put 9.7 million shares into an employee stock
ownership plan. In January, the company announced a recapitalization
plan that included selling $300 million of stock to Corporate
Partners L.P., a private investment group.
   Shamrock, a television and radio concern owned by the Roy E.
Disney family, owns about 4.8 million shares of Polaroid and is
waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the
May 9 annual meeting, in addition to its hostile tender offer.
   The companies are also expecting a decision this week from a
lower Delaware court on whether a judge will combine her decision on
Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan with a new request for a
preliminary injunction by Shamrock against Polaroid's agreement with
Corporate Partners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Time-Warner     03-15 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Executives To Be Well Paid in Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed $18 billion merger between Time Inc.
and Warner Communications Inc. could be a highly lucrative
transaction for top executives of the two media firms, the companies
said.
   Warner Chairman Steven Ross is expected to get nearly $50 million
by exercising stock rights under his employment contract when the
merger takes place, the company said in a filing Tuesday with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Ross will receive a salary of $800,000 a year and a share of the
profits in the merged company, Time Warner Inc. The arrangement is
roughly equivalent to compensation Ross receives at Warner, the
company said.
   Other top Warner executives could receive as much as $15 million
each by exercising their rights under Warner stock's option plan,
Warner said. The plan allows the executives to cash in their
holdings in the event of a merger.
   At Time, Chairman J. Richard Munro and President N.J. Nicholas
Jr. will not receive large cash payouts as a result of the merger
that will create the world's largest media concern. However, they
stand to draw large salaries under their compensation agreements
with the new company.
   Munro, who will serve as co-chairman of Warner with Ross for the
next two years, will receive at least $1.46 million in annual salary
and bonuses, Time spokesman Louis Slovinsky said.
   If Munro retires before May 1990 he will receive nearly $4.28
million in deferred compensation and still be paid $750,000 a year
as chairman of the executive committee, Slovinsky said.
   The terms are similar to those Munro would have at Time without a
merger, but provide for increases depending on how well Time Warner
performs.
   Nicholas, who will succeed Munro and is expected to become Time
Warner's sole chief executive after five years, will be paid at
least $1.3 million annually. However, the company said stock options
expected to be granted to Nicholas and other Time executives could
sharply increase his compensation.
   Warner Communications has a larger compensation structure than
Time does. The Wall Street Journal quoted sources as saying Time
Warner likely will bring Time managers in line with their Warner
counterparts after the merger is completed.
   The merger, which will be accomplished through a stock swap, will
create a company with projected annual revenue of $10 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890315-0302 </DOCNO>
