<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FuturesMeeting Bjt   03-15 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Futures Meeting, Bjt,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Leaders Gather Under Cloud of Fed Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures industry leaders gathered
Wednesday for their annual four-day meeting amid speculation that
federal authorities in Chicago were preparing to charge six people
in connection with an investigation of trading fraud in the
commodities pits.
   Anton Valukas, the U.S. attorney in Chicago, would not comment on
the rumors, which have been spreading among defense attorneys.
   Meanwhile, some congressmen who usually attend the Futures
Industry Association's annual meeting at the industry's expense
reportedly have made other plans this year, apparently wanting to
avoid appearing to be too close to the industry.
   The government's wide-ranging undercover investigation of
commodity futures trading at the Chicago Board of Trade and the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange has yielded no charges since it was
disclosed on Jan. 19.
   The probe is believed to focus on as many as 100 traders and on
allegations that they systematically cheated customers out of
millions of dollars while executing their orders on the trading
floors of the world's two largest futures exchanges.
   Futures are contracts to buy and sell commodities and financial
instruments at a specified price on a future date.
   Some lawyers representing traders and firms targeted by the
investigation said they believed Valukas was preparing to charge
about half a dozen people in the near future.
   They did not dismiss the possibility that charges may be
announced in Chicago while many futures-industry leaders _ exchange
officials, brokerage executives and commodities lawyers _ are
gathered in Boca Raton.
   ``It would be kind of true to form,'' said Chicago attorney
Gerald Fishman, who recalled that the Chicago Tribune broke the
first story of the investigation while many of the top commodities
lawyers were at an American Bar Association meeting at a Caribbean
resort.
   ``It might have some timely impact to do it while everyone's
gathered together,'' said Jeffrey Cole, another Chicago-based
commodities lawyer.
   About 1,100 people are attending the Futures Industry Association
meeting at the posh Boca Raton Resort and Club, where panel
discussions were scheduled on such topics as regulation, customer
protection and congressional reauthorization of the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, the federal agency that oversees futures
trading.
   Reauthorization of the CFTC, which begins with the House and
Senate Agriculture committees, has been delayed by concerns raised
by the Chicago investigation
   About 20 members of Congress are expected to attend the meeting.
The Chicago Tribune reported on Wednesday that some have will not
have their expenses paid by the trade group or by futures exchanges
and will not accept speaking fees.
   House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza,
D-Texas, who usually attends the meeting, decided not to go after
reports of the investigation surfaced, the Tribune reported, citing
an unnamed source it said was close to the committee.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., who is heading the House panel's
investigation into alleged trading abuses, will travel to Florida at
the committee's expense and won't accept a speaking fee for his
appearance at a luncheon Thursday, the Tribune reported, quoting an
unidentified aide.
   Futures Industry Association President John Damgard said some
congressmen ``may want to avoid any semblance of being too close to
the industry'' in light of the federal probe and the CFTC hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
