<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-15 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar headed sharply higher Wednesday
against major foreign currencies in active trading after the
government reported that the January trade deficit shrank to its
lowest level in three months.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $391.10 a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EST, down $4.40
from Tuesday's late bid.
   Currency dealers said the trade report, while in line with
general market expectations, helped revive interest in the dollar
here and abroad.
   ``They (the trade figures) were neither good nor bad, and they
opened the way for the market to do what it wanted to do naturally _
buy dollars,'' explained the chief dealer at a U.S. bank in London.
   The report issued by the Commerce Department showed the trade gap
shrank to $9.49 billion in January from a revised December shortfall
of $10.99 billion, due to a rare surplus with Europe and a decline
in the deficit with Japan. That was the smallest overall imbalance
since $8.78 billion in October.
   Dealers reported that the Federal Reserve sold dollars on at
least three occasions Wednesday, but that such intervention had
little affect on the dollar.
   ``They just wanted to make their presence known,'' said Robert
Ryan, senior trader Irving Trust Co.
   Also helping the dollar Wednesday was the yen's weakness, dealers
said.
   In Tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar closed at
129.88 Japanese yen, down from 129.92 yen. The dollar traded at
130.27 yen in London, and at 130.60 yen in New York, up from 129.79
yen late Tuesday.
   The British pound rose to $1.7235 in London from Tuesday's late
$1.7170. Sterling fetched $1.7200 in New York, down from $1.7280.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's late
rates, included: 1.87225 West German marks, up from 1.86075; 1.6080
Swiss francs, up from 1.5930; 1.19635 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19385; 6.3355 French francs, up from 6.3065; and 1,373.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,365.75.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Tuesday: 1.8670
West German marks, up from 1.8630; 1.6038 Swiss francs, up from
1.5935; 6.3200 French francs, up from, 6.3125; 2.1065 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1010; 1.1935 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1970;
and 1,369.37 Italian lire, up from 1,366.12.
   Gold prices declined largely on profit-taking, dealers said.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $392.10 a troy ounce, down from $396.20 Tuesday.
   Gold settled at $392.25 an ounce in London, down from $395.75.
The late Zurich bid was $393.25 an ounce, down from 395.25.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $395.91 an ounce, up from
$395.37.
   Silver prices also weakened. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $6.091 a troy ounce, down from
$6.176 Tuesday. Silver fell in London to $6.12 an ounce from $6.17.
</TEXT>
