<FIRST>r f AM-OilLeaseSale     03-15 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Lease Sale,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Gulf Leasae Sale Attracts High Bids of $397.5 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McKNIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies who offered more than $18
million were the highest bidders for federal oil and gas leases sold
Wednesday in the central Gulf of Mexico.
   FMP Operating Co. and Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Co.
entered the joint bid on a 5,000-acre block in the heavily explored
West Delta region south of Plaquemines Parish, La.
   Bids were received on 2.9 million acres of the 32.1 million acres
offered for lease by the Interior Department. High bids totaled
$397.5 million, according to J. Rogers Pearcy, regional director of
Interior's Mineral Management Service.
   ``It was comparable to last year's sale. We didn't have quite as
much deep-water bidding this time,'' said Pearcy.
   In a 1983 lease sale, Pearcy said the government leased $1.4
billion worth of deep-water tracts for a five-year term.
Lease-holders relinquished or let expire 303 of those leases, but
127 of them were resold Wednesday, Pearcy said.
   ``The interest in these previously leased tracts indicates that
the Central Gulf continues to capture the attention of the oil and
gas industry as a promising province,'' said Robert Kallman,
director of MMS.
   ``Throughout the history of oil and gas exploration in the Gulf,
many of the larger discoveries have come from tracts which had been
previously leased,'' said Kallman.
   Last year, 931 bids were received on 684 tracts. This year, 821
bids were received on 591 tracts. One tract got seven bids, but many
attracted only one bidder.
   More small companies participated this year in the annual lease
sale, said an MMS spokeswoman.
   ``We're seeing a number of small and new companies that have not
participated before,'' said Eileen Angelico.
   Angelico said 117 companies qualified to bid this year compared
to 112 last year; 81 actually bid, compared to 84 in 1987, she said.
</TEXT>
