<FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 1909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-15 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Roll to Gains for Third Straight Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rolled up impressive gains for a third
straight session Wednesday after a report showed a
larger-than-expected drawdown in U.S. gas stocks last week and Saudi
Arabia's announcement that it would cut allocations to U.S. and
European customers by as much as 30 percent.
   On other markets, precious metals plummeted despite some signs
inflation was heating up and livestock futures were higher and pork
futures mostly higher as traders awaited a key government report and
tried to estimate demand in coming weeks.
   Energy futures took off from the opening bell, stoked by an
American Petroleum Institute (API) report released after the close
of the markets Tuesday that showed gasoline stocks down by 4.7
million barrels and distillate stocks down by 5.9 million over the
previous week.
   The range of estimates preceding the API report ranged from no
change to a drawdown of about 2 million barrels in gasoline stocks.
   The larger-than-expected declines sent prices zooming. Gasoline
took over leadership of the complex from crude oil and the April
contract broke important resistance at 54.50 cents _ a price level
it had scaled three times since last spring but failed to surmount.
   Alos helping prices was a report that Saudi Arabia told the
Aramco Partners, which include most of the largest U.S. and Western
European oil suppliers, that their daily allotment of 1.3 million
barrels would be cut between 20 and 30 percent for April.
   The Saudis, apparently seeking to toe the OPEC line and keep
within production quotas, similarly cut Japanese allotments a day
earlier.
   ``After today, you're looking at the highest energy prices since
the summer of 1987. But it's hard to delineate what propelled the
market,'' said Jim Ritterbusch, vice president of trading and
research for Carson Petroleum.
   ``The API report was a definite spark ... so was the Saudis
cutting back. But once the shelf came out at 54.50, there was a lot
of panic.''
   Crude oil settled 11 cents to 48 cents higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with the contract for delivery in April at
$19.77 a barrel. Heating oil was .38 cent to 1.79 cents higher, with
April at 54.19 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline soared 1.45
cents to 2.30 cents higher, with April at 55.80 cents a gallon.
   Several analysts said the inflationary implications of higher
energy prices may have been the major reason that the precious
metals, slumping in recent months, didn't fall further Wednesday.
   Precious metals, viewed by investors as a hedge against
inflation, came under pressure at the start of the day after release
of a better-than-expected figure on the U.S. trade deficit.
   Platinum slipped $11 to $11.20 lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, with April at $538.30 a troy ounce. Gold settled $4.10 to
$4.80 lower at the Comex, with March at $392.10 a troy ounce; and
silver was 2 cents to 3.1 cents lower, with March at $6.091 a troy
ounce.
   ``It could have been worse if the oil prices hadn't worked to
cushion the decline,'' said Craig Sloane, a metals analyst with
Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co., New York.
   Livestock futures posted modest gains, although some traders
stayed on the sidelines in anticipation of Thursday's U.S.
Department of Agriculture's report. The report is expected to show
slightly fewer cattle on feedlots than at the same time last year,
but some traders suspect the weights might be lower, indicating the
animals will come to market later.
   ``We've got record-high prices for beef at retail,'' said Chuck
Levitt, analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Chicago, ``but
complicating things is the fact that the trade doesn't have a good
handle on what demand is going to be like in the coming weeks.''
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .42 cent higher, with April at 77.77
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .32 cent higher, March
at 80.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower to .25 cent
higher, with April at 43.65 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .10 cent lower to .58 cent higher, with March at 38.15 cents a
pound.
   Grain and soybeans prices closed mixed to mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat was 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.37{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to }
cent higher, with March at $2.77 a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 1{
cents lower, with March at $2.08\ a bushel; and soybeans were 2{
cents lower to 2 cents higher, with March at $7.66{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
