<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Congress 1stLd-Writethru f0193 03-15 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0193,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To End Eastern Walkout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 8 grafs with House passage; picks up 7th graf pvs,
The bill ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed legislation Wednesday that
would require a recalcitrant President Bush to name an emergency
panel to try to end the devastating Machinists union strike against
Eastern Airlines.
   The labor-backed bill was approved on a mostly party line 252-167
vote by the House, where most of the majority Democrats are
sympathetic to the airline's unions.
   Rep. Glenn Anderson, D-Calif., chairman of the House Public Works
Committee, said the measure ``offers the best hope of resolving the
current labor dispute, which threatens the survival of Eastern
Airlines.''
   But Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark., ranking GOP member of
the public works committee, said the emergency panel was not needed
because, despite the strike, ``there is no national transportation
emergency.''
   The measure was considered a long shot to become law because of
opposition from the Bush administration. But House passage of the
legislation seems to score several political points for unions and
their Democratic allies.
   It forces Bush and his Republican supporters to resist a measure
that is also opposed by Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of Eastern's
parent company, Texas Air Corp. Lorenzo is a widely unpopular figure
on Capitol Hill, where he has been criticized by Democrats,
Republicans and even Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner for
his business practices.
   It focuses attention on Bush's refusal to follow the
recommendation of the National Mediation Board, which urged the
president to name an emergency panel on Feb. 24, eight days before
the walkout. Since 1926, the mediation board has asked presidents to
name emergency panels in 34 airline disputes and they have always
consented _ until Bush's refusal.
   It also demonstrates that labor, which was often battered during
the Reagan administration years, can still move legislation in
Congress.
   The bill would give the president one day after enactment to
appoint a board, which would study the dispute and offer a
recommendation to end the strike. While the board did its work,
there would be a cooling-off period of up to 26 days, during which
Eastern would have to pay pre-strike wages to its workers.
   Supporters say the neutral board's recommendations could offer a
face-saving way for the two sides to reach an agreement without
seeming to make concessions. If labor or management reject the
proposed solution, Congress could later impose it with separate
legislation, they argue.
   Opponents argue that an emergency panel is not needed because the
strike has caused inconvenience but not a national emergency. They
also say the board would have little chance of solving a bitter
battle that has been building for 17 months.
   The 8,500 members of the International Association of Machinists,
which represents mechanics, baggage handlers and other ramp workers,
walked off their jobs March 4. Eastern was seeking a new contract
with $125 million in wage and benefit concessions, while the workers
wanted $50 million in improvements. The airline said it was losing
$1.5 million a day before the strike, and has lost $1 billion over
the last decade.
   The airline's pilots and flight attendants have joined the
walkout, forcing Eastern to pare its 1,040-flights-per-day schedule
back to about 100. On March 9, Eastern sought protection from its
creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, making
the carrier's future murky.
   The bill would also require that the emergency board recommend
terms for new contracts between Eastern and its pilots' and flight
attendants' unions, both of whose contracts have expired.
   The legislation's future in the Senate is shakey because under
the chamber's procedures, a minority of lawmakers can kill a bill.
Bush has said he opposes the measure, arguing that labor and
management must work out a solution between themselves.
Administration officials have indicated Bush would veto the measure
should it ever emerge from Congress.
</TEXT>
