<FIRST>u f AM-Metromedia-ITT     03-15 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Metromedia-ITT,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metromedia To Buy ITT's Long Distance Telephone Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent company of Metromedia Long
Distance announced Wednesday it intends to buy ITT Corp.'s
long-distance telephone division, making Metromedia one of the five
largest long-distance carriers in the United States.
   Metromedia Long Distance did not disclose in its letter of intent
the purchase price for ITT Communications Services, Inc. The
proposed sale also would include ITT Chernow Communications Inc.,
the call-accounting equipment and services unit of ITT
Communications.
   ``Our goal is to grow the business, not only within geographic
segments, but with new products and services, and thereby better
serve our customers,'' said John W. Kluge, chairman of Metromedia
Corp.
   The long-distance division of ITT is concentrated in the
Northeast, Southeast and West. Metromedia Long Distance provides
service to parts of Texas, Florida and the New York-New Jersey area.
   ``They are a perfect complement to where we're located,'' said
Carole Smargon, a spokeswoman for Metromedia Long Distance.
   State and federal regulatory agencies must approve the
transaction, expected to be completed in the fall, Metromedia said.
   Ms. Smargon would not disclose the total assets of both
companies. Metromedia Long Distance has about 600 employees and ITT
Communnications has about 1,100, she said.
   Metromedia is a privately held partnership that owns and operates
companies in the telecommunications, robotic painting, computer
software and hospitality industries. It also owns a majority share
in Orion Pictures.
   Previously it owned one of the largest television station groups,
as well as major cellular-paging, radio broadcasting and outdoor
advertising operations.
</TEXT>
