<FIRST>u f AM-FordBronco 2ndLd-Writethru f0269 03-15 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford Bronco, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0269,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study That Cleared Suzuki Samurai Leads To Ford Bronco II Rollover
Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, Last September, with 2 grafs to CORRECT that
action in August on petition filed by Center for Auto Safety, not Consumers
Union, adds details. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials announced Wednesday an
investigation of alleged rollover danger in Ford Bronco IIs, after
finding the Bronco fared worst in an accident study which cleared
the Suzuki Samurai of similar allegations.
   An engineering analysis, which is the second of three levels of
investigation conducted by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, will cover 1984-1989 Bronco IIs, an agency spokesman
said.
   Studies of vehicle fatalities showed the four-wheel-drive Bronco
II has had more fatal rollovers than other vehicles in its class,
even taking into account miles traveled and the number of vehicles
in use, said spokesman Tim Hurd.
   According to a Fatal Accident Reporting System study included in
a 1988 report on the Samurai, 43 Bronco II single-vehicle rollovers
caused fatalities, or 19 for every 100,000 vehicles. There were 8
Samurai fatal rollovers, or 6 per 100,000 vehicles; 13 involving the
Chevrolet S10 Blazers or GMC Jimmy, or 6 per 100,000, and 6 fatal
Jeep Cherokee rollovers, for 2.5 per 100,000.
   Ford Motor Co., in a statement from Detroit, said it believes the
record of its 590,000 Bronco IIs is not significantly different from
that of other utility vehicles.
   ``The Bronco II is a well-designed, safe utility vehicle, and
Ford believes that the accident statistics do not reflect any
safety-related defect in the vehicle,'' the company said, adding
that accidents in all such vehicles are ``strongly influenced by
adverse driver or environmental factors.''
   Spokeswoman Barbara Mansfield said Ford has done extensive
testing on the Bronco II to verify it has ``reasonable and
appropriate handling and stability characteristics.''
   Hurd, speaking for the highway safety administration, said, ``The
Ford Bronco II appears to have a higher number of single-vehicle,
first-event rollovers, particularly those involving fatalities.''
   ``In the process of studying rollovers, we began to get curious
about the Bronco,'' he said.
   Hurd said investigators will analyze rollovers involving the
sport-utility vehicle to determine if environment, types of drivers
or the vehicle itself might have contributed to the accidents.
   He said that although the call for an engineering analysis of the
Bronco II was formally based on letters to the safety
administration, it is also the result of the Samurai investigation
and extensive study into rollovers. He said there have been several
petitions for the agency to adopt rollover standards covering all
vehicles.
   Last August, the agency concluded that critics of the Samurai
failed to demonstrate the little truck has an excessive tendency to
roll over and denied a recall petition filed by the Center for Auto
Safety, a public-interest group often at odds with the auto industry
and its regulators.
   Consumer Reports magazine, in a July 1988 issue, also called for
a ban of the Samurai, saying ``it literally trips over its own
feet.'' The magazine's publisher, Consumer Union, petitioned the
safety administration to draft regulations to guard against
rollovers.
   In other action Wednesday, the highway safety agency announced
the start of several preliminary evaluations, the lowest level of
investigation. They included allegations of:
   _ Parking brake failures in selected models of 1980-84 Ford Motor
Co. cars.
   _ Exhaust gas intrusion into the passenger compartment of 1986-87
Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable cars, following 10 complaints; 795,000
of the vehicles were manufactured.
   _ Locking of the power steering mechanism in 1986-89 Ford
Aerostar vans, following seven complaints involving three, two
injuries and two fatalities; 350,000 have been built. were built Aero
   _ Possible heater hose misrouting which may cause fires in
ambulance conversions built by more than 40 manufacturers.
   In addition, the safety agency closed investigations into
unsubstantiated reports of:
   _ Broken drivers seats in 1984-87 Chrysler Caravan and Dodge
Voyager vans.
   _ Defective power steering hoses in 1986 Buick LeSabres.
   _ Steering column problems in 1988 F150 Ford pickup trucks.
   _ Steering damper separation problems in 1988 Chevrolet Blazer
and GMC Jimmy trucks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
